<DOCNO> AP881221-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0111EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EPA-Steel     12-21 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EPA-Steel,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Says It Can't Stop Plant From Violating Consent Decree</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency says it is
powerless to stop Sharon Steel Corp. from operating a coke
production plant without required anti-pollution controls.
   ``We don't have EPA troops. We can't go out there and surround
the place,'' said Lee Blackburn of EPA's regional office in
Philadelphia.
   Blackburn said in interviews this week that Sharon Steel is
risking possible fines by operating its Monessen, Pa., plant without
anti-sulfur emission controls that are required by a federal court
consent decree.
   Each day the plant continues to run without the controls exposes
it to possible fines of up to $50,000 _ a maximum of $25,000 per day
for each of two operating coke oven batteries, Blackburn said.
   Sharon was the nation's 12th largest steel producer before it
filed for reorganization under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws
in April 1987. It now ranks No. 17.
   The Monessen plant is seen as a key to helping the company get
back on its feet by providing a reliable source of coke for the
company's steelmaking operations in Farrell, 75 miles northwest of
Pittsburgh. Coke is a raw material of steel.
   The coke plant began operating after the Pennsylvania Department
of Environmental Resources granted a temporary operating permit in
the middle of last month.
   The permit and an air quality assurance plan were approved by the
state on Nov. 14, even though a required inspection of the plant had
not yet taken place. The inspection by state and EPA officials
occurred four days later.
   The inspection was ``to make sure all the equipment is there. It
was a procedural thing. The plant had already been in operation
before,'' said Susan Woods, a spokeswoman for the Pennsylvania
Department of Environmental Resources.
   The EPA contends that the plant should not have begun operating
without the pollution equipment, regardless of what the state agency
did.
</TEXT>
