<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Rabies     12-21 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Rabies,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shanghai Issues Rabies Alert, Instructs Owners To Kill Dogs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shanghai, China's largest city, has issued its
first rabies alert in 30 years and instructed people to kill their
dogs, an official newspaper reported today.
   More than a dozen people have contracted rabies after being
bitten by dogs this year, the China Daily quoted Zhao Chonghe,
director of Shanghai's division of health and epidemic prevention,
as saying.
   He said none of the victims has died.
   The report said 100 people died of rabies in Shanghai in 1950,
but the city of 12 million has had no reported cases since 1958.
   Shanghai, like Beijing and other Chinese cities, prohibits the
keeping of dogs as pets, and there are only about 500 legally
registered dogs in the city for use by police and for other special
purposes, the daily said.
   However, it said there is a large underground market for dogs,
with one market selling 100 dogs a day, and that 2,000 people have
been injured by dogs in Shanghai this year.
   Zhao was quoted as saying authorities have issued a public alert
on the rabies threat and instructed owners to kill their dogs. The
dogs of those people who do not obey the instructions will be
confiscated, he said.
</TEXT>
