<DOCNO> AP881221-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0113EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NavyBias     12-21 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Navy Bias,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Navy Still Discriminates Against Minorities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has made gains against racial bias but
it still discriminates against blacks and other minorities in
recruitment and other areas, an internal Navy report says.
   ``Minorities are succeeding in the Navy. But in spite of this
progress and the realization of significant growth in career
opportunity, shortfalls continue for minorities in accessions,
promotions, advancements and distribution,'' the report said.
   ``The Navy must strongly reinforce its continuing commitment to
equal opportunity programs and efforts,'' the report said. ``Much
remains to be done.''
   The inch-thick report, which summarizes a special internal
analysis of Navy personnel policies ordered by the chief of naval
operations, was released earlier this week. The study was performed
by a naval group of 24 men and women and offers some candid advice
to Adm. Carlisle A.H. Trost, the chief of naval operations.
   The panel recommended 75 different changes or new initiatives to
Trost, and the Navy's top admiral has accepted all 75, the service
said Tuesday.
   The study group reported that black and Hispanic sailors and
officers are more likely to receive lower marks on their evaluation
reports; that ``a majority'' of sailors say they have ``heard racial
jokes or slurs at their commands,'' and that the Navy has not done
enough to educate officers on their responsibility to promote racial
equality.
   The Navy also has failed to direct its recruiting advertisements
to minority neighborhoods and to direct minorities into the
technical specialities or ratings where they have the best shot at
promotion, the group found.
   The group recommended more funds for recruiting minority
officers, and new initiatives at Navy training centers around the
country to guide minorities into technical ratings.
   And it also concluded that all officers on the way to executive
officer or commanding officer assignments ``receive training
covering the Navy's equal opportunity goals, significant minority
issues, results of the fitness report studies, promotion and
screening board results and the CNO's annual equal opportunity
report.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
