<HEAD>Suspected Embezzler Brought Back Home To Face Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment adviser who disappeared last August
after allegedly taking more than $20 million of his clients' money
was extradited back here Tuesday night to face fraud and
embezzlement charges.
   Henry Gherman, 52, vanished from South Florida days before about
50 of his investors, including several doctors and nurses, received
a letter apologizing for the alleged theft.
   Gherman has been jailed since October in Tokyo, where he was
arrested after some American tourists recognized him in a Taiwan
hotel.
   Gherman arrived aboard a commercial flight at Miami International
Airport Tuesday, trying to hide his handcuffs with a trench coast as
he was escorted through the packed terminal by a dozen police
officers, FBI agents and U.S. Marshals.
   A Tokyo court had approved his extradition from Japan earlier
this month based on an Aug. 29 criminal complaint charging him with
two counts of fraud and five counts of embezzlement.
   He managed to share only a strained smile with family members
before being rushed off to jail pending a hearing Wednesday before
U.S. Magistrate Linnea Johnson in Miami federal court.
   ``I hurt for him,'' said Gherman's daughter, Shari Gherman Rance,
who refused to condemn her father despite his four-month
disappearance. ``He's still my father ... running off was wrong. He
should have stayed and faced the music, but he chose not to.''
   Gherman, whose North Miami Beach business handled investments and
pension funds for an assortment of Miami-area doctors, may have been
embezzling funds from clients for his own use since as early as
1978, said FBI spokesman Paul Miller, adding that an investigation
by the U.S. Attorney's office is continuing.
   ``We've located $2.2 million so far,'' Miller said. ``They're
still checking into further records.''
</TEXT>
