<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SerialSlayings     12-21 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Serial Slayings,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transient Arrested in Latest Killing Investigated by Task Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 46-year-old transient was arrested Tuesday in
connection with a woman's strangulation, the latest of 40 slayings
under investigation by a task force trying to determine if the
deaths are linked.
   Alan Michael Stevens was taken into custody Tuesday morning by
members of the Metropolitan Homicide Task Force in his van in San
Marcos, 38 miles north of San Diego, said San Diego sheriff's Sgt.
Liz Foster.
   Stevens, who was living in the van, was arrested for
investigation of the murder of Cynthia Lou McVey, 26, of Livermore,
Calif., whose nude body was found dumped Nov. 29 near a highway in
northern San Diego County.
   ``The task force will look at him to see if there's any
possibility he's linked to any other cases,'' said Foster.
   A connection between the deaths of the 40 slain women remains
under investigation, as does a possible connection to the 40 ``Green
River'' serial killings and eight disappearances in the Pacific
Northwest.
   There are similarities between the killings in San Diego and in
Washington and Oregon: Most of the victims were strangled and their
bodies dumped outside cities, and the killer or killers targeted
prostitutes or street people.
   But Lt. Dan Nolan of the Kings County Police Department in
Seattle, Wash., told the Times-Advocate of Escondido, Calif., that
there was apparently no connection between Stevens and the Green
River killings.
   Nolan said investigators were given Stevens' name some time ago
by San Diego investigators and do not believe he is the person they
are seeking.
   Foster said Stevens' arrest was the result of evidence obtained
after the discovery of McVey's body, but couldn't release details.
The sergeant did not know Stevens' occupation or hometown.
   McVey's death was caused by asphyxiation due to strangulation,
according to the coroner's report. She was a transient from the San
Francisco area and, according to her husband, she was a drug user.
</TEXT>
