<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     12-21 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEYMOUR, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This northeastern Wisconsin city is laying
claim to national fame as the birthplace of the hamburger, and it's
prepared for a beef with any city that thinks otherwise.
   ``We're going to establish Seymour as the national home of the
hamburger,'' vowed Thomas Duffey, a member of the Home of the
Hamburger Steering Committee.
   The group was formed about two years ago to look into promoting
the city as the 1885 birthplace of the hamburger.
   Committee members think potential challenges to the title could
come from St. Louis and New York City.
   ``We would welcome another city if they want to debate this,''
said Dick Tepp, committee chairman. ``It would only help us.''
   He said no other city could match Seymour's research of the
origins of the hamburger. The group even has asked the daughter of
the supposed hamburger-founder Charles R. Nagreen to help.
   Nagreen's sole survivor, Violet Gauerke, of Appleton, said her
father was 15 years old when he coined the name of the hamburger to
refer to the fried ground beef patties served at the Outagamie
County Fair in Seymour on Aug. 14, 1885.
   ``He was well known as Hamburger Charley,'' she said.
   Seymour expects to stake its claim as the hamburger capital next
August during its annual Seymour Celebration Days.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Christmas party spawned a little gorilla
warfare, but there were plenty of popcorn balls, cranberries and
hibiscus blossoms to go around when the Los Angeles Zoo held a
holiday party to toast their apes.
   It was definitely an adult party, though, said zoo spokeswoman
Lora LaMarca. ``They were not quick to share with their children,''
she said of the adult gorillas.
   The zoo staged the party for its 12 gorillas _ who range in age
from 18 months to 26 years and weigh 40 pounds to 450 pounds.
   The gorilla families were showered with gifts, including lengths
of fire hose, heavy duty tubs, rag dolls and burlap sacks, Ms.
LaMarca said.
   Tuesday's celebration for the apes was a first at the zoo, but it
was so successful, a party probably will be staged next year for the
orangutans and the year after for the chimpanzees, she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BASKING RIDGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jenna Hamburger's decision to answer
her first personal advertisement in a magazine fulfilled an almost
prophetic 10-year-old note from a high school chum who placed the ad.
   Ms. Hamburger and Marc Meltzer will be married in May.
   ``I think it was fate,'' she said. ``I really do believe that
things happen for a reason. ... I think that there was a definite
reason why the one ad I answered was his.
   In 1978, when they were seniors at Fair Lawn High School, Meltzer
wrote on the back of his wallet-size yearbook picture: ``Jenna,
let's make a pact to meet again in 10 years,'' and gave it to her.
They lost touch after graduation.
   In January, Meltzer's sister suggested he place a personal ad in
New York Magazine, which he said was the first and last ad he ever
placed. Ms. Hamburger wound up answering the ad.
   ``It's the weirdest thing that's ever happened. It certainly
gives you a reason to pause and ponder about fate,'' said Meltzer,
who lives in Basking Ridge. ``Jenna wasn't just someone who went to
my high school. She was someone I liked when I was in seventh
grade.''
   They had their first date earlier this year, and announced their
engagement in November.
   ``I think somebody, somehow was watching over us,'' said Ms.
Hamburger, of Clementon. ``There's some reason why we met the way we
did.''
</TEXT>
