<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Obit-Dodd     12-21 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Dodd,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writer and Ex-head of Publishing House Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUTNEY, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward H. Dodd Jr., a publisher and an author
of books about the South Seas, is dead at the age of 83.
   Dodd, who was the great-great-grandson of Moses Woodruff Dodd who
founded the publishing house of Dodd, Mead in 1839 in New York, died
at his home here on Monday.
   After graduating from Yale University in 1928, Dodd sailed a
76-foot schooner to the South Seas with four classmates and later
wrote about the adventure in ``Great Dipper to Southern Cross.''
   That journey was the beginning of his love affair with the
Pacific islands. He owned a house on one of the Society Islands, 200
miles from Tahiti, and divided his time between there and his home
in Vermont.
   Dodd wrote five books about Polynesia: ``Tales of Maui,''
``Polynesian Art,'' ``Polynesian Seafaring,'' ``Polynesia's Sacred
Isle,'' and ``The Rape of Tahiti.''
   Born in Manhattan, he went to work in the Dodd, Mead shipping
room in 1929, and the next year became a book salesman. He joined
the editorial staff in 1935 and became its head two years later. He
was president of the house from 1953 to 1957, when he semi-retired
to write full time.
   Dodd and his siblings approved the sale of Dodd, Mead in 1981 to
Thomas Nelson Inc., a Nashville-based religious publisher. Nelson
sold the company to private investors in 1984, and the firm is now
in liquidation.
   Dodd is survived by his three children. A memorial service will
be held Wednesday at 3 p.m. at River Valley Playhouse in Putney.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
