<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FamilyDiet     12-21 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Family Diet,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother and Son Lose 253 Pounds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 368-pound woman and her 338-pound son
shed a combined 253 pounds under a judge's threat to place the
teen-ager in a foster home unless he lost weight and stopped
skipping school.
   ``It's like a miracle, because I was near death,'' said Nancy
Gray, 48, who along with her 16-year-old son, Joseph, enrolled in a
diet program in upstate New York and in Fort Walton Beach, Fla.
   ``I was so close to 400 pounds it was ridiculous, and by staying
in bed I thought nobody would notice it,'' said Ms. Gray, who lost
102 pounds.
   Joseph Gray, who lost 151 pounds, said he frequently skipped
school to take care of his mother and because he was embarrassed
about his weight.
   ``When lunch time came around I was so hungry I would ask one of
my friends to get me a double lunch, and I would take it to the
bathroom and eat it there.''
   After a judge said Gray could be sent to a foster home, Ms. Gray
enlisted the care of diet expert Dick Gregory of Plymouth and in
June, the two joined 11 others under Gregory's care.
   ``They told us when we first got here that within seven days our
appetite would be gone,'' Gray said Monday. ``I had a lot of doubts
about that, because I ate a lot of food. Then came the third day,
and my appetite was totally gone.''
   Ms. Gray, whose weight complicated her respiratory problems, said
she has gone from using a wheelchair to walking for three hours
every day.
   The Grays, who live in Duxbury, are leaving Gregory's supervised
care six months early so that Joseph can return to school, but they
don't expect to revert to their old habits.
   ``I know it's going to be different,'' Gray said. ``I used to
just sit around and eat. Now I'm going to be going out, going to
school and doing all kinds of things.''
</TEXT>
