<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delinquent Mortgages Declining</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of Americans behind in their
mortgage payments fell in the third quarter of 1988 to the lowest
level in a year.
   The Mortgage Bankers Association of America said Tuesday that
4.73 percent of the payments on the 10.8 million mortgages surveyed
in the July-September period were at least 30 days late.
   It was the lowest rate since the third quarter of 1987, when 4.71
percent of the mortgage payers were behind. The delinquency rate was
4.9 percent in the second quarter of 1988.
   The foreclosure rate also edged down to 0.26 percent in the third
quarter, compared with 0.27 percent in the second quarter.
</TEXT>
