<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0221EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-US-SovietTrade     12-21 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet Trade,0556</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By JIM HEINTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By the end of a 13-day trade fair, Soviet
officials found the American business world a bit baffling, but the
more than $300 million worth of contracts signed at the exhibition
left them eager to learn more.
   And along with the contracts, they believe the fair made a great
advance in reducing misconceptions about Soviet goods.
   ``There was a myth that (U.S.) tariffs should not be reduced
because the Soviets didn't have anything worth selling. The myth is
dead,'' said Vladimir N. Cheklin, senior vice president of the
US-U.S.S.R. Trade and Economic Council.
   The contracts signed at the fair, which ended Tuesday, included
export-import and joint venture agreements for products ranging from
chemical equipment to sweatshirts, said Bagrat Arutyunov, foreign
exhibitions chief of the Soviet Chamber of Commerce. But the Soviets
admitted there were some segments of the market they had misjudged.
   They had expected Americans' love of home appliances to spark
strong interest in their high-fidelity equipment and proudly
displayed their best turntables. However, Cheklin said, they found
out that phonographs are losing ground to cassette and compact-disc
players.
   ``Now we know better where to concentrate our efforts,'' he said.
   And computer software teaching high school chemistry was designed
with the assumption that American students have a better grounding
in sciences than they actually do, said Alexy Botcharov of the
Soviet Academy of Sciences.
   The fair, which opened on the day Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev cut short his New York visit, was the first in which the
cost was borne entirely by the Soviet companies involved, rather
than relying in part on government support. It also was a departure
from previous exhibitions in terms of style.
   There was little political or nationalist propaganda _ just a few
flags, a slide show and a photograph of Gorbachev. Aside from some
displays of books and art objects, the products on display showed
few overt indications of where they were made; few trade names were
in the Cyrillic alphabet.
   Such Westernizing of Soviet products was seen as a paradox by
some people at the fair. On one hand, it may be necessary to
overcome Soviet goods' reputation of shoddiness, said Greg Rohn, of
Canada's Winchester Co., which distributes Soviet products there.
   But, he added, ``it seems that Russian products are starting to
become almost trendy'' as relations with the West improve.
   The Soviet Simvol cooperative hopes to capitalize on that aspect
with its line of T-shirts and sweatshirts emblazoned with Russian
slogans and the logo of Moscow State University. John Odoxta of
Sanctuary Music, a U.S. company involved in a joint venture with the
cooperative, said the shirts were popular souvenirs among fair
visitors.
   That was a heartening sign for future business, but current U.S.
tariffs plus manufacturing costs meant that selling the shirts at
U.S. market prices brought him a $20-per-shirt loss.
   Arutyunov said one of the most important aspects of the contracts
signed at the fair was the guidance that Western firms would be able
to provide in marketing and advertising because communism had long
eschewed such capitalist techniques.
   ``I can honestly say we're in the Stone Age in advertising,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
