<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0225EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PirateShip     12-21 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pirate Ship,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Station Owners Won't Give up the Ship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has again squelched a pirate rock 'n' roll
radio ship, saying the right to free speech does not include the
right to radio broadcasts without a license from the Federal
Communications Commission.
   But the engineer of the unlicensed station aboard the Sarah,
moored off New York, said Tuesday he hasn't given up the seagoing
enterprise even though it has broadcast for only two brief periods
since 1987.
   ``Everybody in the project is absolutely frustrated,'' Al Weiner,
former owner of the old fishing vessel, said Tuesday. ``We could go
on the air and not harm or create one single problem. It's just that
we've got a hysterical FCC.''
   Weiner had asked U.S. District Judge John J. McNaught to lift a
temporary restraining order stopping broadcasts. But McNaught ruled
that the FCC was right to shut the Sarah down.
   Weiner's attorney, Jeremiah Gutman of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, argued that the Sarah was a foreign-registered ship
in international waters and didn't come under the FCC's
jurisdiction. He also maintained that since the station, Radio New
York International, was broadcasting on an unassigned AM frequency,
the FCC was violating First Amendment rights to free speech.
   McNaught rejected those arguments, noting that the government
said numerous stations could be subject to interference if the Sarah
broadcast.
   ``The First Amendment does not guarantee anyone the right to
broadcast by radio,'' the judge wrote.
   The judge also said international agreements ban the
establishment of radio stations aboard ships outside national
territories.
   Weiner maintained that the Sarah is an international ship because
it is registered in Sealand, a self-proclaimed principality in the
North Sea off the coast of Britain. But prosecutors argued that
Britain does not recognize Sealand.
   ``The FCC's licensing requirements guarantee orderly use of the
airwaves. The defendants cannot hope to evade these requirements by
taking to the ocean waves,'' U.S. Attorney Frank McNamara said after
the judge's decision issued Dec. 13.
   Gutman said he is studying the ruling, and probably will file an
appeal.
   The Sarah has broadcast only twice, from more than three miles
off shore. In July 1987, Radio New York International operated off
Long Island for about four days before agents of the FCC and the
Coast Guard boarded the ship and stopped broadcasts.
   This fall, the Sarah was registered as a Maine pleasure boat and
headed back to the waters off Long Island, broadcasting for another
four days before the temporary restraining order was issued.
   Weiner has since sold the ship to a British company, but has a
five-year option to repurchase.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
