<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     12-21 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Against Yen, Nikkei Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell Wednesday against the Japanese
yen, while share prices advanced on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 124.22 yen, down 0.48 yen from Tuesday's
close of 124.70 yen. Despite its higher opening at 125.48 yen, the
currency fell sharply while moving in a range of 124.10 to 125.50
yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
97.86 points the previous day, added another 130.25 points, or 0.44
percent, closing at 29,698.19.
   The U.S. currency's firmness in early Tokyo trading followed
similar trends in overseas markets, dealers said.
   But the dollar fell quickly as speculative investors and trading
companies began selling the currency to cash in gains made when the
dollar neared the mid 125-yen level, said one dealer with Bank of
Tokyo. Other investors were buying the dollar when it fell back to
around 124.50 yen, the dealer said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The dollar's strength in early trading and prospects for lower
Japanese interest rates contributed to the rise in the Nikkei, said
an analyst with Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   ``Investors are interested in export- and real estate-related
issues because of the higher dollar,'' he said, speaking on
condition of anonymity. Trading otherwise was inactive because of
the year end, the analyst said.
</TEXT>
