<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--HorsePunched     12-21 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Horse Punched,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Award to Woman Whose Horse Was Punched Partially Overturned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court partially overturned a
damage award to a woman who claimed her horse became shy when a man
punched it in the jaw.
   Linda Van Eaton of Kansas City had been awarded $8,500 after her
appaloosa ``Velvet'' was punched by Roland Thon. The Missouri Court
of Appeals on Tuesday ruled that $5,100 for mental distress was
improper because there was no expert testimony.
   Ms. Van Eaton also was awarded damages for her claims of assault
and property damages.
   Thon said he punched the horse in self-defense when it charged
him as Ms. Van Eaton rode along a road near his home.
   Besides punching the horse, Thon yelled at Ms. Van Eaton and
threw gravel at her, according to court papers.
   Ms. Van Eaton, who had sought $99,000, said the horse became shy
after it was punched and would buck, fidget or bolt when people
approached.
