<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Ford-PUSH     12-21 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford-PUSH,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Calls For More Minority Hiring, Cites Ford As an Example</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. and Operation PUSH culminated six
years of negotiations by signing an agreement to promote ``mutual
affirmative action goals'' that will target $541 million to minority
businesses next year.
   Peter J. Pestillo, vice president of employee and external
affairs for Ford, said Tuesday's agreement formalizes a process that
began in 1982.
   ``Ford has been working hard to help open doors for minorities,''
Pestillo said. ``Today we are pledging to continue to seek
improvements for blacks in all functional areas of the company.''
   While the signed agreement itself does not specify amounts that
Ford will direct to minority businesses, it pledges to ``set
quantifiable benchmarks wherever feasible, and ... measure progress
in all affected areas.''
   Ford has ``set the pace'' for hiring, promoting and doing
business with minority companies, the Rev. Jesse Jackson, the
founder of Operation PUSH, said Tuesday at a joint news conference
to announce the agreement.
   ``Multiply it times Forbes 500 and you would have a radical
assault on poverty, illness, disease, despair in this country,'' he
said.
   The agreement commits Ford and Operation PUSH to a ``continuing,
cooperative arrangement ... with the goal of achieving mutual
affirmative action goals.''
   Operation PUSH _ People United to Serve Humanity _ is aimed at
improving economic opportunities for minorities.
   Blacks sold $240 million worth of goods and services to Ford in
1987, a 100 percent increase over 1985, the automaker said.
   Goods and services bought from all minorities last year totaled
$341 million. That figure increased to $421 million this year, and
Ford said it has a goal of buying $541 million worth of goods and
services from minority suppliers in 1989.
   PUSH officials said the number of the Ford dealerships owned by
blacks increased from 20 in 1982 to 245 this year _ a total more
than that of the other U.S. automakers combined. They said the
company hopes to have 75 more black-owned dealerships by the end of
next year.
   Pestillo also said blacks occupy 3 percent of the management jobs
at Ford, an increase of 50 percent since 1982. He said the company
is doing more business with companies owned by blacks to purchase
such things as supplies, insurance and advertising.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
