<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0343EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     12-21 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Finishes Lower Against Yen, Shares Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar reversed direction and finished
lower against the Japanese yen today, while share prices rose
sharply on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar finished at 124.22 yen, down 0.48 yen from Tuesday's
close of 124.70 yen. It opened at 125.48 yen but then fell sharply,
moving in a wide range between 124.10 and 125.50 yen.
   The currency's higher opening in Tokyo after a 0.68-yen gain on
Tuesday was attributed to similar trends on overseas markets. But at
the higher rates, speculators and trading companies began selling
dollars, dealers said.
   Daiwa Bank's Takamasa Yamasaki said concerted dollar-selling by
speculative dealers and investment banks resulted in the currency's
sharp drop from the mid-125-yen level in early trading.
   ``But the majority of traders were sitting on the sidelines since
the Christmas holidays are approaching on overseas markets,'' he
said.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 97.86-point
gainer Tuesday, added another 130.25 points, or 0.44 percent,
closing at 29,689.19. The index gained 41.02 points in the morning
session and rose sharply in the afternoon.
   Dealers said stock investors were in a cautious mood because of
the fluctuation of the dollar-yen rate in the currency market.
   ``Market players were wondering why the dollar was so high this
morning, but as it began falling, participants' uncertainties were
erased, which helped the Nikkei's rise,'' said a dealer with a major
securities firm in Tokyo.
   The Nikkei's afternoon gain also resulted from some foreign
securities firms aggressively buying in the spot market and selling
future issues priced higher in the SIMEX market to make profits, he
said. SIMEX is a futures market in Singapore, where the Nikkei's 225
issues are listed. Wednesday was SIMEX's settlement day for December
trading.
</TEXT>
