<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Crack,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tiny Crack Found in Shuttle Pump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers inspecting space shuttle
Atlantis have found a tiny crack on a bearing part in one of the
shuttle's high-pressure liquid-oxygen pumps, officials said.
   The crack was found Sunday on a pump in main engine No. 3 during
normal inspections at the Kennedy Space Center, said Conrad Nagel,
who is in charge of preparing Atlantis for launch.
   Nagel said officials already had planned to replace the pumps,
which send liquid oxygen to the main engines.
   The pumps will be shipped to the manufacturer, Rockwell
International's Rocketdyne division in California, to determine the
cause of the crack.
   Nagel said Tuesday it was too early to say how the crack would
affect future launches. Atlantis' next launch is scheduled for late
April.
   Atlantis completed a secret four-day military mission on Dec. 6.
</TEXT>
