<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StrandedWoman     12-21 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stranded Woman,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Help Stranded Woman Reach Bedside of Injured Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stranded woman was able to return home to her
injured husband after a police officer called on his colleagues for
help and they chipped in to pay for her bus ticket to South Carolina.
   ``It's people like all of you that make life every day worth it!
Have a Merry Christmas! And thanks again!,'' Samantha Reed wrote in
a tear-stained letter she gave an officer before boarding the bus
recently.
   Lt. Mike Hibbs, who was working off-duty at the Greyhound bus
station, was the first to notice Mrs. Reed. ``She looked like she
had a problem,'' he said.
   Mrs. Reed told police she was en route to Nevada to visit her
mother, who has cancer, when she learned that her husband had been
seriously injured in an automobile accident back home in
Spartansburg, S.C.
   But even after she turned in the unused portion of her ticket to
Nevada, Mrs. Reed did not have the $81 she needed to return to South
Carolina. Hibbs called local charities, but couldn't find one open
on the weekend.
   Sgt. Drew Roberts took over when he relieved Hibbs.
   ``She was desperate and I was desperate,'' Roberts said.
   Roberts called his colleagues at the traffic division and asked
that they donate $1 each to help the woman get home. A dispatcher
sent Roberts' message to patrol officers via the police mobile
computer system.
   ``It just ballooned and within minutes there were police cars
parked up and down the road around the bus station,'' Roberts said.
``I got a lot of money real fast. Even off-duty officers in their
personal cars were coming by.''
   Roberts ended up with $138.
   ``The whole thing gave me a lump in my throat,'' Roberts said.
   Mrs. Reed cried when he gave her the money, and offered to repay
the officers, Roberts said. Before she boarded the bus, Mrs. Reed
hugged Roberts and handed him the letter thanking the officers ``for
providing me with the money to take me back home to be with the one
who needs me most.''
</TEXT>
