<HEAD>Boston Mayor Helps Douse Burning Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Raymond L. Flynn tried to douse a burning car
with a fire extinguisher, then directed traffic at a busy downtown
intersection when firefighters arrived to finish the job.
   Flynn and his wife, Catherine, were leaving a bookstore around
noon Tuesday after they had made a donation to The Boston Globe's
Santa Fund when he saw the burning car.
   Flynn grabbed the extinguisher from a merchant, sprayed the car
until the extinguisher was empty, then directed traffic to make room
for fire trucks.
   ``Where did he come from?'' asked Sarah Weatherwax, who sells
items from a pushcart across the street. ``He always seems to show
up at these things.''
   ``People may think I did this for publicity,'' Flynn said later.
   In 1987, Flynn rescued a handicapped person from a burning
building, and intervened in a hostage crisis in Roxbury. His wife
said she once saw him pull three people from a burning car.
