<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Soviet     12-21 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Soviet,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan, Soviet Union Agree To Resume Talks On WWII Peace Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan and the Soviet Union today agreed to resume
talks on a peace treaty formally ending World War II, despite their
failure to overcome a territorial dispute that has chilled relations
for decades.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze said the two sides
had also agreed to prepare for a summit.
   During the last summit meeting in October 1973, peace treaty
negotiations stalled on a 43-year-old dispute over a group of
Soviet-held islands that Tokyo wants returned to Japan.
   Tokyo and Moscow have rival claims to the Kuril islands off
northern Japan, from which 17,000 Japanese residents were ousted by
the Soviets at the end of World War II. Japan asserts a long
historical right to the islands, which now are fortified by 10,000
Soviet troops.
   Shevardnadze gave an upbeat assessment of his two days of
meetings with his Japanese counterpart Sousuke Uno before flying on
to Manila today, becoming the highest-ranking Soviet official to
visit the Philippines since the two countries established diplomatic
relations in 1976.
   ``We have attained a degree of mutual understanding that allows
us to speak of a new chapter in Japan-Soviet relations,'' said
Shevardnadze, speaking Russian that was translated into English.
   ``An important step forward ... has been made that opens up good
prospects for Soviet-Japanese political dialogue and for a practical
development of our relations,'' the Soviet envoy said.
   Later, however, Uno told a news conference ``there can be no
peace treaty without a resolution of the territorial issue.''
   After Shevardnadze's departure, the two nations released a
nine-page joint communique that made no direct reference to the
territorial dispute but vaguely mentions ``difficulties existing in
their bilateral relations.''
   Citing the agreement on further meetings leading to a possible
summit between Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita, Shevardnadze said the talks had won ``a
victory for reason, for balance of interests, and for a realistic
policy.''
   He said he would meet Uno in Paris next month while attending a
conference on chemical weapons, and that Uno would visit Moscow in
the spring.
   Japan has repeatedly invited Gorbachev to visit this country, but
no date emerged from Shevardnadze's visit.
   Asked about the territorial issue, Shevardnadze said the two
sides had ``agreed to consider the historical and political aspects
related to removal of difficulties pending in bilateral relations.''
   He did not directly mention the islands, but did say the Soviets
had agreed on humanitarian grounds to consider ``increasing in 1989
the number of locations where Japanese can visit burial grounds of
their relatives on Soviet territory.''
   Shevardnadze also said no concrete agreements had been reached on
economic matters, ``but we hope to promote economic cooperation.''
   He said the tentative agenda for a Japan-Soviet summit would
include agreements on protecting investments, principles of economic
cooperation and establishment of banking offices, as well as treaty
issues and other matters.
   In 1987, two-way trade between Tokyo and Moscow totaled $4.9
billion and accounted for just 1.8 percent of Japan's total trade.
It is expected to climb slightly to $4.98 billion this year.
   Shevardnadze, who will visit North Korea after the Philippines,
said Moscow had established trade and other unofficial relations
with South Korea but would not establish governmental relations with
Seoul, an action that would further isolate its ally North Korea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
