<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NukePlants     12-21 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuke Plants,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Department to Negotiate Legally Binding Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Department of Energy decision to
negotiate a legally binding agreement with Ohio to clean up a
federal uranium refinery does not obligate the agency to do the same
elsewhere, a spokesman said.
   The Energy Department decided Tuesday to accept a consent decree
that would enforce a $50 million federal agreement made Nov. 22 to
clean up the Portsmouth Gaseous Diffusion Plant in Piketon, said
spokesman Doug Elmets in Washington.
   A day earlier, news reports indicating the Energy Department was
backing away from a consent decree prompted state Attorney General
Anthony Celebrezze to insist that Ohio had a commitment that federal
officials should honor.
   Elmets said the department reached its decision after discussions
with Ohio officials and consultations with the Justice Department
and the Energy Department's operations office in Oak Ridge, Tenn.
   ``This decision was based on the same factors that influenced our
decision on two earlier consent decrees in regard to Fernald
litigation,'' Elmets read from a statement.
   He was referring to the announcement earlier this month of a
court-approved agreement that gave Ohio authority to regulate the
Energy Department's $1 billion cleanup of the Feed Materials
Production Center, a weapons-grade uranium processing plant in
Fernald, 20 miles northwest of Cincinnati.
   At that plant, company documents released Tuesday revealed that
the former operator of Fernald mistakenly donated a ``slightly
contaminated'' dump truck to a local school board in 1950.
   When officials at National Lead of Ohio realized the mistake,
they decided not to alert the school board because they didn't think
the contamination level posed a health threat, the documents
indicate. The whereabouts of the truck today is unknown.
   The documents were released to the U.S. House Subcommittee on
Transportation, Tourism and Hazardous Materials, which is
investigating radioactive pollution at such plants for more than
three decades.
   Elmets said the Energy Department's latest decision on the
Piketon cleanup does not mean the government will pursue similar
agreements with other states that claim federal nuclear
installations have polluted the environment.
   ``The only precedential value to this decision is that we will
continue to analyze lawsuits of this kind on a case-by-case basis,
and if any state makes a similarly attractive and fair settlement,
we will give it the same serious consideration. Otherwise we will
litigate,'' Elmets said.
   Ohio officials said they were satisified with the department's
decision.
   ``I'm happy we're back at the negotiating table and are not going
to waste our efforts on legal maneuvering,'' Celebrezze said, adding
that he would settle only for a consent decree because ``I want
something that's enforceable in court. I'll settle for nothing
less.''
   The Piketon plant processes uranium for fuel for commercial
nuclear power reactors. It generates toxic wastes such as
polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs, solvents and metals, as well as
radioactive materials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881221-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0514EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Quebec     12-21 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quebec,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Cabinet Ministers Resign Over French-Language Row</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Quebec Cabinet ministers have resigned over
their premier's defiance of a Supreme Court ruling that the
predominantly French-speaking province allow the posting of signs in
English.
   The country's highest court said last week that Quebec may make
sure that French predominates on outdoor signs but barred the
province from preventing the use of other languages.
   Robert Bourassa, the provincial premier, angered both English
speakers and francophone militants on Sunday with what he termed a
compromise: French must remain the only language on outdoor signs
but other languages can be used indoors so long as French
predominates.
   Environment Minister Clifford Lincoln, one of four English
speakers in Bourassa's Cabinet, resigned Tuesday and said he
considered the so-called compromise a violation of individual rights.
   ``In my beliefs, rights are rights are rights. There are no
partial rights. There are no indoor-outdoor rights,'' he said.
   Two of the other English speakers _ Public Security Minister
Herbert Marx and Communications Minister Richard French _ quit later
Tuesday.
   Bourassa based his decision on a clause put into the constitution
by Western provinces as a protection against federal power that
allows provinces or the national government to override a court
decision.
   The resumption of linguistic divisiveness in Canada followed four
years of general calm that made possible the 1987 Meech Lake
constitutional agreement recognizing Quebec as a ``distinct
society.''
   Only eight of the 10 provinces have ratified the accord, named
for the place in Quebec where it was signed. New Brunswick and
Quebec have not.
   Premier Gary Filmon of Manitoba described the Quebec decision as
a ``national tragedy'' and called for a national conference of
provincial leaders to persuade the French-speaking province to
accept the court decision.
   Which language can be used on signs is a volatile and symbolic
issue Quebec's French speakers _ 81 percent of the population _
consider essential to preserving their linguistic and cultural
heritage.
   Bourassa's plan prohibits languages other than French on signs
both outdoors and in such places as shopping malls and interiors of
public transportation facilities.
   A crowd of 10,000 attended a rally Sunday in Montreal demanding
no changes in the language law, which was passed in 1977 by the
separatist Parti Quebecois government.
   Power in the province shifted from the English-speaking minority
to the French speakers in the 1970s. Separatist sentiment abated
after the language law was passed and Quebec's voters rejected
sovereignty in a 1980 referendum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
