<BYLINE>Teen-Ager to Drop Assault Charges Against Rep. Kennedy
^By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager says he will drop the assault and
battery charges he filed against Rep. Joseph Kennedy II after the
congressman allegedly shoved him after a near traffic accident.
   Victor H. Avila, 17, said Kennedy, D-Mass., grabbed his sweater
and pushed him against his car following the incident Tuesday. Avila
said he was unhurt.
   ``I did not hit him but I made myself very clear,'' Kennedy, 36,
told WBZ-TV on Tuesday night, adding that Avila was speeding. ``The
fact is that people drive too fast in these city neighborhoods.''
   Avila said he would go to Brighton District Court today to drop
the charges because Kennedy had come to his home Tuesday evening to
apologize.
   Jim Mahoney, a spokesman for Kennedy, said Kennedy had not
apologized but had met with Avila and his father ``just to clarify
things.''
   Mahoney said Avila's car forced the congressman off the road.
   ``Joe gave a very stern reprimand to the young man driving the
other vehicle and then later in the day, the young man and his
father came over to Joe's house about 4 or 5 p.m. where they
discussed the whole incident,'' Mahoney said.
   According to the complaint Avila filed with Boston police on
Tuesday, Avila was driving up a hill and passed Kennedy's car, which
was traveling in the opposite direction, a police spokesman said.
Avila and Kennedy each veered off the road to avoid a collision, the
complaint said.
   ``We had a little misunderstanding, a little feud, and tempers
were really mad, both of us,'' Avila said. ``It's all over.''
</TEXT>
