<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Jail     12-21 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Jail,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Congressman Allowed to Stay Out Of Prison Pending Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The start of former Rep. Mario Biaggi's
eight-year prison term was delayed by an appellate court pending his
appeal of his Wedtech racketeering conviction.
   ``We're very happy,'' said James LaRossa, Biaggi's attorney,
after Tuesday's decision by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
Biaggi, who will remain free on bail, did not attend the hearing.
   A three-judge panel ruled unanimously in favor of Biaggi, who had
been scheduled to start his sentence on Jan. 9. The 10-term
Democratic congressman was forced to resign from the House of
Representatives on Aug. 5 following his conviction.
   ``There are substantial questions which affect (Biaggi) alone,''
said Judge Wilfred Feinberg, the chief judge of the 2nd Circuit,
after the panel heard arguments and briefly recessed.
   Biaggi was convicted with ex-Bronx Borough President Stanley
Simon, Wedtech Corp. founder John Mariotta and two other people of
turning the South Bronx military contractor into a racketeering
enterprise for their personal gain. Simon and Mariotta still face a
Jan. 9 surrender date.
   Convicted of lesser charges stemming from the scandal was
Biaggi's son Richard, 39, who received a two-year prison term
despite a tearful plea from his father asking the trial judge for
mercy.
   The elder Biaggi, who represented the Bronx, was convicted of 15
counts of racketeering, conspiracy, extortion and receiving bribes
for squeezing $1.8 million in stocks and cash from Wedtech.
   LaRossa said the main issue in the appeal concerns U.S. District
Judge Constance Baker Motley's refusal to allow certain testimony by
Richard Biaggi's wife, Toni, about a conversation in which she and
Richard agreed to give the elder Biaggi a percentage of Wedtech
stock.
   According to LaRossa, Toni Biaggi had quoted her father-in-law as
saying he would only take the stock if it was deemed to be within
congressional ethical guidelines.
   The eight-year term for Biaggi is to run concurrently with the
2{-year sentence imposed following his November 1987 conviction for
taking an illegal gratuity and obstruction of justice in a case
involving ex-Brooklyn Democratic boss Meade Esposito.
</TEXT>
