<HEAD>Dollar Little Changed, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was little changed in light European
trading early today. Gold prices were mixed.
   Dealers said they expected sustained corporate demand to support
the dollar through the end of the year, but they said fears of
central bank intervention could impede the dollar's advance.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.48 Japanese yen to a closing 124.22 yen. Later, in
London, it edged back up to 124.60 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.7750 West German marks, unchanged
   _1.4990 Swiss francs, down from 1.4995
   _6.0635 French francs, down from 6.0675
   _1.9995 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0080
   _1,304.20 Italian lire, down from 1,309.32
   _1.1995 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2000
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8035 from $1.8070 late
Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $414.40 a troy ounce, up
from $414.25 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $413.85.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $414, up from $413.50 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 27 cents to close at a bid
$415.94.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $6.13 a troy
ounce, down from $6.11 bid late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
