<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CentralAmerica-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0433 12-21 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Central America-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0433,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precedes ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Central American, Caribbean Nations Keen To Help
on Drugs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs, Rangel and Gilman comments today; picks
up
5th graf pvs, In addition</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressmen just returned from Central American
and Caribbean countries said today the incoming Bush administration
should move quickly to take advantage of a ``new spirit of
cooperation'' in the region to fight drug trafficking.
   Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., chairman of the House Select
Committee on Narcotics, said a 12-day trip to 10 nations was
highlighted by a ``breakthrough'' in Cuba, where President Fidel
Castro offered to work in the effort. The 10-member congressional
delegation returned Tuesday.
   Rangel, interviewed on NBC-TV's ``Today'', said that political
leaders in the region now see drug trafficking ``as a threat to
their national security, and they're asking their friends in the
United States to become partners in fighting against this drug
epidemic.
   ``There is an entirely different attitude we've seen in the
leadership of these countries,'' he said.
   Rangel said Castro promised to provide the United States with
intelligence on potential drug planes flying over Cuba, even if the
aircraft do not land on that island country.
   Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., also interviewed by NBC, said the
next step would be a summit meeting of regional leaders, which was
called for in a massive anti-drug bill Congress passed earlier this
year.
   ``We found there is a willingness and a desire to work
cooperatively,'' Gilman said.
   Rangel said congressmen would meet with members of the new Bush
administration to help coordinate an anti-drug policy.
   ``We're meeting, Republicans and Democrats, asking for a meeting
with President Bush, the attorney general, and the members of the
Cabinet, to take advantage of this new spirit of cooperation,'' he
said.
   In addition to Cuba, the congressional delegation visited Mexico,
Belize, Jamaica, the Dominican Republican, Guyana, Trinidad and
Tobago, meeting with heads of state at every stop.
   ``If there is a common thread running through what we have
learned at our various stops, it is that there is a growing concern
on the part of the various governments to come up with effective
measures to fight the drug problem,'' said Rangel, chairman of the
House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control.
   The 1988 anti-drug abuse legislation urges the assistant
secretary of state for international narcotics matters to seek
establishment of a regional anti-narcotics center in the Caribbean.
   ``Such a center would go a long way in helping to more
effectively combat narcotics trafficking and drug abuse in the
region,'' said Gilman.
   Rangel said the countries visited were willing to attend a
hemispheric summit on drug trafficking and narcotics abuse, but
there was no indication when such a summit might take place.
   The delegation also made these points:
   _Mexico's newly installed President Carlos Salinas de Gortari
promised to ``make life miserable for the drug traffickers,'' Rangel
said.
   _Officials in Belize revealed that crack cocaine had been
introduced into the country.
   _Trinidad and Tobago authorities said they wanted to launch a
national anti-drug initiative, while officials in Guyana and the
Dominican Republic pointed out that those countries recently passed
anti-drug legislation.
   Rangel and Rep. Guy Vander Jagt, R-Mich., said they hoped the
delegation could discuss their findings with President-elect Bush,
but there was no scheduled meeting yet.
   In addition to Rangel, Gilman and Vander Jagt, the other members
of the delegation were Reps. Frank J. Guarini, D-N.J., William J.
Hughes, D-N.J., Solomon P. Ortiz, D-Texas; George W. Crockett Jr.,
D-Mich.; Kweisi Mfume, D-Md.; and Delegates Walter E. Fauntroy,
D-District of Columbia, and Ron de Lugo, D-Virgin Islands.
</TEXT>
