<DOCNO> AP881221-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0901EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     12-21 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Losing Candidate Claims Government Fraud In Presidential Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main opposition candidate for
president said today she lost the election because of widespread
fraud by the governing party.
   The candidate, former Prime Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike, vowed
to challenge the results of Monday's contest.
   ``The election results are something I cannot accept,'' she told
reporters at her Colombo home. ``There was a number of violations of
election law.''
   Mrs. Bandaranaike lost to Prime Minister Ranasinghe Premadasa by
50.9 percent to 44.9 percent, according to election results
announced by the government. A third candidate finished well back.
   Mrs. Bandaranaike said her lawyers told her there was enough
evidence to have the election result voided and said that her party
would take the case to the Supreme Court.
   She accused her opponents of taking ballot boxes to police
stations instead of official counting centers and stuffing them with
ballots.
   During the news conference, she waved about 700 blank ballots she
claimed were found outside a police station.
   Ranjan Wijeratne, chairman of the governing United National
Party, dismissed the charges. ``The people have given a verdict.
Everybody must bow down to the collective decision of the people,''
he said.
   A 10-member election observer group from countries in the region
issued a report today saying ``the electoral process, even though it
may have been flawed ... did in fact take its course, should be
viewed positively.''
   Mrs. Bandaranaike said the Central Committee of her Sri Lanka
Freedom Party would decide whether to call for demonstrations
against the election result.
   Activity in the capital of Colombo appeared returning to normal
today after tension caused by ethnic extremists who waged a campaign
of intimidation to disrupt the election.
   Commuter train service and other forms of public transportation
that ran sporadically the past month were normal in the morning.
   The violence that has plagued this strife-torn Indian Ocean
island had not stopped, however.
   Tamil Tigers, an ethnic insurgency seeking independence for
minority Tamils, blew up a truck this morning with remote-controlled
explosives, killing four special task force policemen in Pullumalai,
20 miles southwest of the eastern port of Batticoloa, the military
said.
   The current cycle of violence in Sri Lanka, formerly a popular
tourist resort, dates from 1983, when Tamils began an uprising
against the majority Sinhalese. Nearly 10,000 people have been
killed on this island of 16 million people.
   Under a 1987 pact with New Delhi, 47,000 Indian troops are
deployed in northeastern Sri Lanka to suppress the rebellion. In
return, the government has granted the Tamils some autonomy.
   The Sinhalese extremist People's Liberation Front that vehemently
opposes the government, in part because of the pact, killed about
650 people during the campaign, officials claim.
   Premadasa, in a nationally televised address immediately after
being declared the winner, urged ethnic subersives to stop fighting
and join the political process.
   ``I have an appeal to make to those who have still to join the
democratic process,'' he said. ``Your participation will enable us
to eradicate fear and poverty with greater speed.''
   He said they had a chance to participate in Feb. 15 parliamentary
elections called by outgoing President Junius R. Jayewardene.
</TEXT>
