<DOCNO> AP881221-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0906EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DesperatePriest     12-21 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Desperate Priest,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jobs Center Director Who Gained Public Sympathy Has Questionable
Past</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jobs-center director who claimed that he was
a priest and generated public sympathy after he offered to sell
valuable lithographs to pay the center's bills admits he faked some
of his credentials.
   The man, John DaeCheck, also acknowledged he has had some brushes
with authorities, including an investigation of his publishing
company by the U.S. Postal Service and the state attorney general.
   But DaeCheck, 42, who also claimed to have led a congregation,
said he remains committed to helping the unemployed through his
non-profit New Times Service Center in suburban Glassport.
   Neal Holmes, owner of Allied Security of Pittsburgh, said Monday
he dropped plans to organize business people interested in giving at
least $10,000 to the center because of questions about DaeCheck's
credentials.
   In addition, Jack Katona, manager of Union National Bank in
Glassport, said Tuesday he would close the account DaeCheck opened
Monday with $500 he received from the sale of a lithograph.
   Katona initially agreed to DaeCheck's request that the bank
manager oversee all transactions in the account, but decided to
sever any connections with DaeCheck.
   DaeCheck generated sympathy when he placed a classified ad to
sell two 19th-century lithographs, saying he needed the money to pay
an overdue phone bill at the center. Dozens of people offered to buy
the lithographs or contribute to the center.
   DaeCheck had told The Associated Press he was the pastor of an
independent Russian Orthodox Church called St. Paul's in Washington,
Pa., and said the job center was a mission of the church.
   But when pressed for details Monday, DaeCheck said he doesn't
have a congregation or conduct services. He further explained that
St. Paul's Church is actually St. Paul's Mission, part of All-Faith
Church Mission Inc. in Washington, founded by the Revs. Harry and
Helen Harrington.
   The Harringtons said they ordained DaeCheck and hundreds of other
people based on the applicants' knowledge of the Bible and their
belief in God.
   The couple said their non-denominational church is licensed by a
Bible college, but neither could remember which college.
   DaeCheck said he briefly attended but did not graduate from
Savanarolo Theological Seminary in Scranton. He said he was ordained
in Washington, D.C., in 1981 by Bishop James Miller of the Orthodox
Church of America. That church was based in Anderson, S.C., and is
separate from the more commonly known Orthodox Church in America,
DaeCheck said.
   But the rector of the Scranton seminary, the Very Rev. Edward
Brzostowski, said Monday he had no records of DaeCheck's attendance.
   Directory assistance in Anderson, S.C., had no listing for the
church or Miller.
   Caren Mariani, a deputy state attorney general, said DaeCheck's
publishing company failed to publish manuscripts, make refunds on
time or register itself as a business with the state.
   In June 1985, DaeCheck agreed to reimburse seven authors a total
of $5,354, to be paid over a 20-month period. The agreement does not
constitute an admission of guilt, Mariani said. Records indicate
DaeCheck has not completed the payments.
   The postal service investigated DaeCheck but never charged him
with any crime, said Postal Inspector Bruce Stutzman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
