<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Transition-Search 1stLd-Writethru a0431 12-21 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Transition-Search, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0431,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Staff Consulting with Executive `Headhunters'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `When he,' to CORRECT inauguration date to
Jan. 20.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush's transition aides are
soliciting advice from professional ``headhunters'' in determining
how best to recruit people for hundreds of high-ranking jobs.
   Transition personnel director Chase Untermeyer said Tuesday that
employees of leading executive search firms have advised Bush aides
on things such as ``finding sources, finding references and
interviewing.''
   Untermeyer's office is charged with sifting through thousands of
resumes that have been submitted for jobs in the new administration.
He said it is easy to learn the recruiting techniques used by
private industry recruiters, who are commonly called ``headhunters.''
   But while government and industry both aim to fill jobs with the
most qualified people, he said, Bush's nominees also ``must have a
feel for te politics of the situation, ... what the president's
programs are, what the mandate of the election was.''
   The No. 1 priority so far has been choosing Cabinet members who
will have a say in filling the sub-Cabinet jobs, Untermeyer said.
Several Cabinet vacancies remain including the secretaries of Health
and Human Services, Transportation, Energy, Interior and Labor.
   Key sub-Cabinet jobs number several hundred. They include the
assistant secretaries and undersecretaries at the agencies,
commission members, ambassadorships and judgeships.
   The new administration will have about 4,300 full-time patronage
jobs out of a federal bureaucracy of about 3 million, Untermeyer
said.
   In selecting nominees to high positions that require Senate
confirmation, Untermeyer said he and his six assistants pore over
resumes and perform preliminary background checks before selecting a
``good grouping'' of about three people for each job.
   Those people will be interviewed by John Sununu, the designated
White House chief of staff.
   ``When he is satisfied that we have a good package, off it will
go to what will be a regular meeting with the president,''
Untermeyer said. Bush, who will be inaugurated on Jan. 20, will make
the selections, he said.
   Those selected will be subject to various congressional and FBI
examinations and will have to provide financial information before
the president submits the nominations to the Senate. An appointment
is final only after Senate confirmation.
   Untermeyer made his comments at a briefing on the transition
sponsored by the National Press Foundation.
   John Trattner of the non-profit Center for Excellence in
Government approved of using management techniques similar to those
employed by business in recruiting.
   He said that by using such methods, the Bush administration
should cut down on inappropriate hirings based solely on friendships
and other non-professional criteria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881221-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0917EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Fires 1stLd-Writethru a0510 12-21 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Fires, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0510,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Probe Animal Rights Activists in Department Stores Fires</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1 graf for 5th graf pvs, ``Police in...'' to UPDATE with
caller saying attacks aimed at fur trade. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``The
caller...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities say animal rights groups claimed
responsibility for firebomb attacks on some of Britain's leading
department stores.
   The attacks late Monday and early Tuesday gutted Dingles, the
largest department store in Plymouth, England; started fires at
Selfridges and Harrods in London and at Howell's in Cardiff, Wales;
and forced evacuation of Rackhams in Birmingham, England, police
said.
   Bombs found at Rackhams and at the House of Fraser in London, a
department store on Oxford Street, were defused.
   There were no injuries. The fires, in the busy final days of the
Christmas shopping season, occurred when the stores were closed. But
authorities said the Dingles fire caused millions of dollars in
damage.
   Police in Manchester said a newspaper there received a telephone
call Tuesday from the Animal Liberation Front claiming
responsibility for the bombings. The caller was quoted as saying,
``These incidents are part of our ongoing war against the fur
trade.''
   ``The caller claimed his group had carried out the wave of
bombings which wrecked a House of Fraser store (Dingles) in Plymouth
and caused minor damage at Harrods and Selfridges in London,'' said
a spokesman for the paper, commenting on condition he was not
identified.
   ``Among the bombs he warned about was one at Rackhams store in
Birmingham, where a suspect package was found this afternoon, many
hours after the call.''
   Press Association, the domestic news agency, received a
telephoned claim of responsibility for the Plymouth fire from the
Angry Brigade, a radical militant group active in the 1970s. It said
the anonymous caller called the fire ``an attack against big
business.''
   Meanwhile, a package containing an incendiary device was found
Tuesday night at the offices of a fur trade publication in London,
police said.
   Police also said they think animal rights extremists may have
sent a package containing an incendiary device to Professor Ian
Glynn, head of Cambridge University's physiological laboratories.
   Glynn became suspicious and called police when the package
arrived at his home on Monday. He said his work does not involve the
use of live animals, a principal complaint of animal rights
protesters.
   All the stores involved in this week's firebomb attacks, except
Selfridges, belong to House of Fraser, a retail group owned by the
Al-Fayed brothers of Egypt.
   Incendiary devices stuffed behind sofa cushions ignited shortly
after midnight in Selfridges and Harrods, but damaged only the
sofas, store officials said. Fire damage at Howell's also was
reported minor.
   Officers said the firebombs had no clear link with letter bombs
sent to prominent people with police connections.
   A letter bomb addressed to the West Midlands chief constable
burst into flames in a postal sorting office in Coventry, police
said. A local councilor and a member of a police oversight committee
called police after becoming suspicious of padded envelopes sent to
them, they added.
</TEXT>
