<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     12-21 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Declares Holiday Cease-Fire With Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino today
declared a unilateral cease-fire with communist rebels for Christmas
and New Year's and called for a peaceful solution to the nearly
20-year-old insurgency.
   Mrs. Aquino said in a statement that government forces will
suspend offensive military operations from midnight Friday until
midnight Sunday, Christmas Day, and again from midnight Dec. 30
until midnight Jan. 1.
   ``All military and police forces shall maintain a state of
readiness for security action and hot pursuit in the event of any
attack or breach of the peace by any hostile group,'' she said.
   ``Let this gesture be seen for what it is _ an earnest (sign) of
our sincere desire for peace throughout our land not only in this
gentle season but throughout the year that is coming, and hopefully
for all times.''
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos said the decision had been endorsed
by Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa and the Department of
National Defense.
   Mrs. Aquino also said the government ``remains committed to the
search for a peaceful resolution of the insurgency problem'' despite
the breakdown of peace talks with the rebels last year.
   ``We remain convinced that, in the reformation of society, and
the improvement of the economy, there is a congruence of objectives
between the government and those rebels who are sincere about
helping our people,'' she said.
   She blamed ``terrorist elements in the insurgency'' for the
continued fighting but added that her government ``remained
committed to the eventual reconciliation of all Filipinos and the
attainment of permanent peace throughout our country.''
   There was no immediate response from the 24,000-strong New
People's Army, the armed wing of the outlawed Communist Party of the
Philippines.
   In a statement to news organizations last week, the New People's
Army said it traditionally observed a unilateral Christmas
cease-fire ``in areas where the fascist AFP (Armed Forces of the
Philippines) does not attack the revolutionary forces and the
masses.''
   The rebels said government offers of unilateral cease-fires were
``a hollow call devoid of sincerity'' because of stepped up military
operations against them.
</TEXT>
