<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0952EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ParksBan     12-21 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Parks Ban,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michigan Appeals Court Strikes Down Ban on Park Use By
Non-Residents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY DAUBENMIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Court of Appeals has struck down
an ordinance adopted three years ago by voters in an overwhelmingly
white Detroit suburb that barred non-residents from using city parks.
   ``We are grateful this very racially divisive conflict may be
brought to an end ... as we approach the season of peace,'' said
Howard Simon, executive director of the American Civil Liberties
Union in Michigan.
   The ruling made public Tuesday agreed with the ACLU and the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People that the
ordinance adopted by voters in the Detroit suburb of Dearborn in
November 1985 singled out blacks.
   Dearborn City Attorney William Hultgren said city officials are
studying the ruling and probably won't decide whether to appeal for
a couple of months.
   ``There have been comments in the past by elected officials that
it would be carried to the highest court,'' Hultgren said.
   ``The ball is in the city's court because it could appeal, but it
would be my hope they would put this behind them and realize the
interdependence of southeastern Michigan,'' Simon said. ``No
community is going to be able to build walls around itself. We are
all interdependent and intertwined.''
   Arthur Johnson, president of the Detroit branch of the NAACP,
said he was elated at the decision.
   The decision upheld a Wayne County Circuit Court ruling
overturning the ordinance. Non-residents have been free to use
Dearborn parks since the court fight began.
   ``We really haven't had any major problems. We really had fewer
problems after the court decision opened up the parks than before
the court decision,'' said Doyne Jackson, director of citizen
resources for Dearborn.
   The ordinance was approved after residents of Dearborn complained
that parks, swimming pools and ball diamonds along the city's border
with Detroit were being used by non-residents.
   About two-thirds of Detroit's 1.1 million residents are black;
fewer than 100 of Dearborn's 90,000 residents are black.
   Besides restricting use of parks to Dearborn residents, the
ordinance required park users to produce driver's licenses or other
identification proving their residency if stopped by police.
   Banning non-residents, the appeals court said, violated a
provision in the Michigan Constitution prohibiting discrimination on
the basis of race.
   The court said in order to be discriminatory under that part of
the constitution, an ordinance need only have a negative effect on
members of one race. Whether city officials intended to discriminate
was irrelevant, the court said.
   The provision allowing police to stop park users violated
portions of both the state and U.S. constitutions barring
unreasonable search and seizure because it gave police unfettered
discretion, the ruling said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
