<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Arafat     12-21 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arafat,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Accuses Israel Of Undermining PLO-U.S. Dialogue
^With PM-Israel-Politics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chairman Yasser Arafat accused
Israel today of undermining the ``very positive'' talks between the
United States and the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   ``Israel is using all available means to undermine the
dialogue,'' Arafat told a news conference during a one-day trip to
Yugoslavia.
   ``No doubt that the dialogue with the U.S. is very important, and
we are hoping that in the future it will have constructive results.
Its initial results are very positive,'' he said.
   Arafat's explicit recognition of Israel's right to exist and his
renunciation of terrorism led the United States to open talks with
the PLO in Tunisia on Friday for the first time since the United
States banned PLO contacts 13 years ago.
   Arafat said that Israel ``is using iron-fist policies'' and
charged it is preparing large-scale retaliation against Palestinians
in the Israeli-occupied territories, where Palestinians have been
staging an uprising.
   ``It is not by chance that on the day of the dialogue (with the
U.S.) the Israelis staged a massacre in Nablus,'' Arafat said. Five
Arab demonstrators were shot and killed by Israeli troops in the
West Bank town on Friday, and a sixth wounded protester died today.
   The agreement between Likud and Labor to form a coalition
government in Israel ``represents an agreement for war and not
peace,'' Arafat said.
   The coalition agreement between the two main Israeli political
parties bars peace talks with the PLO and the establishment of a
Palestinian state. It calls instead for negotiations with Jordan and
the Palestinians on the basis of the U.S.-brokered Camp David
Accords signed in 1978.
   The coalition agreement also calls for the expansion of Jewish
settlements in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Arafat said the accord between the two Israeli parties does not
provide for an international peace conference on the Middle East,
does not recognize independent Palestinian state, and envisages no
negotiations with the PLO.
   Arafat's visit to Yugoslavia, one of a series that followed
Washington's decision to open the dialogue with the PLO, comes as
part of an apparent campaign to drum up support for an international
Middle East conference under United Nations auspices.
   His trip follows visits to East Germany, Romania and Austria in
the past week. Arafat is to meet Premier Ciriaco De Mita in Rome on
Friday, De Mita's office said today.
   The Italian news agency AGI also reported that Arafat has
requested a meeting with Pope John Paul II. Arafat last met with the
pope in 1982. Vatican spokesmen could not be immediately reached to
comment on the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
