<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-TaxBattle     12-21 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Tax Battle,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tax Vote Sets Off Shouting Match By Japanese Lawmakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliamentary debate on a tax reform plan that would
give Japan a sales tax turned into a raucous shouting match today
when the governing party pushed the measures through a key committee
session.
   Opposition legislators stormed from their seats after the upper
house Tax System Committee chairman, Matazo Kajiki, interrupted nine
hours of deliberations to call a vote.
   The bills, which would cut corporate and income taxes while
introducing the new 3 percent sales tax, already have been approved
by the majority Liberal Democrats in the lower house. Passage in the
upper house, where the governing party also holds a commanding
majority, is expected Friday.
   The voting was carried live on national television.
   Viewers saw orderly rows of Liberal Democrats standing at their
desks in a stoic ``yes'' vote, while opposition members swarmed
around Kajiki's podium roaring their disapproval.
   Committee members stood on nearby desks and grabbed at Kajiki's
collar before security guards escorted the chairman out of the room.
   Earlier today, opposition parties, business groups and labor
unions rallied in Tokyo's Hibiya Park to denounce the sales tax,
which would go into effect on April 1. Police said 7,000 people took
part, but estimates on news reports ran as high as 12,000.
   ``We have fought our hardest to get the tax bills withdrawn,''
said Takako Doi, chairwoman of the largest opposition Japan
Socialist Party. ``We will continue to fight alongside you until the
last.''
   News reports said opposition legislators would introduce
no-confidence motions against Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and
other leaders before the upper house votes on the bills Friday.
   Today's approval in the committee session was a key step toward
effecting the first major overhaul of Japan's postwar tax system.
Tax reform, a top goal of Takeshita's administration, has eluded
previous governments.
   Boycotts by a stubborn opposition derailed parliamentary debate
on the measures after disclosures last summer that Liberal
Democratic politicians, including Takeshita and former Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, profited from questionable stock dealings.
   The scandal resulted in amendments to introduce taxes on capital
gains, a large source of political funds. The government also is
considering opposition demands to boost aid to Japan's growing
elderly population.
   The current extraordinary session of parliament ends next week.
   The Shimouma Consumers' Cooperative Association, a Tokyo
consumers cooperative, says its study indicates that under the new
tax plan, a typical four-member household with an annual income of
$53,225 would pay $1,305 less in income and residents' taxes, but
the new sales tax would cost it an additional $500.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
