<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0518 12-21 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0518,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Strike Staged; Four Wounded in Violence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with soldiers sentenced for beating
Palestinians. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HAITHAM HAMAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians in the occupied
lands staged a general strike today to urge their Arab brethren in
Israel to show more support for their uprising.
   Arab sources said four Palestinians were wounded by Israeli
troops.
   In Israel, a military court sentenced four soldiers, including a
woman, to jail terms of up to nine months for beating Palestinians
at the Dhahiriya detention camp in the West Bank, the army said.
   Also today, a Nablus resident died of gunshot wounds suffered
during clashes in the city Friday, raising the death toll from those
clashes to six.
   Witnesses told the Jaffa military court that beatings were the
norm at Dhahiriya, a camp made up of tents and old stables in the
southwestern corner of the West Bank, the Haaretz newspaper
reported. Palestinian human rights activists say detainees are
frequently abused.
   The army denied beatings are a policy. ``I flatly deny any
allegations of a policy of torture or misconduct,'' said army
spokesman Col. Raanan Gissin. ``Some deviations did occur, and we
took the necessary measures.''
   The indictment against the four soldiers listed 22 beating
incidents at Dhahiriya in March.
   The defendants ``shared in a common desire to take vengeance on
Arab prisoners suspected of hostile actions against the army,'' the
Maariv newspaper quoted the judgment as saying. ``They did not
choose their victims, but beat any prisoner that came along.''
   Lt. Uzi Saadon on several occasions kicked prisoners and punched
them with his elbows, said an army spokeswoman.
   The court Tuesday convicted Saadon of aggravated assault and
conduct unbecoming of an officer. He was given a five-month jail
term, a seven-month suspended sentence and was demoted to private.
   Private Ronit Melnick, a clerk at the jail, beat prisoners
several times with a nightstick, Maariv said. She was given one
month in jail and a two-month suspended sentence.
   The newspaper quoted Ms. Melnick as saying the beatings were
prompted by an incident in which Arabs tried to attack her while she
was hitchhiking in southern Israel.
   Cpl. Victor Mesika was given nine months, with a nine-month
suspended sentence and demoted to private, the army spokeswoman
said. Cpl. Roman Goldstein got a three-month jail term and a
four-month suspended sentence.
   A military spokeswoman said the army was considering a request by
military court judges to investigate senior officers running
Dhahiriya.
   Nablus, the West Bank's largest city with 120,000 people,
remained under curfew for a sixth day today. Arab reports said
troops went from house to house, ordering residents to remove stone
roadblocks and paint over anti-Israeli slogans.
   The army also imposed curfews on the Gaza Strip's eight refugee
camps, confining 250,000 Palestinians to their home.
   Four Palestinians were shot and wounded in stone-throwing clashes
with soldiers in the village of Tubas, near Nablus, and the Tulkarem
refugee camp, Arab hospital officials said. An army spokeswoman said
she was not aware of the shootings but was checking the reports.
   The one-day strike shut down the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip as Palestinians closed down their shops and stayed home from
their jobs.
   The strike was called by the pro-PLO Unified National Leadership
of the Uprising to urge Arabs in Israel to show greater support for
the uprising.
   At Ramallah Hospital, Abdul Rahman Kadura of Nablus died today
after being shot in the chest last Friday, doctors said. The army
said it was checking the report. The death brough to 333 the number
of Palestinians killed since the uprising began Dec. 8, 1987.
Thirteen Israelis also have been killed.
</TEXT>
