<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MyersonTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0479 12-21 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Myerson Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Out for Third Day in `Bess Mess' Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, `The jurors ...,' with deliberations resuming.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury asked to rehear testimony by the
prosecution's chief witness at Bess Myerson's divorce-fixing trial,
then sent the former Miss America and her co-defendants home for a
second day without a verdict.
   The U.S. District Court jury, which on Monday began deliberating
the conspiracy case, asked Tuesday to rehear Sukhreet Gabel's
testimony about a secret June 1986 meeting with Miss Myerson. The
jury also asked to rehear Judge John Keenan's instructions on the
law governing circumstantial evidence.
   The jurors then returned to their deliberations, recessing for
the night. They resumed deliberations this morning.
   Miss Myerson, who was Miss America in 1945; her lover, Carl
``Andy'' Capasso, 43; and former state Supreme Court Justice
Hortense Gabel, 76, are charged with plotting to cut Capasso's
temporary support payments to his estranged wife.
   The three were charged with conspiracy, mail fraud and aiding the
violation of state bribery laws. Miss Myerson, 64, also was charged
with obstruction of justice.
   If convicted on all counts, Miss Myerson could be sentenced to 30
years in prison and fined $513,000; her co-defendants up to 25 years
in prison and $263,000 in fines.
   Miss Myerson, once the city's cultural affairs commissioner, is
accused of giving a $19,000-a-year city job to Mrs. Gabel's
daughter, Sukhreet, to influence the judge, who was making interim
rulings in Capasso's bitter divorce from his wife, Nancy.
   The obstruction of justice charge against Miss Myerson stemmed
from an alleged attempt to influence Ms. Gabel's grand jury
testimony.
   According to Ms. Gabel, Miss Myerson, her former boss, arrived
unannounced to her apartment building in June 1986 while the grand
jury was investigating her hiring.
   Ms. Gabel testified that Miss Myerson told her during a nighttime
walk around the block that ``you could be dangerous,'' and that she
should ``keep your mouth shut.''
   The prosecution's case against Miss Myerson, Capasso and Mrs.
Gabel consisted of mainly circumstantial evidence because there were
no witnesses to the alleged bribe scheme.
   The government presented more than 30 witnesses and 100 pieces of
evidence to back up what they claimed were the illegal links between
the two undisputed facts in the case: Ms. Gabel was hired as Miss
Myerson's special assistant in August 1983 and a few weeks later,
Mrs. Gabel slashed Capasso's temporary support payments to his
estranged wife, Nancy, from $1,850 to $850 a week.
</TEXT>
