<1ST_LINE>r i PM-TrainRobbery     12-21 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Train Robbery,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Train Robbers Get Away with $1.6 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINTERTHUR, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four gunmen who held up a Swiss
express train got away with $1.67 million in cash, police said today.
   Police said the ``Italian or French-speaking'' robbers were still
at large despite a large-scale manhunt mounted immediately after the
holdup Monday.
   The men boarded the intercity train shortly after 9 p.m. when it
stopped at the Zurich airport station. They made their way to the
baggage car at the end of the train, tied up two post office
employees and cut up the mailbags.
   A passenger from the adjoining first-class car happened to
witness the holdup and was sprayed with tear gas and subdued.
   Two men armed with a machine gun and a revolver then entered the
first-class car and held up about 20 passengers while the other two
collected the parcels.
   All four rushed off the train 15 minutes later during a stop at
Winterthur, north of Zurich, and fled on foot carrying their haul
and their weapons in blue canvas bags, police said.
   To determine the value of the haul, police had to contact the
senders of all insured parcels shipped on the train. The police
communique did not say who mailed the parcels, but a police
spokesman said earlier that investigators had been in touch with
several banks.
</TEXT>
