<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1059EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Politics 2ndLd-Writethru a0522 12-21 0847</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0522,0869</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Approves Coalition With Likud</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with signing set for Thursday
morning. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``The delegates...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Party today approved joining a
coalition with the rival Likud bloc, virtually assuring the
formation of a national unity government to run Israel for the next
four years.
   Earlier today, the right-wing Likud voted to approve the
government after an overnight session marked by shouting and heated
debate. Israel army radio said the two parties would formally sign
their agreement Thursday morning and the new government could be
installed by parliament immediately.
   At a meeting of the center-left Labor's 1,275-member central
committee, party head Foreign Minister Shimon Peres urged the
delegates to vote for the accord, saying it was the only chance to
stem Israel's growing isolation and conflict with its Western allies.
   The delegates voted yes by an overwhelming show of hands.
   ``If a joint government with Likud and Labor had not been
established, this process of isolation and conflict with the world
would have persisted,'' Peres said. ``By building such a government,
such a process will be halted.''
   Although Peres was expected to win approval to join a Likud-led
Cabinet, younger legislators argued heatedly against the proposed
government, saying it would be deadlocked over the peace process.
   ``You once called (Likud's Prime Minister) Yitzhak Shamir the
murderer of peace. Now he has three lawyers on his team so he can
murder it again,'' legislator Chaim Ramon was quoted by Israel radio
as saying.
   Peres also said the joint government was needed to curtail the
influence of ultra-Orthodox religious parties and would effectively
bar passage of a controversial ``Who is a Jew'' amendment.
   ``We didn't understand the extent of sensitivity among U.S. Jews
about the Law of Return. I believe that now this law will remain as
it is,'' Peres said.
   He referred to anger by American Jews, most of whom are
non-Orthodox, over the proposal to accept only Orthodox conversions
to Judaism.
   Peres also vowed that although he would become finance minister
in the new government, he would continue to work toward reviving
peace talks with Arab states. ``The flag of the peace process
remains in our hands. It has nothing to do with a ministry, he said.
   The daily Haaretz reported today that although Peres will be
finance minister, a secret addition to the coalition agreement
requires that he be consulted on all sensitive defense and foreign
policy decisions.
   The new Cabinet, expected to number between 23 and 25 ministers,
could be installed by a vote of confidence in a special meeting of
parliament as early as Thursday, Israel radio reported.
   The government will resemble the current broad-based coalition
that has ruled Israel since 1984. One major difference is that
Shamir will be prime minister for all four years, instead of
switching after two years with Peres.
   It was unclear how many of the four religious parties would join
the new government. Two of the parties, Shas and Degel Hatorah, have
said they would not join. The Agudat Israel and National Religious
Party also threatened to remain outside. None of the extremist
right-wing factions were expected to join the coalition.
   The new coalition agreement, a text of which was published by
Haaretz, also bars both large parties from pulling out and forming a
narrow coalition with smaller factions in the event of disagreements.
   New elections would have to be held if the government is toppled
by a no-confidence vote, the newspaper said.
   The coalition agreement bars peace talks with the PLO and the
establishment of a Palestinian state. It calls instead for
negotiations with Jordan and the Palestinians on the basis of the
U.S.-brokered Camp David Accords signed in 1978.
   The agreement also calls for the expansion of Jewish settlements
in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip and for the building of
five to eight new settlements in the next year. U.S. officials have
called such settlements an obstacle to peace.
   Likud's approval of the accord came just after 2 a.m. in secret
balloting by 1,445 party central committee members after a 4-hour
meeting in which opponents fiercely denounced the agreement.
   Some 796 delegates, or 55.1 percent, voted for the accord, with
642 delegates, or 44.4 percent, voting against and three abstaining.
   At the meeting, many members questioned whether joining a
government with Labor would not blur Likud's right-wing ideological
stance.
   Shamir declared that a unity government had a common enemy to
fight: the PLO-proclaimed independent Palestinian state.
   ``Despite the differences, we must be united against the danger
of a Palestinian state...and the international effort to push us
back to the ill-famed 1967 borders,'' Shamir shouted. Israel
captured the West Bank and Gaza in 1967.
   Hecklers interrupted his speech with shouts of ``boo,'' and
former Defense Minister Ariel Sharon led the opposition in demanding
a government without Labor.
   ``We need a government in which one party has a majority,''
Sharon said. ``Labor is a danger to Israel's future and security.''
</TEXT>
