<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1111EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Quake     12-21 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Quake,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Damages Houses in Kirghizia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake damaged houses in a mountain village
of Soviet Kirghizia today, but apparently caused no injuries, Tass
reported.
   The official Soviet news agency said the quake in the small
Soviet republic bordering China registered 6 on the 12-point Soviet
scale that measures visible effects.
   An earthquake with a magnitude of 6 is listed by Soviet
references as a ``strong'' quake capable of knocking pictures from
walls and causing light damage to buildings.
   The quake that struck the republic of Armenia on Dec. 7, killing
an estimated 55,000 people, was reported to have had an intensity of
10.5 on the Soviet scale near its epicenter.
   Tass said the epicenter of the earthquake in Kirghizia, 1,300
miles south of Armenia, was on the southwest slopes of the Fergana
mountain range in the southern part of the republic near the village
of Shamaldy Sai.
   ``According to preliminary data, the tremors damaged houses in
the village, but there were no casualties,'' Tass said.
   Tremors also were felt in neighboring Uzbekistan, including in
that republic's capital of Tashkent which was heavily damaged by a
quake in 1966. There was no damage in Tashkent or any other city of
Uzbekistan, Tass said.
   In Denver, John Minsch of the National Earthquake Information
Service said the agency's seismology equipment had no reading on the
temblor.
   ``So far, I haven't found anything on the records. I'm still
searching, but it possibly is too small for us to see,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
