<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChristmasFurloughs     12-21 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Christmas Furloughs,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Limits Christmas Prison Furloughs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crackdown on furloughs for inmates
convicted of violent crimes means fewer Texas prisoners will be
allowed to go home for Christmas.
   Texas Department of Corrections officials said they will release
only 45 inmates for seven-day Christmas furloughs, compared with 160
freed for the holiday last year.
   Of the 160, 37 were convicted either of murder or involuntary
manslaughter. Others included prisoners serving time for aggravated
assault on a peace officer.
   The furlough crackdown began after the presidential candidates
this year traded accusations about violent prisoners given prison
leave.
   President-elect George Bush criticized his Democratic challenger,
Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, for allowing violent
prisoners in Massachusetts to be released on furlough, including
Willie Horton, a murderer who was charged with raping a woman after
he failed to return from a weekend leave.
   Texas Gov. Bill Clements, a Republican, joined in the criticism
until he was forced to admit that similar policies were in effect in
his state. Nearly 900 prisoners, including 500 murderers, were
granted furloughs during Clements' administration.
   The Texas Board of Correction responded by narrowing the
eligibility for furlough. Among those excluded were inmates with
histories of sex offenses and those convicted of capital murder.
   Prison board Chairman Charles Terrell said Tuesday it was the
board's intention to tighten up, but not destroy, the furlough
program.
</TEXT>
