<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Cuomo-Brown     12-21 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuomo-Brown,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Endorses Ron Brown For National Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo today endorsed Ron Brown, a
former top campaign aide to Jesse Jackson, to become national
chairman of the Democratic Party.
   Because of Cuomo's stature within the party, the endorsement is
almost certain to strenghten Brown's campaign for the post.
   The governor made the endorsement in a letter to the state party
chairman and telephoned Brown to inform him of the action, said
press secretary Gary Fryer.
   Brown ``would make a superb national chair and if I had a vote to
cast at this moment, it would go to him,'' the governor wrote.
   The party's new leader is to be chosen at a meeting of the nearly
400 voting members of the Democratic National Committee in
Washington on Feb. 9 and 10. Chairman Paul Kirk has announced he
will not seek re-election.
   Other contenders for the post are Richard Wiener, Michigan party
chairman, and former Reps. James Jones of Oklahoma, Michael Barnes
of Maryland and James V. Stanton of Ohio.
   In his letter, Cuomo noted that of the announced candidates, he
knows Brown best. ``He was my student in law school and we have
stayed in touch over the years,'' said Cuomo, a former professor at
St. John's University Law School.
   Cuomo was considered a contender for the 1988 Democratic
presidential nomination but announced in 1987 that he would not run
and later said he wouldn't accept a draft if there were a deadlocked
national convention.
</TEXT>
