<2ND_LINE>PM-Armored Robbery, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0448,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Santa Claus Look-alike Holds Up Armored Car</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead and INSERTS one graf after 6th graf pvs,
`Authorities suspect ...' to UPDATE with reward posted; SUBS last
graf to CORRECT that holdup was third robbery of an armored car
company, sted an armored car.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK SEAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An armored car company offered a
$70,000 reward for a gun-wielding Santa Claus and helper who robbed
two guards of more than $700,000, the FBI said today.
   Police and the FBI said the straight-faced Santa took two sacks
of cash from Dunbar Armored Security Inc. guards outside a United
Bank branch in a shopping plaza Tuesday morning.
   No shots were fired and neither guard was injured, police said.
One guard was apparently inside the bank, while the other was
carrying the sacks to a van.
   ``This is not a joke. Get up against the wall. Give me the bags
of money,'' the robber, between 35 and 40 years old, told the
guards, according to Detective Capt. Russell Hughes.
   The white-bearded robber, dressed in a Santa hat and trench coat
and bearing a silver revolver, hopped into a car with a male
accomplice and drove off, Hughes said.
   Authorities suspect that the robbers tailed the armored car to
the bank, said Terry Shumard, an FBI spokesman. He said the two bags
held more than $700,000 in cash.
   Shumard said Dunbar has authorized a $70,000 reward for
information leading to the arrests of the robbers.
   ``It's too bad people have to use Santa Claus like that because
kids look up to him,'' said a teller at the bank who would only
identify herself as Miss Mroz. ``This was really strange.''
   A Farmington resident who witnessed the robbery followed the
suspects' car in his van for about a mile on Interstate 84 and
provided investigators with descriptions of the robbers, Lt. Anthony
Duffy said.
   Employees and the two or three customers inside the bank at the
time were unaware the theft was taking place, according to teller
Jane E. Neveu.
   It was the third robbery of an armored car company in five years
in the suburban Hartford community of 60,000, including the 1983
theft of $7.1 million from a Wells Fargo depot, the second-largest
cash robbery in U.S. history.
</TEXT>
