<HEAD>Red Cross Officials Arrive in Cyprus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 6th pvs, ``Junot, who...'' to UPDATE
with militias appealing to Red Cross to return. Pickup 7th pvs,
``The suspension...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HASSAN MROUEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven Red Cross officials who were
evacuated from Lebanon after they received death threats arrived in
Cyprus today on their way home to Switzerland.
   The International Committee for the Red Cross said in Geneva on
Tuesday that it was suspending its humanitarian operations in
Lebanon because of ``serious threats against its delegates on
mission in Lebanon, placing their lives in acute danger.''
   The evacuees, eight men and three women, left five hours later
for Zurich. Six Red Cross officials remained in Lebanon and were due
to leave today.
   ``We're disappointed,'' said Francis Junot, deputy chief of the
Red Cross delegation in Lebanon. ``We received a communication from
Geneva and were ordered to leave ... I can't comment on the nature
of the threat.''
   ``This has never happened before,'' he said. ``We expect the
situation won't last and we'll be able to return after studying the
situation. We hope to return.''
   Junot, who has served in Lebanon on five separate ICRC missions
since 1981, said he had not felt in danger.
   Later today, the two largest Moslem militias in south Lebanon
appealed to the Red Cross to return, blaming a spate of terrorist
attacks on humanitarian workers on a ``criminal minority.''
   The appeals came in separate statements by the Sunni Moslem
Nasserite leftist militia that governs the southern port city of
Sidon and the mainstream Shiite Moslem Amal militia in Tyre.
   Both factions called for concerted action against terrorist
groups in south Lebanon in order to guarantee the safety of foreign
humanitarian agencies.
   The suspension of operations in Lebanon, torn by civil war and
factional violence for 13 years, was the first time the Red Cross
has withdrawn its workers from any country in its 125-year history
because of death threats.
   ``I came to Lebanon one year ago ... I didn't feel threatened and
I'm ready to go back anytime,'' said one of the evacuees who refused
to identify himself.
   The announcement Tuesday came four days after the release of
Peter Winkler, a Red Cross delegate who was held hostage for nearly
a month.
   After Winkler was kidnapped Nov. 17 in the southern port city of
Sidon, the Red Coss withdrew 10 of its 27 workers in Lebanon.
   Swiss authorities said Winkler's kidnappers, believed to be
pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems, sought a more lenient sentence for a
Lebanese Shiite, Hussein Hariri, who goes on trial in Switzerland
soon on charges of hijacking an Air Afrique airliner in June and
killing a French passenger.
   The Swiss were the largest Western community remaining in west
Beirut after waves of kidnappings, assassinations and civil war had
forced tens of thousands of foreigners to flee Lebanon in the last
13 years.
   The Red Cross workers were doing humanitarian work, including
fitting artificial limbs and visiting Palestinian and Lebanese
prisoners in jails in the Israeli-controlled section of south
Lebanon.
   About 150 Lebanese employees of the Red Cross have been told to
``go home for a week'' and await further word from Geneva on whether
a total shutdown will be ordered.
   The ICRC operates in about 80 countries, providing food and
medical relief to civilians trapped in wars, conflicts and disasters.
   Fifteen foreigners are currently being held in Lebanon, including
nine Americans, three Britons, an Irishman, an Italian and a Belgian.
   The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was abducted March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
