<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RefundRap 1stLd-Writethru a0511 12-21 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Refund Rap, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0511,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Throws Out Man's Conviction For Razor Return</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 3rd graf, `In 1985 ...,' to UPDATE with
comment by public defender who handled case.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man shouldn't have been convicted of a
crime and sentenced to 32 years in prison after he tried to get a
refund for an electric razor for which he didn't have a receipt, the
Indiana Supreme Court ruled.
   The court Tuesday struck down the attempted theft and habitual
criminal convictions of Richard Allen Smith and ordered the
49-year-old Indianapolis man discharged from prison.
   In 1985, Smith received a 2-year sentence on the theft conviction
and 30 years for the habitual offender charge, which was supported
by earlier auto theft and drug convictions.
   ``It's the kind of case that could happen to anybody,'' said M.E.
Tuke, the public defender who handled Smith's appeal.
   Smith's problem began in November 1978, when he took a $42.96
Remington razor to a Hook's Drug store in Mooresville and later to
another outlet of the chain in Martinsville to get a refund. The
package he presented had a Hook's price tag on it, but employees
refused to give Smith a refund, citing store policy requiring a
receipt for a refund.
   He then went to a Danner's department store in Martinsville and
presented the razor, without a price tag, for a refund. Hook's
employees, suspicious about Smith's behavior, had alerted Danner's
employees of his earlier attempt to get a refund.
   Danner's employees called police when Smith showed up and stalled
until police arrived to arrest Smith, court records show.
   The long gap betwen his arrest and sentencing occurred because
Smith left the courtroom during his trial and remained at large for
four years, according to court records.
   Prosecutors argued at his trial that Smith attempted ``to exert
unauthorized control'' over Danner's profit margin by creating the
false impression he had purchased the razor at the store.
   However, the Supreme Court concluded that to prove Smith was
trying to create a false impression, the state needed to prove Smith
hadn't purchased the razor at Danner's. There was no evidence to
demonstrate where the razor was purchased, the court said.
   ``Without that crucial element of proof, every citizen engaging
in a simple refund transaction would risk criminal penalties,''
Chief Justice Randall T. Shepard wrote for the court. ``Some
citizens such as those seeking to return gifts simply do not know
where the item was originally purchased.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
