<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Landers-Abuse     12-21 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Landers-Abuse,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Letter to Ann Landers Prompts State Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who wrote columnist Ann Landers
saying they've kept their teen-age daughter chained in their
basement for several months should seek help, the state's top social
services official said.
   Social Services Director Patrick Babcock appealed on Tuesday to
the unidentified couple to call a state child abuse hotline for
help, saying the state's first objective would be to help the
family, not prosecute them.
   State officials tried to determine the identity of the couple
after reading the letter Tuesday in the Landers advice column, which
is syndicated and carried by 1,200 newspapers, but found it
impossible to determine whether the letter is authentic or a prank,
Babcock said.
   ``I'm not sure we will ever be able to trace it back,'' he said.
   Ann Landers was on vacation, but an assistant in her Chicago
office, Laurie Solomon, said today the anonymous letter was received
about two months ago. Miss Landers is about six to eight weeks ahead
on her column, Ms. Solomon said.
   ``All we had was a Detroit postmark,'' she said.
   ``Miss Landers did not question the authenticity of the letter,''
Ms. Solomon said. ``She's been doing this for so long, she generally
can tell when a letter is a fake letter.''
   The column ``doesn't always appear on the same day in every
paper, but this letter ran the day it was scheduled to appear,'' she
said.
   Ms. Solomon said the office has not heard from anyone claiming to
be the man who wrote the letter, but was contacted by Michigan
officials for help in tracking down the family.
   The letter was from a man who said he and his wife had punished
their 17-year-old daughter for her drug and alcohol abuse by
chaining her to a bed frame in the basement of their Detroit home,
initially for 24-hour periods.
   ``Our daughter has been chained to her bed frame in our basement
for three months now and we are afraid to let her out for fear of
getting into trouble with the law,'' said the letter.
   The man said the daughter was becoming hostile and had cut her
arm badly when she broke a bathroom window during her once-a-week
shower. He said he feared the arm might be infected, but he was
afraid to seek medical attention for her for fear of arousing
suspicion.
   The writer did not identify himself, signing the letter ``Needing
Guidance in Detroit.''
   Landers advised the writer to unchain his daughter and take her
to a hospital emergency room and to seek legal help.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
