<DOCNO> AP881221-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1216EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   12-21 0908</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0945</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout
the nation.
   Dec. 18
   The Press-Enterprise, Riverside, Calif., on federal pay raises:
   It's said, by those urging federal pay increases, that the
current congressional salary of $89,500 may sound like a lot to the
average citizen, but the average citizen doesn't understand the
problem. ...
   A member of Congress, for instance, often has to support two
households on a salary that has lost purchasing power over the
years; that, and the high cost of D.C. living, is cited by the
advisory commission urging a raise in Senate and House salaries to
$135,000.
   Then again, average citizens may have trouble getting into one
home. ... And the average family _ $30,200 a year _ sustains its
purchasing power by relying on two incomes.
   All of which is to say that if it's sympathy the members of
Congress are looking for, they aren't going to get it. Except from
their own, of course. ...
   A case can be made that, considering their responsibilities, that
(salaries) can go up a turn or two, perhaps to the $100,000 level,
as long as it is tied to a ban on outside honoraria. But most
members of Congress still won't think they're getting what they
deserve. Few people do.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 19
   Portland (Maine) Press Herald on the federal budget deficit:
   Bringing the government's annual deficits under control remains
our biggest domestic challenge. One of the easiest ways of raising
money for deficit reduction would be to increase the gasoline tax.
...
   The advantages of a boost in the present 9-cent-a-gallon federal
tax are numerous. Analysts estimate that each penny increase would
generate $1 billion a year in additional revenue. ...
   A couple of arguments make it difficult. First, ... the United
States is virtually without any mass transportation for much of the
public. ...
   Second, a gasoline tax increase would fall more heavily upon
lower-income groups than on the weathly. And the regressive nature
of the gasoline tax would be magnified since many of the nation's
poorer families operate older, less fuel-efficient cars.
   Nevertheless, America confronts the coming New Year one year
older and deeper in debt. The federal deficits simply have to be
reduced significantly. An increase in the gasoline tax offers a
partial solution. No one should reject it out of hand.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 19
   The Albuquerque (N.M.) Tribune on the National Economic
Commission's stand on open meetings:
   The National Economic Commission, established by Congress last
February under a mandate to come up with a way to shrink the huge
federal deficit, displayed an unsettling arrogance the other day
when it canceled a meeting rather than comply with a court order to
open its discussions to the public.
   In response to a court suit filed by three news organizations and
Ralph Nader's group, Public Citizen, federal Judge Joyce Hens Green
told the commission that government ``sunshine'' laws require that
its meetings be open to the public.
   Rather than comply, the commission canceled its next scheduled
meeting, and its general counsel reportedly is looking for ways to
get around the judge's ruling.
   What are members afraid of? If the commission wants public
support for whatever it recommends, it stands a better chance of
getting it if the people who pay the bills are let in on the
decision-making process.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 20
   Fort Lauderdale (Fla.) Sun-Sentinel on John Tower as defense
secretary:
   John Tower may have been the best friend the Pentagon ever had
during his days as chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee,
but the diminutive Texan is going to have to trade his sword for a
scissors as George Bush's secretary of defense.
   His old committee, now chaired by Democrat Sam Nunn of Georgia,
should make certain in confirmation hearings that Tower's conversion
from screeching hawk to eagle-eyed overseer is genuine. ...
   The Senate, which tends to handle alumni such as Tower with
excessive courtesy during confirmation hearings, should put aside
the kid gloves in its inquiry into Tower's fitness to head the
Defense Department.
   Only the most vigorous personal and philosophical investigation
of Tower's credentials is in order when the position is so important
and the candidate is so controversial.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 19
   The Evening Sun, Baltimore, on Jack Kemp as HUD secretary:
   The ... appointment of Rep. Jack Kemp to be secretary of Housing
and Urban Development in the Bush administration strikes us as an
imaginative choice.
   That may sound surprising, coming from a newspaper which has
criticized the Kemp-Roth supply-side economic theories which have
brought the nation to grief during the past eight years.
   Rest assured, if Kemp had been appointed Treasury secretary or
chairman of the economic advisers, it would have been time to sound
the sirens throughout the land.
   But as HUD secretary, Kemp will not be applying his crackpot
economic theories; rather, he will be putting his considerable
energy and determination behind revitalization of America's cities.
   Throughout the Reagan administration, urban policy has been based
on a fantasy called enterprise zones to encourage inner city
development through tax relief. The policy wasn't thought out
clearly to begin with and was administered with such cavalier
indifference that the General Accounting Office only last week
pronounced the enterprise zones program in Maryland a waste of time
and money.
   Now Kemp will have a chance to make the promise good, if it can
be done.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
