<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0818</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: be done.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 20
   St. Louis Post-Dispatch on Bush's Cabinet choices:
   President-elect George Bush has made two disappointing choices in
naming Sen. John Tower defense secretary and ... settling on Rep.
Jack Kemp as secretary of Housing and Urban Development. ...
   Bush apparently was trying to mollify the party's right wing, but
there was no need to. Any debt he owed the far right was paid when
he selected J. Danforth Quayle as his running mate. ...
   Tower's selection as defense secretary could cause the new
president serious political problems. The former Texas senator has
pledged that he will work to control the Pentagon's budget and to
reform the military's wasteful and fraud-ridden procurement system.
But to do so, ... Tower will have to go completely against his own
hawkish track record.
   While in the Senate, he fought hard for every useless or
overpriced Pentagon program that came along and he resisted
procurement reform proposals. In a deficit-tight era, with the
Pentagon facing unavoidable cuts, ... Tower is the wrong man. By
picking him, ... Bush is practically guaranteeing confrontation with
Congress over military spending. ...
   Kemp is well known for his strong ideological commitment to
supply-side economics and a return to the gold standard. He can be
expected to advocate a laissez-faire approach to housing for the
poor that won't meet their needs.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 14
   The Times, Trenton, N.J., on federal pay raises:
   Some citizens will look at the 50 percent pay raises recommended
for members of Congress ... and recoil in horror.
   Senators and representatives already receive $89,500 a year. How
can another $45,000 ... possibly be justified?
   Well, read the fine print.
   The congressional raises (would be linked) to a ban on honoraria,
... fees paid to members of Congress by special interest groups for
giving a speech, or writing a blurb, or just showing up at an event.
   Getting rid of that kind of hidden payola would constitute an
investment in good government.
   And, as Common Cause President Fred Wertheimer warns, make sure
that the door is also closed on other, roundabout ways by which
special interest might provide financial benefits to members of
Congress. Not doing this, as ... Wertheimer says, ``will only lead
to the honoraria problem surfacing in new forms.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 15
   Statesman-Journal, Salem, Ore., on federal pay raises:
   After we get over the initial shock of a 50 percent increase in
pay for our congressmen, federal judges and top government
officials, the raise will look like a good deal for them and for us.
...
   We get what we pay for. If we don't pay senators and
representatives enough to maintain a home in Washington, D.C., and
afford the normal duties of a federal lawmaker, then the average man
and woman won't be able to serve in Congress. ...
   When the dentist bill or the tuition payment comes due, a
congressman who is supporting one household at home and another in
D.C. may do what he has to. He or she will accept money from special
interest groups. The payment is called an honorarium. ...
   The proposed pay increase would abolish the honorarium. ...
   The average (pay) for all of us should be higher. ... The effort
should be on giving the low-paid a decent salary, not on denying pay
that is adequate for men and women filling our most important public
offices.

</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 16
   The Morning News Tribune, Tacoma, Wash., on U.S.-PLO talks:
   The difference between what Yasser Arafat said in English at a
news conference (Dec. 14) and what he said in Arabic before the
United Nations (Dec. 13) in Geneva was so small as to be almost
invisible to the naked eye.
   But it was important enough to matter _ and to pave the way for
the first direct talks in 13 years between the U.S. and Palestine
Liberation Organization. ...
   Arafat and the State Department thought they had worked out .. .
precisely what Arafat had to say in Geneva to meet the three
conditions the U.S. has set for dealing with the PLO on the
Palestinian issue. But his speech came up short, in the U.S.
estimation, and again the U.S. declared Arafat had not gone far
enough. ...
   In his press conference, Arafat specifically renounced without
qualification ``all forms'' of terrorism. He also dropped the
qualifiers he had previously attached to the PLO's acceptance of
U.N. resolutions outlining Israel's right to exist.
   That was enough. Now, the U.S. has properly shifted the onus to
Israel, which must demonstrate it is serious about pursuing
realistic options for a settlement. It cannot pretend there's a
solution to the Palestinian question that does not involve the PLO.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
