<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0878</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: the PLO.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 15
   The Honolulu Star-Bulletin on U.S.-PLO talks:
   What (PLO Leader Yasser) Arafat's statement means, however, is
far from certain. He does not speak for everyone in the PLO, much
less the entire Arab world. And he is notorius for changing his
position to suit his circumstances.
   Israel doesn't believe either Arafat or the PLO has changed, and
wants nothing to do with them.
   It may be no coincidence that this initiative was taken by an
outgoing administration at a time when the political fallout can be
minimized. President-elect Bush was undoubtedly involved in the
decision.
   It will now be up to the incoming Bush administration to make
what it can of this breakthrough.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 14
   Daily Journal, Fergus Falls, Minn., on federal pay raises:
   ``Underpaid'' is not generally a term used to describe those who
earn $89,500 a year, so it's hard for most people to feel much
sympathy for members of Congress.
   Thus, Americans ... are not likely to passionately embrace the
idea of raising lawmakers' salaries by 50 percent. Yet it's true
that a pay raise for Congress is in order. ...
   A presidential advisory commission recommended that members of
Congress, along with federal judges and other top government
officials, receive pay raises of 50 percent. The panel attached one
stipulation to its recommendation, though, and that is the reason
this pay raise should be adopted: Members said members of Congress
should get the raise IF they could no longer collect speaking fees.
   It's those speaking fees that leave Americans with the impression
that their lawmakers are being bought and sold by the monied
interests of the nation.
   No one is suggesting that government officials should get rich
off their public service. But it isn't unreasonable for the
government to pay enough so that public service isn't an enormous
financial sacrifice; if that's the case, only the rich can afford to
run for office, and, in the end, it's the country that ends up
poorer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 14
   The Janesville (Wis.) Gazette on the shortage of registered
nurses:
   A federal commission studying ways to resolve the nationwide
shortage of registered nurses called for higher pay.
   That's no surprise. But the panel said attention also must be
given to increasing professional representation of nurses on
policymaking. The latter may hold just as much a key to the solution
as the pay.
   The 19-member commission convened by the Department of Health and
Human Services noted that with increasing frequency, nurses provide
services that should be carried out by other health care workers.
   In the past five years, the commission said, the nation's
hospitals had laid off 100,000 staff employees and added their
duties to those of other nurses.
   The panel also reported that nurses were being asked to render
more care typically performed by such higher-priced personnel as
respiratory and physical therapists.
   Giving employees increased input on policy-making matters has
become more common in many lines of work in the past decade as
companies seek ways to improve quality, increase competitiveness and
contain costs. Nurses on the front lines of the exploding medical
care field should have plenty to offer in that continued search for
excellence.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 21
   The Times-News, Hendersonville, N.C., on the governor's right to
veto:
   North Carolina's governor is the only governor in the union who
can't veto legislation. ...
   Now state Rep. Al Lineberry, D-Guilford, has said that he's
preparing a bill for the 1989 legislature that would, among other
things, give the governor veto power and limit the number of terms
top legislative leaders could serve.
   Sounds good, but it's not, principally because the veto as
envisoned by Lineberry and House Speaker Liston Ramsey, D-Madison,
largely would be symbolic.
   A simple majority in the legislature would be required to
override it. Because a simple majority is required (on three
readings) to pass legislation to begin with, what's the point?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 15
   The Decatur (Ill.) Herald and Review, on recruiting violations:
   Nevada-Las Vegas basketball Coach Jerry Tarkanian'a case against
NCAA investigators has been winding its way through the courts for
more than a decade.
   When it began, the Nevada Supreme Court and a U.S. district court
agreed that NCAA probers had exceeded the bounds of procedural good
taste during an investigation of recruiting improprieties at
Nevada-Las Vegas under Tarkanian from 1975 to 1977.
   At the time, courts were inclined to protect individuals from the
wrath of private as well as governmental bodies, insisting that
private investigative bodies follow proper rules of due process. . ..
   Tarkanian might well have won his dispute had his lawyers gotten
to the Supreme Court by the mid-1980s.
   Alas, in the late 1980s, the courts, following the lead of the
Reagan administration, seem more than willing to let private bodies
act in ways that would bring sharp censure to government bodies.
   In effect, the court argued, in a 5-4 decision, that the NCAA,
being a non-government, had no obligation to observe constitutional
decorum during its probe of Tarkanian.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End Editorial Rdp</HEAD>
