<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0550 12-21 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0550,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Date Set for North Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Adds detail thruout with prosecutors seeking North's
notebooks, Simon on classification questions</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell today set
Jan. 31 as the starting date for the trial of former National
Security Council aide Oliver North in the Iran-Contra affair.
   Gesell's decision came at the end of an hour-long hearing in
which one of North's lawyers, Barry Simon, pressed the judge to set
a trial date.
   Simon said the defense ``would like to get subpoenas out'' to a
number of people, including some in the Reagan administration who
will be leaving government next month ``for the four corners of the
earth.''
   ``We certainly hope we can meet that date,'' John Keker, who will
head the prosecution team appointed by independent counsel Lawrence
Walsh, said after the hearing.
   During the hearing, Keker revealed that the government is trying
to obtain notebooks which North compiled while he was the NSC.
Portions of the notebooks were disclosed at congressional hearings
last year which looked into the sale of arms to Iran and the
transfer of profits to Nicaraguan rebels.
   During the hearing, Simon, who has clashed repeatedly with
Gesell, complained that North's lawyers should be told which
portions are classified among some 30,000 pages of documents it has
in its possession. Simon has said the documents are relevant to the
defense of the former White House aide and that in some cases
perhaps only a single word or sentence in a document of several
pages is classified.
   Prosecutors said it would take several weeks to identify which
portions of all the documents are classified.
   North's lawyers have until Jan. 3 to identify 300 classified
documents they plan to use at trial.
   There are legal obstacles that could scuttle a trial of North
before it gets started, particularly the question of using
classified documents.
   Experts from the U.S. intelligence community are meeting with
aides to Walsh in sessions dealing with deletions of sensitive
information from classified documents.
   Gesell ruled Dec. 12 that too much material relevant to the case
had been excised from some classified documents Walsh wants to use
as evidence at trial.
   Material had been blacked out from portions of 300 classified
documents he is planning to use at trial. Gesell said that while the
documents had all been properly classified, too much had been held
back, especially if a jury was to understand the facts of the case.
   Gesell said that all references to eight countries involved in
the Iran-Contra affair must be restored and made public at trial.
The countries included Israel, Iran and Nicaragua.
   The judge also said that the text of information obtained by
intelligence must for the most part be presented verbatim. He said,
however, the methods and techniques used to obtain intelligence
reports should remain secret.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
