<HEAD>Boat People Threaten to Burn Down Vessel Housing Them</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese boat people protesting a shortage of
food and water on Wednesday threatened to set fire to a ferry that
is serving as their shelter, police said.
   The 162 refugees have been forced to live on the vessel in Hong
Kong harbor because a refugee center on the outlying Green Island
was overcrowded, authorities said.
   The refugees calmed down after talking to United Nations
representatives and authorities who promised to look for other
accommodations, police said.
   It was the third protest in as many days by the refugees, who
also complained of a lack of warm clothing. Until Friday, the vessel
housed 472 Vietnamese, but more than 300 have moved to the Green
Island center.
   About 600 Vietnamese refugees, many of whom fled by boat from
their homeland, have arrived in Hong Kong in the past month.
