<DOCNO> AP881221-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1251EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MinistersTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0536 12-21 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ministers Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0536,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Reached In Civil Rights Leaders Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with details of agreement and
case being dismissed against all 13 defendants; CORRECTS that only
five of 13 were to stand trial today. Picks up 11th graf pvs, `The
management ...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today dismissed charges against 13
civil rights leaders arrested during a protest of the city's housing
program after prosecutors reduced the charges and all 13 pleaded no
contest.
   The city prosecutor called the arrangement a compromise. An
attorney for the defendants said city officials agreed to meet with
them next month to try to resolve differences.
   The 13 were arrested for trying to block a City Council meeting
in June. They were protesting the firing of a black community
development official, the reassignment of another, the retirement of
a third and the resignation of a fourth because of alleged
mismanagement of the housing program.
   Jury selection in a trial for five of the 13 was scheduled to
resume today in Municipal Court, but Judge John Patterson dismissed
the jury pool and went into his chambers with defense attorneys and
prosecutors.
   ``While the case only involved a second-degree misdemeanor, there
were other important issues involved, but they were not a matter for
this court,'' Patterson said.
   Patterson had warned the defendants that he would not allow the
trial to be used as a forum on problems between the city
administration and blacks.
   The Revs. Issac Johnson, Rudolph May, Reece Barbour, Ronald
Barnett and John Reese each were charged with one count of
obstructing official business, a second-degree misdemeanor. The
charge carries a maximum sentence of three months in jail and a $750
fine.
   Under the agreement, the city reduced the charge to failure to
disperse. The ministers pleaded no contest; the judge dismissed the
case and ordered their records expunged.
   A trial for the eight other defendants was scheduled for next
month, but the charges of obstructing official business were dropped
under the agreement. In addition, two faced charges of resisting
arrest that also were dismissed.
   City Prosecutor John Madigan, who called the agreement a
compromise, said: ``Sometimes it takes a court trial to figure out
this isn't the way to go.''
   Jay B. Simmons, an attorney for the ministers, said the city
``extended a fair offer.'' City officials, he said, agreed to meet
with the ministers by the second week in January in an attempt to
resolve their differences.
   ``At this point, major differences have not been resolved. They
(city officials) must learn to consult with us before taking action
or they will continue to have problems,'' he said.
   The 13 ministers and civil rights leaders were arrested after
they refused to leave City Council chambers during a protest of the
city's handling of problems in its Community Development Department.
   The management shuffle in the department followed an
investigation by the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development that said the city's housing rehabilitation program was
deficient.
   The civil rights leaders wanted to know why the men were
reprimanded without being consulted about problems in the
department. They also asked for a public hearing into the
allegations.
   City officials rejected their requests, sparking months of
protests by civil rights leaders, who claim there is a conspiracy
against black officials in Toledo.
   Racial tensions were heightened in July, when Police Chief Martin
Felker ordered police to randomly stop and question groups of black
teen-agers in an attempt to end racial violence in the city's Old
West End. Felker rescinded the order in August after protests.
   Blacks comprise about 17 percent of Toledo's 340,000 residents.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
