<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Czechoslovakia     12-21 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Frees Four Activists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities in Czechoslovakia have freed
four political prisoners, including a Roman Catholic activist who
was detained in a psychiatric hospital after leading a petition
drive for religious freedom.
   A Vienna emigre source said authorities apparently gave the
activist, Augustin Navratil, permission to spend his 60th birthday
on Dec. 22 and Christmas at home because they feared a throng of
visitors at the hospital.
   Navratil, the author of a petition for religious freedom that
garnered about 600,000 signatures this year, was hospitalized in
Kromeriz on Oct. 28 because of alleged insanity.
   Swiss psychiatrists who examined him earlier this year declared
him sane.
   About 1,000 people demonstrated on his behalf earlier this month
and hundreds were expected to visit him in Kromeriz during the next
few days, the emigre source said. Navratil must return to Kromeriz
on Sunday.
   The source, who asked not to be identified, said Ivan Polansky, a
publisher of underground literature who was sentenced in June to
four years in jail, was released Dec. 15 for health reasons.
   Polansky, 52, suffers from a heart condition, the source said.
   His sentence was reduced to two years under an amnesty issued by
the authorities Oct. 28 to mark the 70th anniversary of Czechoslovak
independence, and was lifted completely after an appeal hearing in
Polansky's jail in central Slovakia this month, the source said.
   Meanwhile, authorities in Prague have released from detention one
of four independent peace activists arrested in October and under
investigation on charges of incitement.
   The emigre source said Lubomir Vydra had been released but
authorities are still investigating him on the incitement charge.
   Activist Jiri Tichy was released Dec. 18 but authorities are
continuing to press charges against him, another emigre source, the
publishing house Palach Press, reported later from London.
   Also today, Keston College, a center in London for monitoring
religious affairs in the Soviet bloc, said Roman Catholic priest
Frantisek Lizna had had his two-month jail sentence confirmed by an
appeals court in Brno.
   Lizna, who is banned by Czechoslovak authorities from preaching,
was sentenced Oct. 26 to two months in jail on charges of disrupting
public order. He is due to be released Monday.
</TEXT>
