<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HighwayKillings     12-21 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Highway Killings,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Arraigned In Rapes In Areas Where Bodies Found Off Highways</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unemployed man pleaded innocent
today to all charges in two rapes that occurred in areas where the
bodies of six women were found along highways.
   Neil Anderson, 35, of New Bedford was indicted Tuesday by a
Bristol County grand jury. Anderson _ who has not been named as a
suspect in the murders _ was charged with aggravated rape,
kidnapping and assault with a dangerous weapon, a knife, in
connection with the Aug. 20, 1987, rape of a woman in nearby
Dartmouth. He also was charged with a July 22, 1988, rape in the
same town.
   Bristol County Superior Court Judge John Sheehan denied a request
to lower Anderson's $20,000 cash bail.
   Anderson's court-appointed attorney, James Quinn, argued that
bail should be reduced to $1,000 cash, saying his client was not a
serious risk.
   ``He has not what I would call a serious criminal record. He's
never been convicted of a crime requiring incarceration,'' Quinn
said. ``He has been unemployed since August and lives at home with
his elderly grandmother and his mother.''
   First Assistant District Attorney Raymond Veary argued against
lowering bail, saying that an investigation into a possible third
rape charge from a case in nearby Fall River was pending.
   After the hearing, Veary declined to say whether Anderson is a
suspect in the murders.
   ``He has been questioned. As to how extensively, I'm not willing
to comment,'' Veary said.
   Quinn said he believed Anderson has been unfairly linked to the
unsolved killings.
   ``As far as I know, the list of suspects is from the telephone
directory. I don't think that he's been singled out,'' Quinn said.
   Anderson declined to talk to reporters.
   The 1987 rape allegedly took place along Interstate 195 in
Dartmouth, the same general area of southeastern Massachusetts where
four of the six bodies were found. The victim was reportedly a
prostitute, but the Bristol County district attorney office has
declined to confirm the report.
   Anderson was arrested last week at his home, about a mile from
the Weld Square section of New Bedford, a neighborhood known for
drugs and prostitution that three of the four identified murder
victims were known to frequent.
   At Anderson's arraignment, prosecutors said the 1987 incident
involved the abduction of a woman from the Weld Square area. The
victim said she was driven to the wooded area and raped at
knifepoint.
</TEXT>
