<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Vanuatu     12-21 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vanuatu,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Of Vanuatu Arrested, Charged With Mutiny</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT VILA, Vanuatu (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Sokomanu was arrested
today and charged with inciting mutiny during his abortive attempt
to install an interim government in this South Pacific island nation.
   The Vanuatu Supreme Court refused to consider bail and ordered
him held in police custody until Jan. 4, his next court appearance.
If convicted, Sokomanu faces a maximum of ife imprisonment.
   Australian diplomats said they were monitoring developments
closely and praised the government of Prime Minister Walter Lini,
whom Sokomanu tried to oust, for its handling of the case.
   Sokomanu's appearance before Chief Justice Frederick Cooke
followed a brief hearing at the Port Vila Magistrate's court soon
after he was arrested during a police raid on his official residence
and office.
   The president also was charged with administering unlawful oaths
and being present when they were taken.
   Sokomanu, 56, became president in 1980 when Vanuatu, then known
as the New Hebrides, achieved independence from France and Britain.
He tried to form an interim government on Sunday headed by his
nephew Barak Sope in the hope of calling new elections in February.
   He said he took the action because of the failing economy and
outbreaks of violence during a year-long power struggle between Lini
and Sope.
   Earlier this week, the Vanuatu Supreme Court ruled the
president's action was unlawful and unconstitutional.
   Australian news reports said both the prosecution and defense
counsels suggested the possibility of house arrest, but Cooke said
the seriousness of the charges gave him no alternative but to deny
bail.
   Public Prosecuter John Baxter-Wright told the court the charge of
inciting mutiny related to the alleged drafting and distribution of
an open letter to Vanautu's police and paramilitary forces late on
Sunday after the president swore in Sope and four others as an
interim government.
   Baxter-Wright said the letter urged members of the security
forces to switch their loyalty from Lini to the Sope administration,
or risk losing their jobs. It also allegedly said military
intervention could be used in Vanuatu to disarm and dismantle the
police force and the Vanuatu Mobile Force.
   Baxter-Wright likened this to an act of treason.
   In his ruling Cooke said it was ``a sad day'' for him to have to
deal with a case against the president. The judge said the charges
were among the most serious possible in Vanautu. ``I cannot flinch
from doing my duty, otherwise I should not be here.''
   The rebel politicians also have been ordered held in police
custody for the next two weeks. The parliament on Tuesday moved to
dismiss Sokomanu as head of state, accusing him of gross misconduct.
   Vanuatu has a population of 130,000 and is 1,200 miles northeast
of Brisbane, Australia.
</TEXT>
