<HEAD>Toyota to Export Its U.S.-Built Cars to Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Corp., Japan's largest automaker, said
Wednesday it will begin exporting U.S.-made Toyota passenger cars to
Taiwan in January.
   The company will send 300 Camry sedans a month to Taiwan from the
Toyota plant in Georgetown, Ky., said a Toyota official.
   He said Toyota also will export 100 Corolla sedans a month to
Taiwan starting in March. The Corollas are made in Fremont, Calif.
by the New United Motor Manufacturing Inc., a Toyota joint venture
with General Motors Corp.
   Taiwan banned imports of passenger cars from Japan in 1974 to
reduce its trade deficit with Japan, which was $4.8 billion last
year.
   The Toyota official said the Georgetown plant produces 5,500 cars
a month and the Fremont plant 10,000 cars a month.
