<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1331EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ColombianJudge Bjt   12-21 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombian Judge, Bjt,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Threatened With Death By Drug Traffickers, Prosecutor Gains U.S.
Asylum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colombian judge who said he was kidnapped, shot
at and threatened with death for prosecuting members of the
country's powerful drug cartels has been granted political asylum in
the United States after a three-year struggle.
   In a case that suggested that ``narcotraficantes,'' or drug
traffickers, are controlling Colombia's judicial system through
intimidation, the judge last month received asylum after maintaining
he would be killed if he returned.
   State Department officials said they could not recall another
case in which a judge from an American ally was granted political
asylum in the United States.
   ``Any judge that has come into contact with anything having to do
with drugs is in danger,'' the judge said in an interview granted on
condition that his name, his whereabouts and specifics about his
past not be disclosed. He now is working at unskilled jobs, in part
to keep his whereabouts a secret.
   In the last seven years, drug traffickers in the South American
nation have killed more than 50 judges, including a dozen Supreme
Court justices, as well as a justice minister, an attorney general,
several journalists and scores of police officers and soldiers.
   The reprisals against those who challenge the drug barons, led by
the infamous Medellin cartel believed responsible for most of the
cocaine brought into the United States, have hamstrung the justice
system, the judge said.
   Few drug cases are prosecuted, he said, and Colombia's Supreme
Court last year ruled that a 1979 extradition treaty with the United
States could no longer be applied. Many judges and lawyers have
resigned and fled.
   ``Two things could be happening. Either magistrates are too
afraid or they are being bought off,'' he said through a translator.
   ``There's no question but that the narcotraficantes have tried to
bring the judicial system to a halt over the years through
intimidation and assassination,'' said a State Department official,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Judges, newspapermen _ it's a
broad-spectrum campaign to try to step on anyone who tries to crank
the society against narcotics.''
   The judge _ who handled cases in various cities as a ``roving''
magistrate with power to investigate, prosecute and adjudicate
crimes _ said he was hounded and threatened from his first drug
prosecution in Medellin.
   He said he was shot at twice, received repeated telephone death
threats and was abducted by a terrorist group. At one point, he
received government protection but suspected his bodyguards had
connections to drug traffickers.
   According to documents from his asylum proceedings, the judge
contacted the U.S. consulate in Bogota, the Colombian capital, and
came to the United States in early 1986.
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service rejected his initial
application for political asylum under the 1980 Refugee Act because
he failed to demonstrate persecution based on politics, religion,
ethnicity, membership in a social group, nationality or race.
   But in deportation hearings, a U.S. immigration judge ruled that
the Colombian judge was in danger from two leftist guerrilla
movements _ including M-19 _ with ties to drug traffickers. M-19 has
been linked to a 1985 attack on the Palace of Justice in which more
than 100 people, including 11 Supreme Court justices, were killed.
   He also ruled that the judge was persecuted as a member of a
social group _ namely, judges who prosecute drug cases _ and granted
asylum.
   ``The government can't protect its own citizens from its own
people,'' said Fernando Colon, directing attorney of the Harvard Law
School Student Practice Clinic, who handled the case. ``What it says
is drug traffickers are in control.''
   ``At least this says this is a political issue and judges are
politically persecuted for abiding by the law,'' Colon said.
   The judge said he guards his identity for fear of Colombian drug
agents in this country.
   According to the State Department, several Colombian judges,
witnesses and their families who have been involved in drug cases
have been paroled into the United States, meaning they have special
admission that can be revoked at any time.
   But government officials said most of the thousands of cases of
refugees seeking asylum because of alleged threats to their safety,
many from Central American nations such as El Salvador, are denied.
   ``All these things are matters of evidence,'' the State
Department official said. ``Otherwise everybody who ever wanted to
short-circuit the normal immigration process would be able to get in
under political asylum claims.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
