<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DoctorBackground     12-21 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Doctor Background,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Blocks Questions About Alleged Nazi Background in Malpractice
Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has barred attorneys in a malpractice
lawsuit from questioning a doctor they allege was a member of
Germany's Nazi party about his World War II activities.
   Cook County Circuit Judge Dean Sodaro ruled Tuesday that lawyers
for the plaintiff, Rahman Sheriff, may not ask Dr. Karl Siedentop,
69, about his activities before 1952.
   ``He (Sodaro) just didn't believe it was relevant to the case,''
said David Novoselsky, one of the attorneys for Sheriff.
   ``It's a reasoned ruling,'' said Neil Quinn, the attorney for
Siedentop. ``The judge made the right decision.''
   Last week, while Sodaro was on vacation, another judge issued a
gag order barring lawyers from talking about the case and sealed the
court record after Sheriff's chief lawyer, David De Jong, accused
Siedentop of being a Nazi.
   ``We've learned Dr. Siedentop joined the Hitler Youth movement in
1931 and joined the Nazi Party in 1939 and in his petition for
naturalization (as an American citizen) did not disclose he was a
Nazi,'' De Jong said before the gag order was imposed.
   De Jong said attorneys should be allowed to question Siedentop
about his past because the doctor's credibility was at issue in the
case.
   The lawsuit filed by Sheriff contends an experimental drug used
by Siedentop during an ear operation in November 1985 caused the
patient to have a series of strokes that left him virtually unable
to function.
   The lawsuit seeks damages ``in excess of $15,000,'' De Jong said.
   Under court rules, Sodaro's decision may not be appealed unless
the judge grants his permission, Novoselsky said.
   The judge Tuesday denied permission to appeal the ruling.
</TEXT>
