<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1336EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0553 12-21 0956</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0553,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sullivan Still on Track for HHS Despite Abortion Flap</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with congressmen's comment after meeting, and also
restores dropped material in top 19 grafs, picking up in 5th graf
pvs, The appointments</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Educator Louis Sullivan, a leading candidate to
head the Department of Health and Human Services, met today with
conservative Republican congressmen who said their concerns about
his views on abortion had been calmed.
   Minnesota Rep. Vin Weber said after the three-hour meeting at
Bush's transition office that Sullivan still appeared to be in line
for the post. The possibility of the nomination has been
controversial since Sullivan made comments in a newspaper interview
in favor of a woman's right to an abortion _ comments not in line
with President-elect Bush's stated views.
   ``He's not used to dealing with the press and he stumbled
badly,'' Weber told reporters. He said he was sure Sullivan could
win the support of anti-abortion groups.
   Bush was said by transition aides to be determined to move ahead
with the appointment, although no announcements were scheduled today.
   Bush advisers told Chicago transit official Samuel Skinner to
return home because announcement of his nomination as transportation
secretary was being delayed yet again while decisions on prospects
for other posts were being made.
   Sullivan met with Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, Weber and New Jersey
Rep. Christopher H. Smith, all outspoken abortion opponents, as well
as transition co-directors Robert Teeter and Craig Fuller.
   Smith, a member of the congressional Pro Life Caucus, said that
he was favorably impressed by Sullivan.
   ``We do have a man here who has said, on the record, that he
believes life begins at conception, that the taking of a human life
is wrong. And he also made the point, significantly, that he
supports a human life amendement. That to the pro-life community is
the most significant issue,'' Smith said.
   The session was part of a damage control operation mounted by the
Bush team to salvage the nomination of the man who would be the
first black named to the incoming Bush Cabinet.
   Sullivan and Bush's top aides spent much of Tuesday in talks with
anti-abortion leaders, assuring them that the medical educator's
views were in line with those held by the president-elect.
   Bush opposes abortions except in cases of incest, or rape or when
the life of the mother would be endangered by a full-term pregnancy,
and he opposes federal funding for abortions.
   Sullivan was quoted in a newspaper interview several days ago as
saying he supports the right of a woman to seek an abortion _ a
position at odds with Bush's _ but opposes the use of federal funds
to pay for it.
   The article set off an instant protest by abortion foes, but
transition officials indicated on Tuesday night they thought the
nomination was back on track.
   Moreover, a transition source noted that Sullivan has strong
backing from Bush's wife, Barbara, a friend of Sullivan and a member
of the board of Morehouse College where he is medical school
president.
   Meanwhile, congressional sources said they had been told that
Texas Air executive Fred McClure would be the new administration's
chief lobbyist in Congress. McClure worked in the White House
liaison office earlier in the Reagan administration.
   Skinner, chairman of the Northeastern Illinois Mass Transit
Authority, was called to Washington last week for an expected
announcement that was then postponed by Bush. He returned to Chicago
for the weekend, then was summoned back on Monday, then told by
transition officials his appointment would come on Tuesday.
   Transition staffers were privately joking that Skinner's trips
back and forth were giving him loads of experience with problems in
the airline industry, plus paying a dividend of frequent-flyer
mileage.
   Amid the controversy over Sullivan, Bush canceled a planned
afternoon appearance for personnel announcements, avoiding questions
from reporters about the abortion dispute.
   Instead, he issued a written statement saying he was putting
former Nevada Sen. Paul Laxalt and former Ohio Rep. Thomas Ashley on
the National Economic Commission, a panel created by Congress to
find a bipartisan strategy for cutting the huge budget deficit.
   The appointments put the commission at its full strength of 14
people. Bush emphasized Tuesday his opposition to raising taxes to
erase the red ink.
   In another development, a Reagan administration source said
Patricia Diaz Dennis, a member of the Federal Communications
Commission, appeared to be emerging as the No. 1 contender for the
job of labor secretary.
   With a self-imposed Christmas deadline for naming his Cabinet,
Bush has filled eight seats and still has six to go. If he is
selected, Sullivan would be the first black in Bush's Cabinet.
   Bush has yet to name a woman to a Cabinet post, although he has
nominated Carla Hills to be chief trade negotiator, a job that
carries Cabinet rank.
   While Bush's aides insisted that Sullivan was still the top
candidate for health and human services, anti-abortion leaders
worked furiously to derail his expected nomination.
   Rep. Bob Dornan, R-Calif., said Bush ``will rue the day'' he
picks Sullivan. Gary Bauer, a conservative leader who was President
Reagan's domestic policy adviser, said the appointment of Sullivan
would be ``politically stupid'' because it would alienate a bloc of
voters that had supported Bush.
   One anti-abortion group, the Ad Hoc Committee in Defense of Life,
issued a statement saying Sullivan's appointment would be a ``slap
in the face.''
   Sullivan's congressional supporters on Tuesday were circulating a
letter in which he said, ``I am opposed to abortion except in cases
of rape, incest and where the life of the mother is threatened. ...
My position on abortion is entirely consistent with President-elect
Bush's position.''
</TEXT>
