<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Steinberg-Doctor     12-21 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steinberg-Doctor,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Who Placed Baby With Steinberg and Nussbaum Sentenced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doctor who illegally placed a 2-day-old boy in
the home of Joel Steinberg, accused of murdering another illegally
adopted child, was sentenced Wednesday to 100 hours of community
service, fined $1,000 and put on probation for three years.
   Peter Sarosi, 35, pleaded guilty to ``unlawfully placing out a
child for adoption'' and was sentenced by Manhattan Criminal Court
Judge John Stackhouse, who could have jailed him for a year.
   Sarosi, an obstetrician and gynecologist, was arrested May 31.
Shortly afterward, he admitted that in June 1986 he arranged to have
a boy born to an unwed teen-ager placed with Steinberg and his
companion, Hedda Nussbaum.
   Police found the boy tied to a playpen and drinking spoiled milk
in Steinberg's apartment Nov. 2, 1987. They had gone there after an
emergency call to help an unconscious 6-year-old girl, Lisa
Steinberg, who died of head injuries three days later.
   Steinberg, a 47-year-old disbarred lawyer, was charged with
second-degree murder for allegedly beating Lisa to death. He denied
he hit her, but Ms. Nussbaum has testified at his trial that he told
her he ``knocked Lisa down and she didn't want to get up.''
   The boy, called Mitchell by Steinberg, was returned to his
biological mother, Nicole Smigiel, and was renamed Travis Christian
Smigiel.
   Graceann Smigiel, Nicole's mother, called the sentence
``ridiculous.''
   ``They should put him in a cell with Joel so they can renew their
friendship,'' Mrs. Smigiel said.
   Stackhouse noted in his decision that the court received two
probation reports on Sarosi. One recommended jail time and the other
suggested a sentence split between jail and probation, even though
both reports predicted that Sarosi was unlikely to be involved in
crime again.
   Paul Schechtman, counsel to Manhattan District Attorney Robert
Morgenthau, said his office had agreed to take no position on
Sarosi's sentencing. But he indicated later that prosecutors were
unhappy when Sarosi, Ms. Nussbaum's physician and a friend and
client of Steinberg's, refused to cooperate in Steinberg's
prosecution.
</TEXT>
