<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bhutto 1stLd-Writethru a0509 12-21 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bhutto, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0509,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Benazir Bhutto Says Pakistan Has No Plans To Make Nuclear Weapons</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs after 3rd pvs, ``Ending corruption...'' to
UPDATE with charges against two W. German companies. Pickup 4th pvs,
``Until Ms...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan has no plans to make nuclear
weapons but won't sign the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty unless
India does, Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto said.
   Negotiations are under way with India on an agreement not to
attack each other's nuclear facilities, she said. The two countries
have fought three wars since independence in 1947. India has tested
nuclear explosives, and Pakistan is believed capable of producing
them.
   Ending corruption and tax evasion and increasing foreign
investment are domestic priorities, the first woman to lead a Moslem
nation in modern times said in an interview Sunday night. She spoke
while traveling to her home in Rawalpindi from Islamabad where she
attended a parliamentary committee meeting.
   In West Germany, a prosecutor said today that two companies in
that country are being investigated in connection with the suspected
illegal sale to Pakistan of material that can be used in the
production of atomic weapons.
   The prosecutor also said officials have evidence that atomic
reactor equipment was illegally sold to Pakistan, India and South
Africa.
   The prosecutor, Albert Farwick, said the companies' officials
have admitted delivering technical equipment to Pakistan as recently
as the summer.
   ``We know that they delivered equipment for processing tritium
and that they delivered tritium gas,'' he said. Atomic experts say
tritium gas is used to boost the effectiveness of atomic weapons.
   Until Ms. Bhutto's populist Pakistan People's Party won the
election last month, Pakistanis had been unable to choose their
government since 1977.
   The 1977 election kept Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, her
father, in power by a landslide. Gen. Mohammed Zia ul-Haq overthrew
him soon afterward. Bhutto was convicted in a murder conspiracy and
hanged in 1979.
   Zia, a staunch U.S. ally, died in a plane crash Aug. 17, after
setting the election date. After winning that election, Ms. Bhutto
said she will continue good relations with Washington.
   On Dec. 29, Ms. Bhutto and Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of India
will meet at a summit in Islamabad of the South Asian Association
for Regional Cooperation. ``We have certain talks going on with
India whereby an agreement can be brought up on non-attack on each
other's nuclear facilities,'' she said.
   Pakistan will not sign the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, thus
opening its nuclear facilities to inspection, unless India also
accepts the document, she said. Some of Pakistan's facilities are
believed to be producing weapons-grade enriched uranium,
particularly the Kahuta uranium enrichment plant 20 miles east of
Islamabad.
   Ms. Bhutto said Pakistan does not have ``a nuclear device ... has
no intention of making a nuclear device, and that's what I can tell
you categorically.''
   India rejected several previous Pakistani offers of comprehensive
nuclear agreements, but Ms. Bhutto said the situation is changing.
``I think we're looking toward, in general, an expression worldwide
of a yearning for a rest,'' she said. ``Pakistan and India are both
a part of the world. The people of both our countries would prefer
to have an honorable peace.''
   Serious economic problems beset Pakistan, including a $12.5
billion foreign debt and hard terms from the International Monetary
Fund for help in reducing it, low foreign exchange reserves and
rampant tax evasion.
   ``At the moment we want to ... concentrate on economic growth,''
Ms. Bhutto said. ``We'd like to get (other countries) interested in
our economic growth.''
   The IMF agreement provides $1 billion of new money over three
years but requires austerity measures to reduce the foreign debt.
   Military spending takes 39 percent of the budget and Ms. Bhutto
has promised no defense cuts, so options are limited.
   IMF loans will help pay immediate bills and the government will
try to renegotiate terms of the other debt, said V.A. Jafarey, the
prime minister's financial adviser.
</TEXT>
