<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Terrorism     12-21 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Terrorism,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Expands Counter-Terrorism Reward Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration said today it will
pay up to $500,000 for information that leads to the ``prevention,
frustration or favorable resolution'' of terrorist acts against U.S.
persons or property overseas.
   The program represents an expansion of a plan in effect since
1984 under which rewards have been offered for information leading
to the arrest and conviction of the perpetrators of specific
terrorist acts.
   Rewards have been offered for six such incidents but no payments
have been made.
   State Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said the
department is distributing posters advertising the program. The
posters are printed in English, French, German, Spanish and Arabic
and will be sent to all U.S. diplomatic posts overseas.
   Persons with terrorism information should notify the nearest U.S.
embassy or consulate, Ms. Oakley said. Information received will be
handled confidentially and the identities of informants will be
protected.
</TEXT>
