<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0548 12-21 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0548,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delvalle Meeting Reagan, Bush, Shultz</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS 7 grafs new to include Reagan comments; picks up 4th
graf, Popadiuk said.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, who will meet on Thursday
with the man he recognizes as president of Panama, said today he
does not know if there will be a change in the Panamanian government
before he leaves office although ``it would be nice.''
   The White House said Eric Arturo Delvalle, recognized by the
United States as the Panamanian president, was flying to Washington
for meetings with Reagan, President-elect Bush and Secretary of
State George Shultz.
   Deputy White House Press Secretary Roman Popadiuk said Delvalle
was to meet with Reagan and Bush on Thursday. He was to arrive later
today for a meeting with Shultz.
   Popadiuk said the meeting at the White House was designed ``to
show visibly the U.S. support for the Delvalle government and for
the people of Panama.'' Delvalle has been living in hiding in Panama
since he was ousted by supporters of military strongman Manuel
Antonio Noriega and replaced by Manuel Solis Palma in February.
   Reagan, asked by a reporter if he foresaw any change in the
Noriega government before his term ends Jan. 20, said, ``I don't
have an answer to that. There is only a limited time left, and it's
quite a problem as you all know, so I don't know. It would be nice
if it could happen.''
   Asked if anything could push Noriega out, Reagan grinned at Bush,
who was sitting across the table from him at a Cabinet meeting, and
joked, ``You said Bush Noriega out?''
   When he was asked what the United States would do to help
Panamanians facing confiscation of their property by the Noriega
regime, the president replied, ``All I can tell you is that we
continue to be involved in that problem and to try to find answers
for the things that are happening. and I can't go beyond that.''
   Popadiuk said he did not know who initiated Thursday's meeting.
   The spokesman was asked about reports that Panamanians working
for United States companies in Panama were disgruntled over U.S.
economic sanctions designed to end the Noriega regime.
   ``We regret any hardship imposed on these long-term loyal
employes,'' he said. ``Noriega's actions demonstrate the great
lengths he is willing to go to find money to shore up his illegal
regime.''
   ``The United States sanctions remain in place,'' Popadiuk said.
``They were undertaken in response to the call by the Delvalle
government for economic pressure against Noriega. The sanctions will
remain in place until the Panamanian people enjoy the full benefits
of democracy.''
   ``Panama's economic problems preceded the economic sanctions,''
he said. ``The Panamanian economy was already deteriorating due to
the Noriega regime's policies.''
   When asked whether Delvalle was considering resigning, Popadiuk
said, ``That is not my understanding of it. We support his efforts
to achieve democracy in Panama, and those efforts will be
continuing.''
   ``We expect President Delvalle to come to the White House some
time tomorrow, and we expect that he will have a brief meeting with
the president,'' he said.
   He said the meeting would probably take place during the
president's regular morning briefing by his national security
adviser, Lt. Gen. Colin L. Powell, and Bush would attend.
   He said that as far as he knew it would be the first meeting
between Reagan and Delvalle.
   Popadiuk declined to ``characterize efforts that we may or may
not be undertaking'' to bring about Noriega's ouster but asserted
that ``our policy remains intact and that policy will continue.''
   The sanctions were modified on June 15 to authorize payment of
taxes and fees for health, maternity and retirement benefits for
Panamanians employed by U.S. companies and U.S.-controlled
Panamanian companies.
   On Aug. 24, another amendment authorized payment of import duties
and port fees to facilitate U.S. exports to Panama.
   Popadiuk said he did not foresee any further exceptions.
   He said that as far as he was aware Delvalle was not bringing any
new proposals.
   The U.S. sanctions have been in effect since February.
   Noriega has been indicted on drug trafficking charges by two
federal grand juries in Florida.
</TEXT>
