<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Germany-USBombing 1stLd-Writethru a0598 12-21 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-US Bombing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0598,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigation Of Two Suspects In La Belle Disco Bombing Dropped</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor said today that authorities have
dropped an investigation of two suspects in the 1986 bombing of
nightclub that killed two U.S. soldiers and led to an American
retaliatory strike against Libya.
   The U.S. soldiers were among three people killed and more than
200 injured in the April 5, 1986 attack at the La Belle discotheque,
a popular haunt of American soldiers in West Berlin.A Turkish woman
also was killed.
   Detlev Achamer, West Berlin Justice Ministry spokesman, said the
investigation of Christiane Endrigkeit and Ahmed Nawaf Hasi was
dropped because of lack of evidence. ``The participation of the
suspects in the bombing could not be determined with sufficient
certainty,'' Achamer said.
   At the time of ther arrests, Endrigkeit, 28, and Hasi, 38, were
considered prime suspects in the bombing.
   The United States charged that Libya was behind the attack. Ten
days afterward, U.S. warplanes bombed Tripoli and Benghazi in Libya
in a retaliatory raid Western diplomats say killed 100 people.
   Prosecutors originally said they suspected Endrigkeit and an
accomplice had planted the bomb at the disco for Hasi. Hasi, a
Palestinian, is serving a 14-year sentence for another terrorist
attack in West Berlin.
   Achamer said the investigation showed that Endrigkeit was in the
vicinity of where the bomb was planted shortly before it went off.
But he said authorities could not establish conclusive links betwen
her and Hasi.
   Achamer said he did not know if Endrigkeit would be freed soon.
Court records indicate she faces other, unrelated charges.
   Achamer said police suspected Hasi because the explosives used in
the La Belle attack were similar to those he used to bomb the
German-Arab Friendship Society in West Berlin in 1985 and in a
failed attack against an Israeli jetliner in London in 1986.
   Hasi's brother was convicted in the London incident.
   Some West German authorities had raised the possibility that
Syria had been behind the attack at La Belle.
</TEXT>
