<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     12-21 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Proposes Joint Team With South For Asian Games</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea on Wednesday urged South
Korea to hold talks on sending a team made up of athletes from both
countries to the 1990 Asian Games in Beijing.
   The proposal came a day after North Korea called for talks with
the South and the United States on ending confrontation on the
divided Korean peninsula.
   Kim Jong-ha, the president of the South Korean Olympic Committee,
said the proposal was outlined in a letter Wednesday from his North
Korean counterpart, Kim Yu Sun.
   North Korea called for talks in the truce village of Panmunjom in
February to discuss forming a joint team for the Asian Games,
scheduled for September 1990.
   ``The people of North Korea ardently want to see both Koreas
participate together as a single team in the games, which are
intended to promote peace and goodwill among various Asian
peoples,'' the letter said.
   South Korean officials said they were studying the proposal and
had no immediate response, but indicated they had favored such ideas
in the past.
   The two Koreas are bitter foes, with hundreds of thousands of
troops stationed along their border.
   North Korea boycotted the 1988 Olympics in Seoul because its
demand to be a co-host was rejected. The communist nation also
boycotted the 1986 Asian Games in Seoul on the grounds that Seoul
refused to form a joint team.
   Talks on clearing the way for joint parliamentary sessions to
negotiate a non-aggression pact are to resume Dec. 29.
   U.S. and Soviet forces divided the Korean peninsula when they
ended the Japanese occupation at the end of World War II in 1945.
The North invaded the south in 1950, beginning the three-year Korean
War.
   The United States, which supported the South, has about 42,000
troops stationed in the country under a mutual defense treaty. North
Korea is seeking the withdrawal of U.S. forces as part of its
proposals.
</TEXT>
