<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AgentOrange     12-21 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Agent Orange,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Names Director of Settlement Fund</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnam veteran who is director of the American
Legion's National Economic Commission was named Wednesday to
administer a $52 million social service fund created by the
settlement of the Agent Orange litigation.
   Dennis Rhoades, 44, was named executive director of the Agent
Orange Class Assistance Program by U.S. District Judge Jack B.
Weinstein, who has presided over the Agent Orange class-action
lawsuit.
   The $52 million will be distributed in grants to social service
organizations that help Vietnam veterans and their families,
including children with birth defects.
   It is part of a $240 million settlement of the lawsuit brought by
veterans exposed to the defoliant during the Vietnam War against the
chemical's makers. A portion of the settlement, $170 million, has
been allocated to the Agent Orange Veteran Payment Program, which
will provide cash payments to totally disabled Vietnam veterans and
to the wives or children of veterans who died.
   Agent Orange was sprayed over Southeast Asia during the 1960s by
the U.S. military, which hoped to deprive communist troops of crops
and cover.
   The herbicide contains the highly toxic dioxin, and veterans
contended exposure to Agent Orange caused cancer and other illnesses.
   Rhoades served in Vietnam in the Army for 15 months in 1968 and
1969. He later worked for many years on veterans issues in
government agencies including the Department of Labor, the Veterans
Administration and the White House.
   He also was executive director of the Vietnam Veterans of America
before he took his current job at the American Legion.
   Weinstein said he expects the $52 million, plus interest, to be
distributed within seven to 10 years.
   To date, the court has received more than 140 proposals from
social service organizations, which will serve as a starting point
for the program's allocation process, Weinstein said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   For more information about the program: Agent Orange Class
Assistance Program; P.O. Box 27413; Washington, D.C. 20038-7413.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
