<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     12-21 0863</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Charles will make a private visit to the
United States in late February but is expected to carry out some
official engagements, Buckingham Palace said Wednesday.
   The prince's itinerary includes stops in New York and Washington,
but the palace said no dates or details were available.
   The 40-year-old heir to the British throne will be traveling
alone, the palace said. His wife, Diana, will remain in Britain with
their sons, Prince William, 6, and Prince Harry, 4.
   Shortly after he returns to London, Charles will be off again for
a skiing vacation at the Swiss resort of Klosters, the palace said.
   Last March, an avalanche hit the prince's skiing party at
Klosters, killing his close friend, Maj. Hugh Lindsay, 36, and
seriously injuring another friend, Patty Palmer-Tompkinson, who
continues to walk on crutches.
   Diana will skip the Klosters trip as well, the palace said, but
she will join Charles for an official tour of Kuwait and the United
Arab Emirates from March 12-17.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Bob Hope singled out his favorite targets
_ U.S. presidents _ as he warmed up the audience at a 1940s-era,
USO-style show that raised $101,000 for a Colorado veterans memorial.
   ``Ronald Reagan wears a hearing aid,'' deadpanned Hope. ``He
wears it in his right ear because he doesn't want to hear from the
Left.''
   Then there was former President Gerald Ford, ``the most thrilling
golfer I've ever played with. We have 73 golf courses in Palm
Desert. He doessn't know which one he'll be playing until after his
tee shot,'' quipped Hope.
   Hope, 85, was joined onstage Tuesday night at a Lowry Air Force
Base hangar by his wife, Dolores, who sang ``I'm Dreaming of a White
Christmas.''
   About 500 people paid $250 for the dinner and show. The rest _
military personnel and veterans _ paid $25 for just the show.
   ``I saw Bob Hope in 1952 in Korea,'' said Air Force Senior Master
Sgt. George Erickson. ``It's a memory to see him again.''
   The show, held in lieu of Hope's traditional holiday tour of
armed forces bases, was designed to honor Colorado's war veterans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city councilman accused the state of
``pandering to the weird obsession'' of an ``obscenely rich woman''
by allowing tobacco heiress Doris Duke to keep pet camels at her
estate.
   ``I am outraged by the special treatment accorded this wealthy
family,'' Councilman Neil Abercrombie said in a letter Tuesday to
John Whalen, the director of the city Department of Land Utilization.
   Last week, the state Board of Agriculture unanimously agreed to
allow Duke, 75, and her adopted daughter, Charlene Gail ``Chandi''
Heffner, 35, bring pet camels from New Jersey to Hawaii for the
winter. The two-hump camels would live at Duke's ocean-front estate.
   The camels would not be subject to the 120-day state quarantine
for household pets but would be treated as cattle, allowing Duke to
keep them under a 65-day ``provisional'' quarantine, officials said.
   Abercrombie said he was especially angry because as a state
legislator he had lobbied to have guide dogs for the blind be exempt
from Hawaii's quarantine laws, but the agriculture board rejected
that.
   ``Something like that they fight, but now they're pandering to
the weird obsession of this obscenely rich woman,'' he said.
   Whalen said he would look into Abercrombie's complaints.
   Ronald Leong, Duke's attorney, said he was not familiar with
Abercrombie's letter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Raymond L. Flynn rushed to douse a burning
car with a fire extinguisher and helped direct traffic when
firefighters arrived.
   Flynn and his wife, Catherine, were leaving the Globe Corner
Bookstore, where they had made a donation to The Boston Globe Santa
Fund, when the car caught fire Tuesday.
   Grabbing a fire extinguisher from a merchant, Flynn sprayed the
car until the extinguisher was empty, then directed traffic to the
side of the street to make room for the fire trucks.
   ``Where did he come from?'' asked Sarah Weatherwax, who sells
items from a cart across the street. ``He always seems to show up at
these things.''
   ``People may think I did this for publicity,'' Flynn said later,
denying the assertion.
   Last year, Flynn rescued a handicapped person from a burning
building and intervened in a hostage crisis. And his wife said she
once saw him pull three people from a burning car.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iceland expanded its ambassadorial
corps by 5 percent and insured a higher public profile for its
diplomacy by declaring Miss World Linda Petursdottir its
``ambassador extraordinaire.''
   Miss Petursdottir, 18, who won the title in November, was given
the additional honor Tuesday by Foreign Minister Jon Hannibalsson,
along with a red diplomatic passport.
   Iceland has just 21 ambassadors, counting Miss Petursdottir, and
10 of them work in Iceland at the Foreign Ministry.
   The new ambassador, however, should be doing some traveling. The
nation's major airline, Flugleider, presented her with a year's pass
for first-class travel.
   After the ceremony in the capital, Miss Petursdottir flew to her
home village of Vopnafjordur, a fishing town of 600 residents, where
she will spend the holidays.
</TEXT>
