<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1534EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HealthContractor     12-21 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Contractor,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Contractor Seen As Pentagon Reformer Has Its Own Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The firm selected by the Pentagon to
demonstrate a model for overhauling the military's troubled health
insurance system is itself having problems and is in danger of
seeing its contract canceled, officials say.
   The Foundation Health Corp. of Sacramento, Calif., has received
two formal ``deficiency and cure notices'' _ the most recent dated
Dec. 13 _ and been given a deadline of Jan. 3 to convince the
Pentagon it can correct its problems, officials say.
   Defense Department health officials say they remain hopeful the
program can be salvaged. They express frustration because the
contractor's difficulties can be traced ``to plain old claims
processing and not to the innovative changes we made.''
   ``The contractor is having trouble processing the claims of
doctors and health professionals on a timely basis,'' adds David
Newhall, the Pentagon's principal deputy assistant secretary for
health affairs.
   Phone calls to Dr. James Schubert, the head of Foundation, were
not returned on either Tuesday or Wednesday.
   Newhall said ``The innovative changes appear to be working. We're
seeing strong doctor acceptance, strong beneficiary acceptance and
early evidence that we can save money. But we've got to correct this
other problem.''
   The award of the health contract to Foundation was announced with
great ballyhoo last January, both because of its potential size and
the sweeping nature of its terms.
   The contract was described as being worth up to $3 billion over
the next five years, and as representing the best hope yet of
reforming CHAMPUS _ the Civilian Health And Medical Program of the
Uniformed Services.
   CHAMPUS is an insurance plan that covers military dependents and
retirees when they turn to the civilian sector for care, either
because they want to use a private physician or because space is not
available in military hospitals.
   The cost of CHAMPUS has been skyrocketing in recent years and now
approaches $2.5 billion a year. To rein in those costs, the Pentagon
asked Foundation to set up a demonstration project in California and
Hawaii to prove that dependents and retirees would take advantage of
a Health Maintenance Organization, or HMO, if it were available.
   There are roughly 125,000 military dependents and retirees living
in the two states who use CHAMPUS each year. In return for agreeing
to use the doctors and hospitals specified by Foundation, those
retirees and dependents are being offered additional medical
services at lower cost.
   At the same time, the Defense Department expects to save millions
because Foundation has signed fixed-price contracts for the delivery
of care with groups of doctors, instead of continuing to pay
whatever bills are submitted by private doctors.
   Newhall says there has been much interest in the new program.
   ``CHAMPUS Prime enrollment exceeds expectations by 50 percent;
there are over 18,000 enrollees and growing,'' he says.
   ``Unfortunately, however, about 40 percent of the total claims
from providers are more than a month old. And when your doctors
don't get paid on time, you have a problem.''
   According to the latest ``cure notice,'' the Pentagon views the
company's ``lack of responsiveness ... (as) an extremely grave
situation for the government.''
   ``In other words, you have not provided the government concrete
or adequate evidence that you can deliver a technical solution to
correcting your contract deficiencies ... we believe it is
imperative that real, measureable and verifiable progress be made ...
   ``This simply means that the existing claims backlog must be
reduced and processing improved. Your failure to adequately respond
to this letter by Jan. 3, 1989, could result in the termination of
this contract for default.''
   ``It is fair to say we think the contractor understands the
seriousness of the Pentagon's stance,'' Newhall said.
   ``And the contractor appears to be moving in directions that
suggest the possibility of a continuing relationship, although that
is still by no means certain.''
   Newhall declined to speculate on what the Pentagon would do if it
ended up canceling Foundation's contract.
   ``Every attempt would be made, given the substantial successes in
all areas except claims processing, to protect the reform
initiative,'' he said. ``But it's still unclear exactly how the
department would proceed.''
</TEXT>
