<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1713EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     12-21 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least Seven Palestinians Wounded in Clashes With Troops</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and wounded at least seven
Palestinians on Wednesday during a strike by residents of the
occupied territories demanding more support from their Israeli Arab
brethren.
   The Roman Catholic Patriarch in Jerusalem called for nine days of
prayer and fasting this Christmas in solidarity with those suffering
in the year-old Palestinian uprising.
   In the West Bank, a 20-year-old Palestinian died of a gunshot
wound in the chest suffered during bitter clashes with troops in the
city of Nablus last Friday, doctors said.
   Abdul Rahman Kadura was the sixth victim of the confrontations
Friday and the 333rd Palestinian to die since the Arab uprising
began. Thirteen Israelis also have been killed.
   Three Palestinians were wounded in the village of Tubas, near
Nablus, when soldiers opened fire after they were met with a barrage
of stones and bottles upon entering the village, Arab reporters said.
   A military spokeswoman confirmed the three woundings, and said
four other Palestinian stone-throwers were shot and wounded in three
other West Bank villages.
   Arab doctors said an 18-year-old Palestinian was in serious
condition at Ahli Arab Hospital in Gaza City after he was shot in
the stomach in a clash in Nusseirat refugee camp. The report could
not immediately be confirmed by the army.
   The Christmas statement issued by Michel Sabbah, the first Arab
named as Roman Catholic patriarch of Jerusalem, spoke of ``prisons
full of suffering men, lack of peace and the entrenchment of
violence and hatred.''
   In a reference to the occupied West Bank, Sabbah noted that the
problems were occurring in the area where Christ was born. He urged
Catholics ``to accompany these sufferings with our prayers and to
focus our attention on the current situation and the political
problem itself.''
   It was the strongest public statement on the uprising by Sabbah,
who was appointed by Pope John Paul II in December.
   Sabbah is responsible for some 110,000 Roman Catholics in Israel,
the occupied territories, Jordan and Cyprus.
   Wednesday's general strike, the third this week, was called by
the pro-PLO Unified National Leadership of the Uprising to urge
Arabs living within Israel to show greater support for the revolt in
the territories.
   ``We call on them to declare a day of Palestinian peace like that
of last year,'' said a leaflet signed by the underground leadership.
On Dec. 21, 1987, thousands of Israeli Arabs demonstrated in support
of the revolt in the territories.
   Underground leaders also have called for strikes on Christmas Eve
and on the Orthodox Feast of the Epiphany Jan. 6 to oppose Israel's
continued occupation.
   Israel authorities, meanwhile, were going ahead with plans for
normal Christmas celebrations in Bethlehem despite calls by
Palestinian leaders in the city for a quiet Christmas in respect for
the uprising.
   A hotelkeeper, Michel Kratim, said that only one-third of the 120
beds in his Star Hotel were booked for Christmas this year. He said
some of Bethlehem's nine hotels and guest houses have no bookings at
all for the holidays.
   Also Wednesday, four Israeli soldiers including a woman were
sentenced to jail terms of up to nine months for beating
Palestinians at the Dhahiriya detention camp in the occupied West
Bank, the army said.
   The indictment against the four listed 22 beating incidents at
Dhahiriya in March.
</TEXT>
