<DOCNO> AP881221-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1715EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WhaleFound     12-21 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whale Found,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquarium Officials Trying to Save Stranded Newborn Whale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veterinarians at the New York Aquarium said
Wednesday that a baby female pilot whale found stranded in shallow
water near a marina has little chance of surviving.
   Aquarium spokesman Rick Miller said the animal _ which may be as
young as 2 weeks _ was under constant care and being fed a rich
mixture of infant formula, heavy cream, cottage cheese and vitamins.
   He said aquarium officials knew of no baby long-finned pilot
whale surviving after being separated from its mother. The mammals
often nurse for 14 to 16 months, meaning veterinarians must force
feed the young whale through a tube.
   ``In this case, the newborn whale is showing signs of pneumonia
and weight loss,'' said aquarium director Louis Garibaldi.
   Should the whale survive and recover, Miller said, experts would
try to return it to the ocean.
   The young animal was found Tuesday morning stranded in shallow
water at the Barren Island Marina in Marine Park in Brooklyn, about
a mile from the open ocean.
   Marina owner Ted Sunday, who waded into the knee-deep cold water
to help the whale, said, ``It was making a very, very sad sound like
a weeping, like a whining sound. That's what prodded me to stay in
the water a little longer.''
   Sunday said he urged the whale into slightly deeper water and
stayed with it until an aquarium crew arrived.
   Whale experts at the aquarium had no way of knowing what happened
to the whale's mother, but speculated she may have rejected her
offspring or perhaps gotten sick and died. It was also possible the
baby whale had become ill and was unable to keep up with other
whales.
   Pilot whales are common along the East Coast and range as far
north as Greenland and south to North Carolina, Miller said. The
young whale found Tuesday was about 6 feet long, but fully grown
females grow to as much as 20 feet. A fully grown male may reach 28
feet in length, Miller said.
</TEXT>
