<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ortega     12-21 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ortega,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Hands Out Christmas Toys to Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega on Wednesday
handed out thousands of Christmas toys to poor children in
shantytowns.
   In the neighborhood of Acalhualinca, some 2,000 children, many of
them in tattered shorts and barefoot, waited in long lines on a dirt
field for the gifts. The girls received dolls or a plastic tea set,
while the boys grabbed for plastic rifles and trucks.
   The $1 million in toys came from profits from government-run hard
currency stores, officials said. The 14 stores nationwide sell goods
ranging from basic foods to stereos for dollars only. Most items
sold are rarely found in the common markets.
   The toys, wrapped in plastic with writing in English, were made
in Taiwan, a country that does not maintain diplomatic relations
with Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   The Sandinistas, who came to power almost a decade ago, have been
making a push this year to show there is no contradiction between
leftist revolution and Christianity.
   The opposition newspaper La Prensa on Tuesday printed a headline
saying, ``Sad Christmas; Cardinal Asks For Faith.''
   The Nicaraguan economy has never been worse. Private estimates
put the annual inflation at more than 20,000 percent, highest in the
world. Ortega recently acknowledged that figure could be correct.
   New economic measures were expected to be announced in the next
two weeks. A series of plans designed to right the situation failed
to pull the bankrupt nation out the mire.
   Despite up to $500 million in Soviet bloc aid, the average worker
earns only about $10 a month. A Christmas dinner of chicken and rice
for a family would be a day's pay.
   The government blames the economic crisis on the seven-year war
with U.S.-backed Contra rebels. Little is said about corruption and
mismanagement.
   The war activity diminished substantially after the March 23
cease-fire talks, but fighting continues in the countryside.
   ``Until we solve the political problems we can't solve the
economic ones,'' Francisco Taboada, a leader of the Social Christian
Party, said in an interview Tuesday night. ``People need guarantees
their land won't be confiscated. There's no confidence.''
   Taboada, a neurologlist, said Christmas would be sad for the tens
of thousands of Nicarguans whose families fled to the United States.
   ``No matter how much money they send back home, that can't
compensate for the saddness,'' he said.
   On Wednesday, few of the children receiving gifts appeared to
think about such sadness. About 14,500 were to be handed presents by
Ortega, who wore a green military uniform.
   ``This is so nice,'' said Lester Enrique Lopez, eyeing his new
plastic rifle.
   Socorro Mejia, 27, held her 2-year-old son and walked with her
five other children, all carrying toys.
   ``This is happiness for the children,'' she said.
   Blanca Rosa Cuba Dias held her gift of doll dishes tightly and
caressed the plastic wrapping.
   ``I never had anything so nice,'' she sighed.
</TEXT>
