<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--WhiteHouse     12-21 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--White House,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Certified As Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House has been accredited officially
as a museum.
   The American Association of Museums, whose 2,300 member
institutions include art museums, zoos and historic homes, said the
White House had met ``the highest standards of management and
operations'' to qualify for accreditation.
   Only 673 of the more than 6,500 museums across the country meet
the association's stringent, detailed criteria for this recognition,
said association executive director Edward Able.
   Able said the White House was honored for its conservation,
interpretation and management of its historic collection of fine
arts, including paintings, sculpture, furnishings and decorative
pieces by American and European artists.
   The museum areas of the Executive Mansion consist mainly of the
ground-floor corridor and first-floor state rooms open to public
tours, Able said, but also include the diplomatic reception room and
other private areas.
   Official recognition of the president's home as a museum followed
a two-year process involving evaluation of thousands of objects in
the collection by the White House staff, a visit by an AAM
accreditation team and a review by an AAM committee of leading
museum professionals.
</TEXT>
