<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0605,0902</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coalition Agreement Ratified, New Government Assured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with signing planned, religious
parties join. Pick up 7th pvs, ``Under the... ADDS 2 grafs at end
with details.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The right-wing Likud bloc and the center-left
Labor Party voted at separate meetings Wednesday to approve a joint
coalition, assuring a new national unity government after seven
weeks of inter-party haggling.
   Both Likud's Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Labor's Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres faced opposition from within their parties
before winning approval for the accord. Shamir's opponents accused
him of selling out Israel's security, and some Labor members told
Peres he was dealing a death blow to the peace process.
   Both leaders told their parties that a unity government was
crucial to withstand the challenges facing Israel, especially the
PLO's recent declaration of an independent Palestinian state and the
U.S. decision to open a dialogue with the organization.
   ``If a joint government with Likud and Labor had not been
established, this process of isolation and conflict with the world
would have persisted,'' Peres told his supporters. ``By building
such a government, such a process will be halted.''
   The government announced a special session on Thursday of the
Knesset, or parliament, for installation of the new government. The
two parties will formally sign the pact before the ceremony, Likud
officials said.
   Three of Israel's four religious parties, the Orthodox Agudat
Israel, the Torah Flag, and the National Religious Party, said late
Wednesday they would join the new government. But they will be
secondary to the major parties and will lack the influence they
sought _ and thought they had won _ in a narrow coalition with Likud.
   Under the new agreement, worked out after seven weeks of haggling
among all parties who won votes in Nov. 1 elections, Shamir will
retain his post for the next four years. Peres, the current foreign
minister, will serve as finance minister.
   Moshe Arens, a close Shamir ally and former defense minister as
well as former ambassador in Washington, will be foreign minister.
   Other key portfolios will remain the same, including Labor's
Yitzhak Rabin as defense minister and Likud's Ariel Sharon as
industry minister.
   Each of the two large parties will have 11 ministers, but the
Cabinet could number up to 25 if the religious parties join.
   Labor and Likud have ruled Israel in an uneasy coalition since
1984, when stalemated elections gave neither party a mandate. A
similar stalemate resulted from the latest elections but Likud
gained a slight edge, winning 40 seats to Labor's 39. The rest of
the votes were split among smaller parties.
   In a decision certain to create friction with Washington, the two
parties agreed specifically to ban contacts with the Palestine
Liberation Organization, which Israel views as a terrorist group.
Israeli leaders were stunned last week when the United States
reversed a 13-year ban on talking to the group.
   Other government policies are expected to resemble those of the
old coalition as well.
   The Labor Party's 1,275-member Central Committee voted by an
overwhelming show of hands in favor of the coalition at a meeting in
the Tel Aviv suburb of Givatayim.
   Peres vowed he would try to revive the Middle East peace process
although he would no longer be foreign minister.
   ``The flag of the peace process remains in our hands, it has
nothing to do with a ministry,'' Peres said. He indicated he would
strive for a territorial compromise with Palestinians in the
occupied lands, which Israel captured in the 1967 Middle East War.
Likud strongly opposes trading land for peace.
   ``The Labor party prefers a Jewish majority to territories,'' he
said. ``We prefer peace.''
   Younger legislators countered that Labor, in its weakened
position, would be unnable to overcome Likud's objections to its
peace initiatives.
   ``You once called Yitzhak Shamir the murderer of peace, now he
has three lawyers on his team so he can murder it again,'' Labor
legislator Chaim Ramon was quoted by Israel radio as saying.
   The Haaretz newspaper said that according to the pact, Peres
would have to be consulted on all major foreign policy issues.
   Likud approved the new pact in secret balloting at an all-night
meeting in Tel Aviv. The party said 55.1 percent of 1,445 party
delegates voted for the agreement.
   Leading the opposition in Likud was Sharon, who argued that
Israel needed a tougher government to quell the year-long uprising
by Palestinians in the occupied territories, in which more than 330
Palestinians and 13 Israelis have been killed.
   Sharon argued that Labor's conciliatory policies were ``a danger
to Israel's future and security.''
   The new coalition agreement, as published by the Haaretz daily
newspaper, contains a new feature that would bar either Labor of
Likud from pulling out and forming a narrow coaliton with smaller
factions.
   New elections would have to be held if the government were
toppled by a no-confidence motion in parliament, the paper quoted
the agreement as saying.
   Shamir said on Israel Television that the includes a secret
amendment ``regulating the relations between two party heads,'' but
would not elaborate.
   Likud officials have accused Peres of acting behind Shamir's back
in the outgoing government to push his own peace proposals.
</TEXT>
