<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Extremists     12-21 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Extremists,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Blames Moslem Extremists for More Than 100 Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem extremists fighting for strict
adherence to Islamic laws were responsible for more than 100 violent
attacks recently, the interior minister said Wednesday.
   The minister, Zaki Badr, said the religious extremists have
desecrated mosques by using them as arms depots and centers of drug
trafficking, according to the state-run Middle East New Agency.
   Police in Cairo killed three extremists in a shootout Monday,
including the suspected assassin of a police officer in Cairo's Ein
Shams district earlier this month.
   At a mosque in Ein Shams, security sources said 32 bottles of
incendiary materials were found last week. There also have been
reports of firecracker explosions at two Coptic Christian churches
in Cairo.
   ``The security apparatus has monitored more than 100 attacks by
religious extremists throughout the republic,'' the agency quoted
Badr as saying. He said they set fire to shops, pharmacies and cars
and attacked Moslem and Christian houses of worship. The interior
minister gave no dates for the attacks.
   Badr's remarks followed a recent crackdown on Moslem extremists
in Ein Shams, where two police officers and three civilians have
been killed since August in unrest linked to the fundamentalists.
Since then, more than 300 extremists have been detained.
   The government said most were affiliated with the Jihad
underground group blamed for the assassination of President Anwar
Sadat on Oct. 6, 1981, and a subsequent coup attempt.
   Badr said security forces are ``mopping up all criminal dens and
have been able to clean the Ein Shams district of the extremists who
tried to control it and to prevent wedding and death observances.''
   The Moslem groups consider wedding festivities and traditional
funeral ceremonies as anti-Islamic.
   Moslem extremists are using violence to demand the strict
implementation of Sharia, Islam's legal and ethical code.
   ``They have turned mosques into storehouses for arms and
ammunition and used them for attacks and for trading in narcotics of
all kinds for the benefit of those who use religion as a screen,''
said Badr.
   In the southern city of Assiut, a center of fundamentalist
activity, clashes have been reported at mosques in recent months.
The Assiut University campus has been the site of many clashes
between police and fundamentalist students. Badr estimated there
were more than 800 extremists among the more than 45,000 students.
   ``The extremists have turned some mosques _ no more than 25 out
of 70,000 mosques nationwide _ into dens from which to mount their
crimes against the people,'' Badr said, according to the news agency.
   Badr was quoted as saying he has the legal power to order the
demolition of buildings used as centers of crime. But he ruled out
such action against mosques ``because we are a devout Moslem
nation.''
   Mosques also have been used as battlegrounds between the
extremists and moderate fundamentalists from the Moslem Brotherhood,
which has 35 seats in parliament and is using peaceful methods to
insist on the observance of Sharia. The government says more than 90
percent of Egyptian laws already conform to Sharia and the rest will
be implemented gradually.
   Badr made his remarks in a speech to a committee of the Shura
Council, a consultative body of elders that works alongside the
People's Assembly, or parliament, but has no legislative powers.
</TEXT>
