<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Soviet-Kennan     12-21 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Kennan,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kremlin Expert Likens Gorbachev's Reforms to Bolshevik Revolution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A noted expert on the Soviet Union, George
Kennan, said in an interview broadcast Wednesday that Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's reforms mark ``the greatest turning point'' in Russia
since the Bolshevik Revolution and are a big help to the United
States.
   ``I think it is greatly in our interest, when he is doing all the
things that we have always wanted someone to do in Russia,'' said
Kennan, who as U.S. ambassador to Moscow was declared persona non
grata in 1952 under Kremlin strongman Josef Stalin.
   ``In my opinion, Gorbachev's reforms in concept were sound and
correct and if carried through will lead to a very important
improvement in Soviet life,'' Kennan said on the ``MacNeil@Lehrer
NewsHour.''
   Kennan, 84, called Gorbachev's reforms ``the greatest turning
point, really, not only since the Second World War but since the
Russian Revolution'' in 1917.
   The ideological basis of Soviet foreign policy, he said, has
``entirely disappeared. No one in Russia today dreams of trying to
implement world revolution in our time, or even to stage any
communist revolutions in any of the Western countries.''
   Kennan said he hoped the Bush administration would recognize that
Moscow was less threatening than in the past.
   ``I would like to hope, of course, that the men around Mr. Bush
and Mr. Bush himself saw things this way, too, and realized that the
Cold War is, really has been left in the past,'' he said.
   Gorbachev's reforms thus far have not improved living conditions
for the Soviet people and as a result, the Soviet leader's
``position today is very precarious because he has had hard luck and
a lot of things have gone adversely and he is being blamed for
them.''
   One of the biggest obstacles to successful reforms in Russia,
said Kennan, was the ``moral damage'' inflicted on most Soviet
people during the Stalinist years of terror and the period of
stagnation under Leonid I. Brezhnev, 1964-82.
   ``You have a deplorable and pathetic situation (with) these
people, for they've lived all their lives under authoritarian
discipline and control. They've been deprived of even the idea that
they could ever change their situation by their own indiviual
initiative and now while they are confronted with the possibility of
what you might call freedom, they have no ide how to take advantage
of it.''
   Kennan said he was unable to explain how such a daring leader as
Gorbachev rose through the ranks of the highly disciplined Soviet
Communist Party during the Brezhnev years to carry out sweeping
reforms of the system.
   ``Numbers of us who have known that country for a long time
simply stand without explanation as to how a man with those
qualities could have emerged from a provincial party apparatus,''
Kennan said.
   The main impetus for change, said Kennan, was ``the realization
on the part of many intelligent people in the Soviet Union in these
recent years of the fact that the whole system was going downhill,
that it was no longer competitive, that the capitalist countries
were going far beyond it.''
   ``The change, after all, has been a change inspired and carried
out from the top, from the upper reaches of the political society
and not really from the bottom. It is these people who saw how
inadequate the system was and who have tried to take action to
change it.''
</TEXT>
