<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Religion 1stLd-Writethru a0645 12-21 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Religion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0645,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Who is a Jew' Law a Victim of Coalition Pact</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with 3 religious parties joining
govt. Pick up 6th pvs, ``Likud won...''; DELETES 17th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decision by Israel's two major parties to
join a coalition has edged the ultra-Orthodox parties from a
posiiton of influence and effectively killed the chances of the
``Who is a Jew'' law that incensed U.S. Jews.
   Although the religious parties emerged from Nov. 1 elections as
kingmakers with control of a crucial bloc of parliament seats, they
drove themselves out of the market by setting too high a price for
their support.
   The price _ a package that included the legislation _ threatened
to alienate Jews abroad, who are Israel's mainstay of support.
   Three of Israel's four religious parties decided to join the
government led by the center-left Labor and the right-wing Likud.
But experts said the new coalition essentially counts religious
parties out of major policy decisions.
   ``This is a revolution,'' said Shmuel Sandler of the Jerusalem
Center for Public Affairs.
   Likud won 40 members in the 120-member parliament, while Labor
won 39. The 18 seats won by the religious parties gave them a
powerful swing vote.
   In the seven weeks of squabbling following the stalemated
elections, the religious parties ran back and forth between the
major blocs, often arguing between themselves over the same
government posts.
   Finally, Likud and Labor settled their differences, leaving room
for the Orthodox to join but not requiring their support.
   The most controversial demand made by the religious parties was a
change in the definition of who is eligible for automatic
citizenship under Israel's unique Law of Return, which opens the
country's doors to any Jew.
   The Orthodox wanted to exclude any person who converted to the
faith under a non-Orthodox rabbi. Most U.S. Jews are not Orthodox.
   Jews overseas launched what many called an unprecedented campaign
to convey their anger to leaders of Likud and Labor, who were wooing
the religious parties with a promise to pass the law.
   ``The pressure from the diaspora made political leaders in Israel
recognize ... that diaspora Jews care deeply about what Israel
does,'' said Rabbi Richard G. Hirsch, executive director of the
World Union for Progressive Judaism.
   ``It also made them recognize that there is no Jewish people
without the Jewish state, and no Jewish state without the Jewish
people, and the Law of Return is symbolic of that.''
   The turning point came when the United States reversed its
position against talks with the Palestine Liberation Organization,
which is banned in Israel as a terrorist group.
   Analysts say Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir realized he needed a
broad and unified government to withstand international pressure to
make concessions to the Palestinians.
   ``Shamir couldn't wage a war on two fronts,'' said Prof. Menachem
Friedman, a Bar Ilan University sociologist specializing in
religious affairs. ``It would not be smart to get into a fight, or
even cause tension with U.S. Jewry and reduce their motivation to
support Israel.''
   Labor leader Shimon Peres said the new pact ``brings an end to
the change in the Law of Return.'' The new government will ``keep
the Jewish people united,'' he said.
   Religious party leaders reacted with anger when they were
informed Likud would not keep its commitments because of the broad
government with Labor.
   ``Even the Mafia keeps its promises,'' Rabbi Yitzhak Peretz, of
the Orthodox Shas party told the Maariv newspaper.
   Some analysts said they hope Labor and Likud, free of the
religious parties, will pass a bill reforming the country's complex
elections system that often leaves small parties in positions of
power.
   The religious parties already have expressed vehement opposition,
however, and the tradition of their participation in the government
may not disappear so easily.
</TEXT>
