<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     12-21 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An onion a day keeps the doctor away?
   John Houston celebrated his 102nd birthday Tuesday, and relatives
said he's lived so long because he ate an onion a day nearly all his
life.
   Victoria Jobe, one of his four living children, said her father
ate a medium-sized onion each night at dinner.
   ``He would eat it like an apple, full of salt,'' she said. ``He
loves them. He just truly loves them.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People scalp tickets all the time, reasoned
Susan Stein, so why not scalp a place in class?
   The graduate student at the University of Nebraska-Lincoln did
just that to get into a class she needed.
   During early registration she discovered a seminar's 12 positions
were filled. That's when she ran an advertisement in the Daily
Nebraskan, the university newspaper.
   ``If you got in this class next semester,'' the ad read, ``I'll
buy your place.''
   ``State your price.''
   Ms. Stein struck a deal with an unidentified person and she's in
the class. She didn't divulge details of the transaction.
   While her ad raised a few eyebrows, Ms. Stein said she had heard
that the practice went on at other colleges.
   ``I think I took everybody off guard. No one (here) had heard of
paying for a class space before,'' she said.
   Ted Pfeiffer, director of registration and records at the
university, said buying a spot isn't illegal and there isn't any
regulation that prohibits it.
   Pfeifer said instructors usually set the size of a class and many
times agree to add students, particularly if the student's need
appears to be urgent.
   ``I guess it says a lot about the power of advertising,'' Ms.
Stein said.
</TEXT>
