<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LittleCommissioner     12-21 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Little Commissioner,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>7-Year-Old Joins City Youth Commission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7-year-old whiz kid who worked for the
re-election of a city councilman has learned how the spoils system
works, receiving an appointment to the city Youth Commission.
   Teddy Andrews still has a ways to go in the political world,
however. At his swearing-in Tuesday, he was asked how he liked the
press conference.
   ``What's a press conference?'' responded the youngest of some 400
people who serve Berkeley on 43 boards and commissions.
   The boy, who has attended one year of school but became bored and
is now studying subjects such as physics and paleontology at home.
He learned Chinese from a University of California-Berkeley physics
student, an ability he put to work on behalf of Councilman Don
Jelinek.
   ``He gave speeches in Chinese, he went door to door. He ended up
being `Don's campaign manager.' He devoted 10-12 hours a day,'' said
the boy's mother, Alexandra Andrews. ``They told me I could get
lost, just as long as I left them Teddy.''
   ``I originally thought that would be a pain we'd have to
tolerate. Was I ever wrong,'' said Jelinek. ``He did everything. He
was a very dedicated worker, then after the campaign he wrote
thank-you notes in Chinese and Korean to non-English speakers who
helped us.''
   The nine-member Youth Commission, appointed by City Council,
meets monthly and advises the council on youth issues.
   ``I decided it would make a great appointment,'' Jelinek said.
``Here's a rare opportunity to have the wisdom of someone who is
physically 7 years old but has a mental and intellectual age of
someone 10 years older.''
   Teddy hasn't made any major promises but said he wants to work to
fix the bathrooms at a park a few blocks from his home in a
residential hotel where he lives with his mother, a single parent
who works several part-time jobs.
   He said he also wants to make it easier for homeless children to
go to school.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
