<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CARE-Soviets     12-21 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CARE-Soviets,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CARE, Junior Chamber Boost Earthquake Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CARE and the Junior Chamber of Commerce are
boosting efforts to assist survivors of the earthquake that
devastated Soviet Armenia, the groups announced at the Soviet
Embassy on Wednesday.
   ``By Christmas Day, 30,100 CARE packages will have reached
earthquake-effected areas,'' said Philip Johnston, executive
director of CARE. The relief agency has already shipped 20,000 CARE
packages to the Soviet Armenia and plans to send a total of 50,000,
he said.
   To help fund the CARE effort, Junior Chamber International has
asked its worldwide organization to raise $1 million, with half that
amount to come from its U.S. affiliate, known as the Jaycees.
   ``During the holidays, almost 5,000 Jaycee chapters across
America are running food, toy and clothing drives to assist those
less fortunate,'' Jaycee President Andy Tobin told the embassy news
conference.
   ``It is in the spirit of Christmas cooperation, not charity, that
I'm asking all Jaycee chapters to donate a minumum of $90 to $150
immediately to CARE,'' he said.
   Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin said the Soviet people ``are
deeply moved by the assistance rendered by the Americans ... I am
sure a new kind of internationalism is being born.''
   The Armenian earthquake has shown that it may be ``necessary to
create an international organization to provide assistance'' to the
victims of major disasters, he said.
   The Soviet government plans to discuss such a new organization in
bilateral talks with the United States and also in the United
Nations, said Dubinin, but ``it is too early for me to specify what
would be the concrete ideas.''
   In the past, the Soviets have played a minor role in providing
aid to natural disaster victims. But Johnston, who has spent 26
years in CARE, said that in recent years the Soviets have helped
provide famine relief in the African nations of Ethiopia and Chad.
   Dubinin denied accusations by some Soviet newspapers that
confusion in the Armenian assistance effort showed that the Kremlin
learned little from relief efforts following the partial meltdown of
a nuclear reactor at Chernobyl in the Ukraine in 1986.
   ``I think that the differences (between Chernobyl and Armenia)
are much more important than the similarities,'' said Dubinin.
   U.S. aid to victims of the earthquake has topped $10 million,
according to figures kept by the Office of Foreign Disaster
Assistance in the Agency for International Development.
   As of Wednesday, the U.S. government had sent $1,909,451 worth of
aid, in the form of medicine, rescue teams, hard hats, work gloves,
plastic sheeting, tents and other goods, said Faye Henderson, a
spokeswoman for OFDA.
   Additionally, American volunteer agencies had reported sending
$8,249,439 worth of goods and services, she said, estimating that
the total would climb as further assistance is reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
