<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RescueShip     12-21 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rescue Ship,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sailors Rescued From Sinking Ship Heading Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE OWEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLOUCESTER CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Their belongings lost at sea, the
captain and 20 crewmen of a Greek cargo ship awaited travel
arrangements home Wednesday after being rescued in lifeboats 400
miles south of Bermuda.
   ``I feel very bad,'' said Chionis Gerasimos, a 30-year sailor and
captain of the Stark, which was abandoned Saturday after it began
sinking. ``I try again. I am seaman.''
   The Sea Merchant, a German ship bound for Philadelphia, rescued
the crew in 10-foot waves.
   The German vessel docked in Philadelphia on Tuesday, and the
rescued sailors spent the night at a motel here. Fifteen were
scheduled to leave Wednesday, with officers staying behind for a few
days to talk with lawyers.
   ``I have to say thanks to my captain,'' said Mihalis Vranas, the
ship's cook. ``He was the last one to leave the ship. A big thanks
to the German ship and to all the crew, who was very kind to us.''
   The Stark, loaded with 7,850 metric tons of dry beans, was en
route from Pensacola, Fla., to Algeria when a cargo hold began
taking on water, officials said.
   Gerasimos said the crew tried to pump the water out but could not
save the ship. He said he did not know what caused the leak.
   James Young, agent for the ship, said said he knew of no salvage
plans and that he heard the ship was sinking. The Coast Guard
stopped monitoring the ship, said Lt. Cmdr. Paul Milligan.
   Young had no overall loss estimate but said the ship probably was
worth about $1.5 million.
   The crew members _ 15 Greeks, two Ghanians and one each from
Yugoslavia, Peru, Ecuador and Syria _ left the ship with only the
clothes on their backs, in some cases without jackets.
   ``We lost everything,'' said Gerasimos. ``Most of my crew had all
bought things for their homes.''
</TEXT>
