<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DeLorean     12-21 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-De Lorean,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Company to Set Up Operation in Former De Lorean Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Nothern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French auto parts maker is to
set up operations in the former De Lorean Motor Car Co. plant, in
what is the biggest foreign investment in Northern Ireland, it was
announced Wednesday.
   The French company, Montupet, is to invest $164 million and
create about 1,000 jobs in the next five years at the west Belfast
plant, which has been vacant since 1982, the Industrial Development
Board said.
   Montupet is to set up a state-of-the-art aluminum casting
operation in the 500,000-square-foot factory, the board said.
   ``The investment is the biggest ever secured by the IDB and the
largest initial investment yet made by an overseas company in
Northern Ireland,'' said Tony Hopkins, the board's chief executive.
   The aluminum foundry is expected to come on line in 1990 and
employ 920 workers, the board said.
   Montupet also is to employ 110 workers at a tool room to be built
at another site, yet to be determined.
   Much of the production will be cylinder heads for Ford Motor Co.,
Montupet's major customer, the board said.
   Montupet, which had sales of $182 million in 1987, has plants in
France, Canada and Spain and also supplies European car makers.
   The plant has been mothballed by the industrial board since 1982,
after U.S. automaker John Z. De Lorean, a former General Motors Co.
executive, encountered financial difficulties.
   The De Lorean car plant, which was established in 1978 and built
with backing from the British government, turned out more than 8,500
gull-winged sports cars and it employed more than 2,600 workers at
its peak.
   Last month, Daewoo Electronics Ltd. announced plans to establish
a $33 million video cassette recorder plant 20 miles northwest of
Belfast.
   The secretary of state for Northern Ireland, Tom King, called it
``more good news for jobs in Northern Ireland at the end of a year
that has seen a substantial fall in unemployment,'' King said.
   Unemployment in Northern Ireland stands at 15.9 percent against
an average for the whole of Britain of 7.5 percent. The higher
figure in Northern Ireland is due partly to the Irish Republican
Army's bomb and bullet war to end British rule in the province.
   The loss of the government's stake of about $140 million in the
De Lorean enterprise in Northern Ireland when it went broke in 1982
prompted widespread criticism of the British officials responsible
for overseeing the investment.
</TEXT>
