<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1944EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Spying     12-21 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Spying,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Rejects Appeal in U.S. Military Spy Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court Wednesday rejected an appeal by two Japanese
convicted of stealing and selling U.S. military documents to Soviet
and Chinese officials, a court official said.
   Masateru Tachibana, 61, and Hiromi Date, 64, were found guilty
March 22 of taking the documents from the U.S. Air Force base in
Yokota, west of Tokyo. The Tokyo District Court sentenced them to 2{
years in prison each, and fined Date $8,000.
   On Wednesday, High Court Judge Takashi Sakamoto upheld the
sentences, said the court official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The documents dealing with aircraft maintenance were
declassified, ``but the value of the information is high and the
previous ruling is justified,'' the high court said.
   Tachibana and Date can appeal to the Supreme Court within 14
days, the court official said.
   Tachibana and Date were arrested in May 1987, along with Hiroshi
Osumi and Sadao Gotoh.
   Osumi, 67, was charged with stealing the documents from the
Yokota base library, where he worked, and selling them to Tachibana
for $74,400 between April 1986 and May 1987. Osumi was convicteed by
the District Court and sentenced to two years in prison.
   Tachibana, a military writer and former employee at another U.S.
air base in Japan, sold the documents to Date and Gotoh for $560,000.
   Date, who worked for a Chinese technical center, and Gotoh,
president of Sanko Ltd., a trading company doing business with
China, were charged with selling the information in the documents to
a Soviet official in Japan and a Chinese official in China.
   The District Court convicted Gotoh, 62, sentenced him to 18
months in prison and fined him $1,600. Osumi and Gotoh did not
appeal.
   Japan has no anti-espionage laws. The maximum penalty for theft
in Japan is 10 years in prison, and for purchase of stolen goods 10
years and a $1,600 fine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
