<1ST_LINE>u i AM-CrashScene     12-21 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash Scene,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses Describe Sky Raining Fire In Jumbo Jet Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Britain-Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The night sky rained fire over a Scottish village
Wednesday after a Pan Am jumbo jet crashed with 258 people aboard,
setting buildings and cars ablaze.
   ``There was a terrible explosion and the whole sky lit up and the
sky was actually raining fire. It was just like liquid,'' said Mike
Carnahan, who was a few hundred yards from the scene.
   Witnesses said the plane hit a gasoline station.
   ``All I could see was flames and fire,'' Carnahan told British
Broadcasting Corp. television in a telephone interview. ``I could
see several houses on the skyline whose roofs were totally off, and
all you could see was flaming timbers and what was left of the
houses.''
   Another eyewitness, hotelier Graham Byerley, told the BBC:
   ``We initially heard a rumbling over the hotel. We thought the
roof was falling in, and then we heard a tremendous shudder on the
ground as though it were an earthquake, and then we saw sparks and
this enormous flame going 200 or 300 feet into the air. There was
debris flying everywhere.''
   Rescue helicopters buzzed overhead and firefighters fought the
flames.
   Police and rescue vehicles were held up by traffic as roads
leading to the site became jammed with motorists trying to get a
glimpse of the disaster.
   ``There's a lot of rescue services trying to get to the area but
the roads are blocked solid with cars and sightseers going over
toward the scene of the crash,'' Cranahan said.
   He said he believed the plane was on fire before it crashed
because ``it was trailing flames when it went over the village.''
   Witness John Glasgow said the crash and explosion littered
streets with debris.
   ``The whole road was ablaze. Two houses were blazing. The road
was completely covered with masonry, garden gates and apparently
parts of the plane, but not very big parts,'' Glasgow told
Independent Radio News. ``There was a lot of smoking debris on fire.
It looked as if the road as burning.''
   ``We tried to get near the plane but it was completely on fire.
There were no bodies about. I don't think there would be any chance
... It went up in a fireball.''
   Glasgow said the aircraft hit a road, kept going for about 1,500
yards and then exploded.
   The plane was bound from London to New York when it crashed.
</TEXT>
