<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bush-Hispanics     12-21 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Hispanics,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says `No Shift in Direction' on Latin Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush told a group of prominent
Hispanic-Americans Wednesday there would be no ``radical shift in
direction'' as his new administration takes office.
   Bush, in a meeting with more than 40 Republicans of Hispanic
origin, also said Nicaragua ``continues to plague me.'' One of the
group's participants said Bush promised that he would not abandon
the Nicaraguan Contras, the U.S.-backed rebels seeking to overthrow
the leftist government there.
   The group cheered Bush when he said he would place ``a lot of
Hispanic-Americans in high office'' in the new administration. So
far, Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos, a holdover appointee, is the
only member of the ethnic group to be named to a top-level job.
   On foreign policy, Bush said, ``There is no anticipated surprise.
... There will not be under a Bush administration a radical shift in
direction in terms of one of our neighboring countries to the south
that concerns many people in this room.'' That was a reference to
Cuba.
   Taking a hard line, Bush said he wanted to have ``some solid
proof not some rhetoric'' that Cuba intends to promote democracy. He
called for an end to surrogacy by the Soviet Union.
   Cuba's government should ``take a lesson from (Soviet leader
Mikhail) Gorbachev and start lightening up,'' Bush said. Gorbachev
has recently promoted policies of openness and restructuring in his
country.
   Bush praised Cuba for allowing human rights officials to visit
the island recently, but he said the country has a ``long way to
go'' before the principles of democracy are in place.
   Marta San Martin, a member of New Jersey's ethnic advisory
council from Union, N.J., said Bush told the group in private that
he would ``not abandon the Contras.''
   Members of Congress have hinted that James A. Baker III, the
designated secretary of state, has told them the new administration
will not seek aid for the Contras immediately in 1989, but will
first explore other options to achieve peace in Nicaragua.
   Among the others in the group were Hugo Menendez, Florida's
secretary of state; Rep. Manuel Lujan, R-N.Mex., and Katherine
Ortega, the U.S. treasurer.
</TEXT>
