<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1757EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Budget     12-21 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Budget,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's Final Budget Said To Be Better Than Gramm-Rudman Target</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's final budget would reduce
the deficit to $92.5 billion for the next fiscal year, even lower
than the target set by law, through a combination of spending cuts,
higher user fees and sales of government assets, administration
officials said Wednesday.
   Officials said all of the decisions have now been made on the
budget, which the administration will send to Congress on Jan. 9.
   Reagan and members of his Cabinet, including President-elect
Bush, were briefed on the budget details at the White House.
   ``We are going to have a budget that we will be presenting to the
Congress very shortly and it will be in keeping with the
Gramm-Rudman program for leading toward a balanced budget,'' Reagan
told reporters as the meeting opened.
   Joseph Wright, head of the White House Office of Management and
Budget, told reporters at a briefing that the administration had
succeeded in trimming the deficit below the $100 billion target
established by the Gramm-Rudman balanced budget law.
   While Wright would not reveal the actual deficit figure, an
administration source, who spoke on condition that his name not be
used, said Reagan's final budget would show a deficit of $92.5
billion.
   This figure includes $6 billion in asset sales, the source said.
These sales do not count toward meeting the Gramm-Rudman target.
However, even with the asset sales discounted, the administration's
budget would still be below the $100 billion target.
   In the past, Reagan's budgets often have been labeled ``dead on
arrival'' when they were submitted to Congress because they proposed
spending cuts that Congress repeatedly had refused to accept in the
past.
   But Wright defended the final Reagan budget, saying it would
serve as a good starting point for the new Bush administration in
its negotiations with Congress.
   ``We did not have to do a slash and burn budget,'' he said. ``It
is reasonable, responsible and conservative.''
   The budget calls for spending $1.15 trillion, an increase of 4.7
percent over projected spending of $1.097 trillion in the current
fiscal year. The administration is projecting that government
revenues will increase by $82 billion in 1990 to $1.056 trillion.
   The administration unveiled new budget estimates that will make
its job of reaching the deficit target a bit easier. The
administration had been forecasting a deficit of $135 billion if no
changes were made from the current level of government services.
   However, Wright told reporters that revised assumptions on how
the economy will perform and various changes in spending projections
had lowered that estimated deficit to $127 billion.
   But Wright said the administration would call for $2.6 billion in
increased defense spending because of its insistence that the
military be funded at 2 percent above the rate of inflation. He said
the administration also would seek $1.8 billion in higher spending
for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, in part for
spending on the space station project, and $5 billion in higher
outlays for such programs as research on a cure for AIDS.
   To achieve the increased spending will require the administration
to make cuts in other programs of $38 billion.
   It has been reported previously that the administration would
seek to cut Medicare by $5 billion by reducing payments to doctors
and hospitals. In addition, the administration is seeking savings of
$2 billion in the Medicaid program which pays the health costs of
poor patients.
   Wright also has said other savings would be achieved through
cutting farm subsidy payments and in reducing government pension
benefits.
   However, the administration has insisted that Social Security,
the government's largest benefit program, will not be touched in
efforts to trim the budget deficit.
   In addition to coming in lower than the Gramm-Rudman deficit
target for 1990, the spending plan projects the deficit will decline
significantly in coming years until it reaches a balance between
spending and revenues in 1993, nine years later than the 1984 target
for a balanced budget that Reagan had promised to reach during his
1980 campaign for the presidency.
   Bush has promised to begin immediate negotiations with Congress
over ways to reduce the budget deficit once he takes office on Jan.
20. He has said he also will submit his own spending blueprint to
Congress, although he has left open the question of whether he will
submit a completely revised budget request or just make
modifications to Reagan's 1990 budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
