<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Transition-Skinner 1stLd-Writethru a0665 12-21 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Transition-Skinner, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0665,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Poor Sam': Skinner Becomes Frequent Flier While Awaiting Bush
Appointment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 1 graf with Skinner's office responding to Metzenbaum</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago transit official Samuel Skinner,
reported to be in line for transportation secretary, is getting a
closeup look at the nation's air traffic system as he awaits formal
announcement from President-elect Bush.
   In less than two weeks, Skinner has been summoned three times to
the nation's capital by Bush transition aides. Three times he has
gone home empty-handed. Though Skinner has been told he has the job
of running the Transportation Department, sources said, the official
announcement from the president-elect has not yet been made.
   ``Poor Sam,'' said one Bush transition aide, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Sheila Tate, the transition's spokeswoman, said Wednesday she did
not know when Bush would made additional personnel announcements.
   The latest snafu involving Skinner occurred Tuesday after
transition aides had put out the word that Bush would make an
announcement, which was expected to involve Skinner.
   Skinner, 50, a private attorney who worked in Bush's presidential
campaigns in 1980 and 1988, had been in the capital since Monday
awaiting a summons from Bush.
   A few hours before Bush was expected to make an announcement, it
was cancelled. Transition aides said Bush wanted to make a batch of
appointments at the same time, but his choice for secretary of
health and human services was mired in a debate over his views on
abortion.
   So Skinner flew back to Chicago Tuesday night _ empty-handed
again.
   Skinner's spokesman in Chicago, Ed Murnane, said his boss is
unperturbed by the situation. ``Sam Skinner is a very patient and
understanding friend of President-elect Bush's,'' he said.
   Another source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
situation has been somewhat anxiety-producing for Skinner. ``He
hasn't had any chance to do any Christmas shopping yet,'' this
person said.
   But Skinner has been assured he has the job, the source said,
adding: ``I don't think he is being Tower-ized.''
   That was a reference to former Sen. John Tower who was rumored to
have the defense secretary's job but was left dangling for weeks
while the FBI investigated allegations of drinking and womanizing.
Bush finally appointed Tower last Friday.
   Skinner also traveled to Washington on Dec. 8 to meet with
transition aides, and flew in for a face-to-face session with Bush
on Dec. 14.
   Skinner is chairman of the Regional Transportation Authority of
Northeastern Illinois, the nation's second largest transportation
system.
   Meanwhile, Skinner's expected nomination drew fire from Sen.
Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, concerning his conduct as a former
federal prosecutor in Chicago.
   Metzenbaum said in a statement that the Senate should look into
why the U.S. attorney's office in Chicago decided against
prosecuting the maker of NutraSweet, G.D. Searle Co., for
``allegations of fraudulent testing.'' Skinner, then the U.S.
attorney, later joined the law firm that defended Searle in the case.
   Metzenbaum, who first raised the issue in 1986, said there were
``serious questions about Mr. Skinner's conduct of the case that
must be answered.'' At the time, Skinner said he withdrew from
participating in the case after his office received the formal Food
and Drug Administration request for a grand jury because he was
discussing a job with the law firm in question.
   Skinner's office issued a statement saying he ``conducted himself
in accordance with Department of Justice guidelines in the matter
mentioned by Senator Metzenbaum.'' Skinner will be happy to answer
any questions senators have about the case, the statement said.
</TEXT>
