<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Judge-Homosexuals     12-21 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Judge-Homosexuals,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Divided Over Judge's Statements</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who said he gave a killer a lesser sentence
in part because the victims were homosexual has divided the city's
religious leaders, with one group Wednesday demanding a retraction
and another planning a rally of support.
   Ken Coulter, pastor of Grace Fellowship Church and part of a
coalition of leaders of churches with large numbers of gay
congregants, said they fear that state District Judge Jack Hampton's
remarks may mean ``open season'' on homosexuals.
   Meanwhile, the Rev. Don Skelton, pastor at Fountain of The Living
Word, said at least seven pastors have agreed to take part in a
rally in support of Hampton on Thursday outside the courthouse. He
said he expected 100 to 150 people.
   ``We're very much opposed to sodomy,'' Skelton said. ``It's
against Texas law for one thing and God's law for another thing.''
Sodomy carries up to a $200 fine. The law was thrown out in 1982 but
reinstated by a federal appeals court three years later.
   Hampton, in an interview last week in the Dallas Times Herald,
said he sentenced 18-year-old Richard Lee Bednarski to 30 years in
prison instead of the maximum life sentence on Nov. 28 in part
because the two murder victims were ``queers.''
   He was quoted as saying he ``put prostitutes and gays at about
the same level'' and would be ``hard put to give somebody life for
killing a prostitute.''
   The remarks have stirred the gay community and equal rights
activists to protest and to seek Hampton's removal from the bench.
On Tuesday, state Treasurer Ann Richards and Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., criticized him in statements read at a rally.
   The Texas Human Rights Foundation has filed an ethics complaint
with the Commission on Judicial Conduct. The panel can, among other
things, censure him or initiate a drawn-out procedure that could
result in his removal.
   The church coalition deploring Hampton's remarks on Wednesday
called on other religious leaders, judges and lawyers to join them
in criticizing the judge.
   ``We ... deplore the mentality recently expressed by Judge Jack
Hampton in the press, which suggest that all human beings are not of
equal value and are not entitled to equal protection under the
law,'' said the Rev. Howard Tyas, pastor of Bethany Presbyterian
Church, reading from the group's statement.
   The church leaders said they were asking him to retract his
comments. They said any further action would be up to ``the system.''
   ``If this is not what he means, we are asking him to speak up and
say this is not what I mean,'' said the Rev. Lou Arceneaux, pastor
at Holy Trinity Catholic Church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
