<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Shultz-Israel     12-21 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Israel,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Hails Formation of New Government in Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz told a
delegation of American Jewish leaders Wednesday he believes the
formation of a new coalition government in Israel could provide
momementum to the Middle East peace process, a participant in the
meeting said.
   Reporting on the meeting, Morris Abram, chairman of the
Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations,
said the secretary feels that the newly formed Likud-Labor coalition
was better for the peace process than a ``narrowly based
government.''
   Much of the meeting, which lasted more than an hour, focused on
Shultz's decision last week to open a dialogue with the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   Abram said the meeting was held to express the ``very deep
concerns'' of American Jewish leaders about recent administration
moves in the Middle East.
   He indicated that the delegation came away reassured by what
Shultz had to say.
   Abram said Shultz told the delegation that the initial contacts
last week with the PLO did not constitute negotiations but ``a very
low level dialogue.''
   He added that Shultz is not pressing Israel to undertake any
dealings with the PLO.
   Abram indicated he disagreed with suggestions by some State
Department officials that the statement last week by PLO Chairman
Yasser Arafat recognizing Israel's right to exist, in effect,
superceded the policy enshrined in the PLO covenant calling for
Israel's destruction.
   Abram said the only way the PLO could legitimately retreat from
that policy would be for the Palestine National Council to amend the
charter.
   Shultz agreed, Abram said, that he ``would like to see that
done.''
   ``The secretary was extremely firm in his statement that nothing
whatsoever had changed with respect to American policy with respect
to the Middle East and the state of Israel,'' Abram said.
   ``He reaffirmed the following: this government does not want an
independent Palestinian state and he laid out the reasons, saying
that such a state would be unstable and would be a threat not only
to Israel but to the whole area.
   ``He stated, furthermore, that the policy of the United States
government remained very firm that Jerusalem should remain a united
city. He spoke passionately of his abhorrence of terrorism, and his
determination that terrorism must cease.''
</TEXT>
