<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-JailedMother     12-21 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Jailed Mother,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rehnquist Reinstates Contempt Citation Against Maryland Woman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist on Wednesday
reinstated a contempt citation against a Maryland woman jailed for
refusing to disclose the whereabouts of her young son, who
prosecutors fear may be dead.
   Rehnquist, acting on an emergency request by state prosecutors,
negated the effect of a ruling by Maryland's highest court that
Jacqueline Bouknight's jailing for contempt is unconstitutional.
   But Ms. Bouknight was destined to remain behind bars no matter
what action Rehnquist took.
   Prosecutors disclosed Tuesday they had independent grounds for
keeping Ms. Bouknight incarcerated. They told the chief justice she
was convicted on Nov. 28 of theft, and sentenced to 18 months in
jail.
   Ms. Bouknight, 21, was cited for contempt last April after
refusing to tell social workers in Baltimore where they could find
her 27-month-old son, Maurice.
   A judge ordered her jailed until she was willing to provide that
information.
   The child earlier had been placed in foster care after being
hospitalized for treatment of a broken leg and several partially
healed fractures.
   Maurice was returned to Ms. Bouknight, who has a history of drug
abuse, after she agreed not to physically punish him and to undergo
training in how to be a parent.
   Social workers say Maurice has not been seen since September 1987.
   The boy's father has been killed.
   The Maryland Court of Appeals earlier this week ruled, by a 5-2
vote, that Ms. Bouknight's jailing on the contempt citation violated
her constitutional protection against self-incrimination.
   ``The state readily acknowledges that Bouknight's risk of
incriminating herself is a substantial one, encompassing among other
possible crimes the felony of child abuse or even murder,'' the
state court said.
   Prosecutors contend that protecting the child outweighs Ms.
Bouknight's right against self-incrimination, and that she should
remain jailed until she cooperates with authorities.
   Rehnquist, in an order accompanied by a four-page opinion, set
aside the state court ruling pending full Supreme Court action on a
formal appeal to be filed by Maryland prosecutors.
   The case is Baltimore City Department of Social Services vs.
Bouknight, A-494.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
