<1ST_LINE>r a AM-911Call     12-21 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-911 Call,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frantic 8-year-old Describes Attack To 911 Operator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A terrified 8-year-old girl who called a
911 operator watched a burglar stab her father and initially refused
to unlock the front door for police, a tape recording of the
conversation shows.
   Police said the 11-minute conversation between dispatcher Valerie
Nelson and the girl, Laura Hollingsworth, allowed the operator to
get help to the family quickly.
   Laura, who was taught in school to call 911 in an emergency,
spoke to Mrs. Nelson as the family tried to fight off the
knife-wielding stranger Dec. 14.
   ``She was very clear considering the emotional state she was
in,'' Mrs. Nelson said. ``She was not hysterical.''
   The intruder, Douglas Spencer Collins, 19, died of a shot from a
hunting rifle, police said.
   Dale Hollingsworth, 36, Laura's father, was stabbed in the head,
arms and hands and was listed in good condition Wednesday at
Arlington Memorial Hospital. Laura's 14-year-old brother, Buddy, was
treated for stab wounds on a hand.
   Laura, according to the tape played on Monday, told Mrs. Nelson
where she lived and that the intruder was demanding to know where to
find a wallet.
   According to the tape, Laura told Mrs. Nelson the intruder ``just
broke in with a gun,'' apparently mistaking the knife for a gun.
   When the child saw that her father was ``covered with blood,''
her voice took on an additional urgency as she pleaded, ``Hurry, I'm
scared.''
   The tape continued:
   Mrs. Nelson: ``OK. I have an ambulance, honey, don't worry. We
have people on the way.''
   Laura, suddenly whispering: ``I think he's got the guy.''
   Mrs. Nelson: ``Who's got the guy?''
   The only response was screaming and sobbing in the background.
   Mrs. Nelson: ``Honey? It's OK. What's going on?''
   Laura: ``He's got a knife!''
   Mrs. Nelson: ``Who does? Your brother?''
   Laura, sobbing: ``No! The guy. Pleeeaaase! Oh, God! Buddy!''
   The conversation was cut of by the sound of a rifle shot, and
then Laura could be heard whispering: ``Oh. Oh, he killed the guy.''
   Mrs. Nelson: ``OK, who got shot? Your father got shot? Honey! Can
you tell me who got shot?''
   Laura: ``He (Buddy) shot the guy that came in here.''
   During several minutes of painstaking conversation, Mrs. Nelson
confirmed that the intruder was dead or dying and that the child's
father and Buddy were injured. Mrs. Nelson also realized the
children thought police officers outside the home were more burglars.
   The exchange went on several more minutes, with Buddy and Laura
distrusting what they were being told because they could not see any
police cars and because one officer had a youthful voice.
   Several minutes later, though, the officers were allowed into the
house.
   Mrs. Nelson said she is used to handling dramatic situations, but
the exchange with Laura was by far the most compelling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
