<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0678 12-21 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0678,0833</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poliburo Shaken Up, Ban on Solidarity To Be Reviewed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Jaruzelski and Rakowski speeches,
party told to reconsider Solidarity. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski made
sweeping changes in the ruling Politburo Wednesday, and Communist
authorities gave their clearest signal yet they are considering
ending a seven-year ban on Solidarity.
   Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski announced that the
Communist Party will reevaluate its attitude toward the outlawed
trade union federation.
   Rakowski told Central Committee members to return to local party
units and poll members on the subject of Solidarity and on its
leader, Lech Walesa.
   Members were ordered to return to Warsaw in mid-January with
their answers at the next session of the 230-member Central
Committee.
   ``We must decide together about what to do,'' Rakowski said.
``Your answer ... will decide about what we will do. And what we do
will decide the future of socialism in Poland,'' he said.
   In the Communist Party shakeup, Jaruzelski removed six hardliners
and veteran members from the Politburo in favor of younger
pragmatists.
   Among those promoted to full Politburo membership was Stanislaw
Ciosek, a party activist known as a liberal who has been active in
conducting talks with Walesa. Ciosek was also given an important
additional post of full party secretary, where he was expected to
assume responsibility for propaganda.
   In all, eight new Politburo members were appointed to replace six
who were removed, increasing the Politburo's overall size from 15 to
17 members. Four new party secretaries were named, replacing four
who were removed.
   The plenum was capped by Jaruzelski's plea to the opposition to
accept the party's offer for talks.
   Referring to the opposition's formation on Sunday of a Citizens
Committee intended to gather mainstream anti-government forces in
one structure under Walesa's leadership, Jaruzelski said:
   ``One can freely create governments in exile or shadow Cabinets,
... but the real reconcilation of Poles is the cause of supreme
importance. Our party opts for it decisively and honestly.''
   The offer for talks is ``unchangeably'' open, he said.
   Walesa refuses to enter talks with the government until
authorities clearly indicate they are willing to make Solidarity
legal again.
   The labor movement was crushed when martial law was imposed here
in 1981 and was later outlawed.
   Rakowski defended the idea of holding talks with Walesa in his
address to the plenum, and said _ in an evident overture to
Solidarity _ that the party is willing to change the structure of
trade unions. When, and under what terms must yet be negotiated.
   He repeated calls for the opposition to begin talks without
preconditions.
   ``We are saying clearly that we desire to discuss the future
model of the trade union movement _ different from the present _
together with the OPZZ (official unions) and moderate leaders of
former Solidarity,'' he said.
   ``The realization of (union) pluralism depends, however, on
reaching agreement about its principles, forms and time.''
   Whether Rakowski's statement would be enough to bring Solidarity
activists to the negotiating table was not clear. No immediate
reaction came from Walesa, whose telephone in Gdansk was not being
answered Wednesday night.
   Ciosek, the new Politburo member, met three times with Walesa
this year in failed attempts to launch formal roundtable talks with
the opposition.
   During Solidarity's legal existence in 1980-81, he was the
government minister in charge of cooperating with trade unions.
   Three people were named candidate members of the Politburo in
voting at the end of the plenum.
   Besides Ciosek, the new party secretaries were Zygmunt Czarzasty,
the Slupsk province party chief who had developed a reputation as a
strong advocate of pragmatic reforms; Leszek Miller, a young party
chief from the province of Skierniewice; and Marian Stepien, a
high-ranking party ideologist.
   Ousted from the Politburo were former Prime Minister Zbigniew
Messner, who had to resign from the government in September amid
criticism of his handling of the economy; Gen. Jozef Baryla, an army
colleague of Jaruzelski; Jan Glowczyk, a former propaganda chief
with a reputation as a hardliner; and three lesser known Politburo
members: Tadeusz Porebski, Zofia Stepien and Zygmunt Muranski.
   The new Politburo members, besides Ciosek, were Gabriela Rebisz,
Kazimierz Cypryniak, Iwona Lubowska, Zdzidlaw Swiatek, Viktor
Pyrkosz, Janusz Reykowski and Zbigniew Michalek. Aside from Ciosek,
the new appointees are little known and two of them _ Pyrkosz and
Reykowski _ had not even been members of the Central Committee
before.
   But Jaruzelski suggested they represented a new generation of
activists.
   ``Life itself, its needs and challenges dictate unavoidable and
necessary changes,'' he said.
   Jaruzelski had said personnel changes were necessary for the
success of party reforms.
   He said in opening the plenum Tuesday that the party should be
open to unconventional compromises with the opposition but it must
remain Poland's ``key political force.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
