<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Shultz-Panama     12-21 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Panama,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Shows Support for Delvalle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz met
Wednesday with ousted Panamanian President Eric Arturo Delvalle as
part of a high-level show of support for a leader whom the United
States continues to regard as Panama's legitimate authority.
   Neither Shultz nor Delvalle spoke after their late afternoon
meeting, but State Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley had
reaffirmed earlier that U.S. backing for Delvalle remains unchanged
10 months after his ouster by forces loyal to Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega.
   Mrs. Oakley appeared to rule out U.S. use of force to depose
Noriega, saying that ``Panama's political crisis can be resolved
only by Panamanians.''
   Delvalle will meet Thursday with President Reagan, who said
Wednesday that ``it would be nice'' if there were a change in
government in Panama before he leaves office next month but doesn't
know if there will be one.
   Panama's Ambassador Juan B. Sosa, a Delvalle loyalist, said the
deposed president is here to discuss several options with
administration officials and his supporters here.
   Sosa said the Panamanian opposition must decide whether to
contest presidential elections set for May.
   He said one option is to boycott the election on grounds that
Noriega is likely to rig the outcome. Alternatively, he said, the
anti-Noriega forces could field a candidate whose entry into the
race would demonstrate beyond doubt the breadth of the opposition to
the military leader.
   Delvalle has been living in hiding in Panama since he was deposed
and was flown to the United States aboard a U.S. military aircraft.
   Deputy White House Press Secretary Roman Popadiuk said the
Thursday meeting at the White House was designed ``to show visibly
the U.S. support for the Delvalle government and for the people of
Panama.''
   The spokesman was asked about reports that Panamanians working
for United States companies in Panama were disgruntled over U.S.
economic sanctions designed to end the Noriega regime.
   ``We regret any hardship imposed on these long-term loyal
employes,'' he said. ``Noriega's actions demonstrate the great
lengths he is willing to go to find money to shore up his illegal
regime.''
   ``The United States sanctions remain in place,'' Popadiuk said.
``They were undertaken in response to the call by the Delvalle
government for economic pressure against Noriega. The sanctions will
remain in place until the Panamanian people enjoy the full benefits
of democracy. ...
   ``Panama's economic problems preceded the economic sanctions,''
he said. ``The Panamanian economy was already deteriorating due to
the Noriega regime's policies.''
</TEXT>
