<HEAD>AP Executive, Son, Daughter-in-Law Were Aboard Crashed Jet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds background and Pan Am statement re no information on
survivors. New throughout.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With Britain-Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Mulroy, 59, director of international
communications for The Associated Press, was aboard the New
York-bound Pan Am jetliner that crashed and exploded Wednesday in
Scotland.
   Mulroy's son Sean, 25, and Sean's wife, Ingrid, also were
passengers on Pan Am Flight 103 when it crashed in the village of
Lockerbie in southern Scotland, about an hour after takeoff from
London.
   There was no word that any of the 258 people on board had
survived. ``We have not heard of any survivors off the aircraft,''
said Jeffrey Kriendler, Pan Am vice president for corporate
communications, in New York.
   Mulroy joined the AP four years ago after 25 years with Pan Am,
where he had been director of communications. He was a native of
County Mayo, Ireland, and maintained a second home in the land of
his birth.
   He and his wife, Josephine, of East Northport, on New York's Long
Island, also are the parents of a daughter, Siobhan, 26, and a
second son, Brendan, 23.
   Mulroy joined the AP in August 1984 as staff executive for
international communications. He was named deputy director of
communications in 1986 and director of international communications
in 1988. In that position, he was responsible for all AP technical
operations outside the United States.
   He was born April 1, 1929, and held an associate degree in
electrical engineering from Birmingham University in England.
</TEXT>
