<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Angola     12-21 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Angola,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Says No Diplomatic Recognition for Angola Without
UNITA Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior State Department official said
Wednesday the United States won't give diplomatic recognition to
Angola unless it holds peace talks with rebels fighting to topple
the Marxist government.
   Angola's deputy foreign minister told reporters his country
absolutely refuses to talk with the U.S.- and South African-backed
UNITA rebels, led by Jonas Savimbi.
   ``With or without Savimbi, we will not talk with UNITA,'' said
the Angolan, Venancio de Moura.
   Taken together, the comments indicated no peace is imminent
between Angola and UNITA, despite the conclusion of a peace
settlement for southwest Africa.
   The foreign ministers of Cuba, Angola, and South Africa were
scheduled to sign final documents Thursday for the withdrawal of
50,000 Cuban troops fron Angola, and for Pretoria to begin granting
independence to Namibia, Africa's last colony.
   De Moura said Angolan officials had been told by Chester A.
Crocker, the assistant U.S. secretary of state, that Washington will
drop its opposition to Angola's joining the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund and extend diplomatic recognition once
the accords were signed.
   But Crocker, who mediated the African accords, stressed the
United States will not cease supplying weapons to UNITA.
   ``Our attitude toward UNITA is unchanged,'' Crocker told
reporters. ``We have no intention of disengaging unilaterally from
the Angolan situation at a time when others continue to provide
large amounts of hardware to the other Angolan parties.''
   Crocker was evidently referring to the Soviet Union, the source
of the Angolan government's weapons.
   When asked if diplomatic recognition of Angola will follow
Thursday's signing of the accords, Crocker said: ``I don't have any
prediction to make on that. Clearly the signing is a very important
step.''
   On U.S. opposition to Angola's joining the IMF and World Bank,
Crocker said ``that is primarily between the Angolans and the IMF to
work out the economic terms of such membership. That has not yet
been done, and so that's what constitutes the principle obstacle.''
   Crocker and the Angolan officials, along with Secretary of State
George P. Shultz and the foreign ministers of Cuba and South Africa,
were to attend Thursday's signing at the United Nations of two
accords on southwest Africa.
   One diplomat who had been expected to attend was Bernt Carlsson,
the Swedish U.N. commissioner for Namibia, who was aboard a Pan Am
jumbo jet that crashed in Scotland Wednesday night. Carlsson, 50,
was flying from London to New York when the jet crashed. His absence
would not delay the meeting.
   The foreign ministers of South Africa, Cuba and Angola are
scheduled to sign accords declaring the independence process for
Namibia will begin April 1, after 73 years of South African rule.
   At the same time, Cuba and Angola will sign an agreement with the
United Nations to have 70 U.N. military observers monitor withdrawal
of 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola over a 30-month period, beginning
in January.
   A much larger peacekeeping force is planned for monitoring South
Africa's withdrawal from Namibia, also known as South-West Africa.
   A decade-old Security Council plan for Namibia's independence
calls for about 2,000 civilian administrators and military police to
back about 7,500 U.N. peacekeepers as South African troops withdraw
and a civilian government is organized.
   The Namibian elections are scheduled for Nov. 1.
   Cuban troops went to Angola in 1975 to help the Marxist
government fight invading South African troops and U.S.-backed
rebels of the National Union for the Total Liberation of Angola,
more commonly called UNITA.
   South Africa insisted on the Cuban withdrawal from Angola in
exchange for its cooperation with the Namibia independence plan.
   Pretoria has ruled the mineral-rich territory of Namibia since
capturing it from Germany during World War I. In 1920 the League of
Nations granted South Africa a mandate to administer Namibia; the
United Nations revoked that mandate in 1966.
</TEXT>
