<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-UN Official,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Namibia Official in Plane Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Britain-Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brent Carlsson of Sweden, the U.N.
commissioner for Namibia, was one of the passengers aboard the Pan
Am jetliner that crashed in Scotland on Wednesday, U.N officials
said.
   Carlsson, 50, was to have been a witness Thursday when the accord
is signed that granting the African colony of Namibia its
independence.
   Flight 103 crashed about an hour after Carlsson's assistant,
Malti Ramen, said the commissioner called her to say he was boarding
the plane.
   On Thursday, the foreign ministers of South Africa, Cuba and
Angola are to sign an accord guaranteeing Pretoria will end its
73-year rule over Namibia, and that 50,000 Cuban troops will
withdraw from Angola.
   South African Foreign Minister R.F. Botha told The Associated
Press he arrived in New York on the Pan Am flight just before the
ill-fated Flight 103.
   Botha, contacted at his hotel, said he was saddened to learn of
the crash.
   Carlsson had been commissioner for Namibia since July 1987. The
United Nations in 1966 revoked a League of Nations mandate giving
South Africa the right to govern Namibia, and asserted its own
authority over the territory.
   South Africa, however, defied the U.N. declaration until this
month, when it finally signed a preliminary agreement that linked
its withdrawal from Namibia with the Cuban pullout from Angola.
   The United Nations considered Carlsson the chief official of
Namibia, also known as South-West Africa. Thursday's accord would
have been its first step toward coming under his control during its
transition to an independent government.
   Carlsson was formerly a special emissary for Swedish Prime
Minister Olaf Palme to Middle East and African nations from 1983-85.
From 1976-83, he was general secretary of the Socialist
International.
</TEXT>
