<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-21 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winter Storm Belts Utah, California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A fierce storm heralded the first day of winter Wednesday,
dumping up to 15 inches of snow through the mountains of Utah,
triggering dozens of traffic accidents and bringing strong winds and
high surf to the California coast.
   A low pressure system and a cold front moving across the
Intermountain region spawned snow throughout the mountainous areas
of the central and southern Plateau west of the Rockies and to the
central Rockies.
   Winter arrived at 10:28 a.m. EST Wednesday.
   The mountains and ski resorts of Utah reported between 10 and 15
inches of snow, with heavy snow continuing to fall through the
areas. Total snow accumulation in valley areas of Utah was expected
to be 3 to 5 inches.
   The fast-moving storm snarled traffic for northern Utah
motorists. The Utah Highway Patrol reported more than 40 accidents
in the Salt Lake Valley by mid-afternoon. No major injuries were
reported.
   Light snow also fell over western Wyoming with the heaviest
accumulations occurring in the mountains. Between 4 and 8 inches of
snow was received in Yellowstone and Grand Teton National Park.
Grant Village in Yellowstone National Park and the ski area near
Teton Village, Wyo., had almost a foot of new snow.
   High wind watches were posted Wednesday night for southeast
Wyoming, as well as for the Colorado eastern foothills, where winds
were expected to gust as high as 60 mph.
   High winds also buffeted the California coast and dangerously
high surf was reported, with wave heights expected to reach 15 to 20
feet.
   Elsewhere, rain was scattered along a cold front that stretched
from southern New England to southeast Texas.
   The Atlantic Coast states enjoyed mild weather on Wednesday, with
record high temperatures set in Binghamton, N.Y., with 52 degrees,
and Syracuse, with 58.
   Temperatures early Wednesday afternoon were in the teens and 20s
over parts of the northern and central Rockies, eastern parts of the
Great Basin, North Dakota, northern Minnesota and the northern half
of the upper Great Lakes; in the 30s and 40s extended through the
Pacific Coast across the central Intermountain region, the southern
Rockies, South Dakota and the central Plains, the middle Mississippi
Valley, the remainder of the Great Lakes and the Ohio Valley to the
central and northern Appalachians; in the 70s and 80s were over
south, central and southeast Texas, along the Gulf Coast, Florida
and along the southern Atlantic Coast; in the 50s and 60s throughout
the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 15
degrees at Havre, Mont., to 82 degrees at McAllen and Harlingen
Texas and Fort Myers, Fla.
   The forecast for Thursday called for showers and thunderstorms
from eastern Texas across the lower Mississippi Valley, eastern
parts of Kansas and Oklahoma, much of the middle Mississippi Valley
and lower Ohio Valley to southern parts of the upper Great Lakes;
snow through much of the northern Plains, the upper Mississippi
Valley and the rest of the upper Great Lakes; and rain through the
Pacific Coast area and snow through the northern Intermountain
region, the Sierra Nevadas of California and northern Nevada.
   High temperatures in the teens and 20s were forecast over the
northern Rockies, North Dakota, northern Minnesota, upper Michigan,
northeast New York and northern New England; in the 30s and 40s from
the northern Pacific Coast across much of the central and southern
Plateau region, the central Rockies, the central Plains and South
Dakota, Iowa and Minnesota, the southern half of the upper Great
Lakes, the lower Great Lakes and the upper Ohio Valley to southern
New England and the middle Atlantic Coast; the 70s through most of
Texas, the Gulf Coast region, southern Georgia and most of Florida;
in the 80s over the southern tip of the Florida Peninsula; and in
the 50s and 60s throughout the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
