<DOCNO> AP881221-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 2038EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash-Scene     12-21 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Scene,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Village Hall Becomes Morgue in Devastated Lockerbie</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Britain-Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Scottish reporter Bert Houston was one of the
first journalists to get into Lockerbie after the village was hit by
a crashing Pan Am jumbo jet Wednesday night. He wrote this report
for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BERT HOUSTON</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soon after the Pan Am Boeing 747
plowed into Lockerbie on Wednesday evening, its council hall became
a makeshift clinic. Within hours, it was a morgue.
   Nobody knows how many of the 2,500 villagers have lost their
lives, but up to half a dozen houses were flattened, and others
caught fire and were gutted.
   Mayor Frank Park stood in the street, dazed and in tears, too
distraught to talk. Pleasant village lanes were littered with
debris, masonry, ripped up fences and shrubbery.
   Royal Air Force rescue authorities say two rows of houses were
demolished and no survivors have been found in the wreckage.
   Sherwood Crescent, the village center that bore the brunt of the
crash, was sealed off, and accumulated traffic blocked the accesses
to Lockerbie, so that rescuers had to fly in and out by helicopter.
There were fears that a gas station hit by the wreckage might blow
up.
   According to initial accounts from authorities, the aircraft
apparently hit a hillside near the tiny hamlet of Corrie, about six
miles from Lockerbie, and left a trail of debris and bodies across
the countryside.
   Along a country road leading to Lockerbie, rescue parties could
be seen examining pieces of smoking wreckage, and there were what
looked like blanket-covered bodies.
   Some of the wreckage also landed on cars on the four-lane bypass
around Lockerbie and they went up in flames.
   A former police inspector, Archie Smith, ran out of his house
with his son when he heard the crash.
   ``I didn't know what it was at first. It was just a mighty bang.
Where the houses were seems to be just a black hole. The fire spread
quickly and my home soon caught alight and it is now destroyed as
well.''
   Smith, who was a policeman for 30 years, said: ``Never, ever have
I seen anything so appalling, so horrific as this.''
   The flames sent up a pall of thick, choking smoke and the streets
were littered with rocks and twisted pieces of metal.
   Sheila McDonald was delivering Christmas presents to a friend's
home on a hillside overlooking the town when she heard ``a horrible
droniong sound.''
   She said: ``This V-shaped object just seemed to come flying
through the air ... it was the wings and front section of an
aircraft ... another part came just behind and all around seemed to
be red dots like sparks.
   ``It hit some houses in the town and there was a mass of flame
and everything just started to shake.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881221-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 2046EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash-Relatives     12-21 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Relatives,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Families Gather To Seek Word of Relatives, Friends</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Britain-Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everard Whitehouse joined a small group of shaken
relatives of passengers who boarded Pan Am Flight 103 at Heathrow
Airport Wednesday night and voiced the frail hope his young cousin
had missed the plane.
   ``People change their minds,'' he said.
   Whitehouse had taken Julian Bennello, 25, of Boston, to the
airport in the afternoon to catch the flight. He returned to the
airport after hearing the news that it crashed in the village of
Lockerbie in southern Scotland.
   ``He's a post-graduate at Cambridge University and is quite
brilliant,'' said Whitehouse. ``He delayed his flight by one day
because he wanted to see a friend of his who was ill in Cambridge.
   ``I've come here because I couldn't get through on the phones.
... His brother rang me from the States and I told him I was going
to the airport. I wanted to make sure he was on the plane as things
changed at the last moment _ people change their minds.''
   Police officers escorted one elderly couple who walked down the
airport's corridor holding hands, tears in their eyes.
   Two tearful women who would not reveal their names said, ``We've
been ringing all the time. We've been trying to phone New York and
the London numbers and they are just engaged. We've come here
because we think a friend of ours is on the plane.''
   Heathrow staff members appeared pale and stunned by the news
about the flight, which had left Terminal Three.
   ``They were the usual mix of holidaymakers and businessmen,'' an
airport security man said. ``Many of them going back home for the
holidays.
   ``They seemed in a pre-Christmas spirit, carrying presents among
their luggage. There appeared to be a lot of women and children
among the passengers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
