<HEAD>Crack Found in Atlantis Pump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A damaged high-pressure pump from one of the
engines that powered the space shuttle Atlantis to orbit on a
military mission Nov. 29 has been sent back to the manufacturer for
detailed examination, a NASA spokeswoman said Wednesday.
   Barbara Selby said the pump was shipped to Rocketdyne, the maker
of the space shuttle's main engines. She said repair of the part is
not expected to delay Atlantis' next launch in April.
   The crack, in a bearing assembly, was found in a post-flight
examination of the shuttle after its four-day, nine-hour classified
military mission.
