<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Crash-Boeing747 2ndLd-Writethru a0743 12-21 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Boeing 747, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0743,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jumbo Jet Has Been Involved In Some of World's Worst Aviation
Disasters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, bgng: ``David Jimenez...'' to CORRECT
number of takeoffs and landings; picks up 9th graf pvs, bgng: ``The
747-100...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Britain-Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing's 747 jumbo jetliner has an average
safety record, but it's been involved in several of the world's
worst aviation disasters over the course of its nearly 20-year
history because of its large capacity.
   The worst single-plane aircraft accident in history involved a
Japan Air Lines 747 that smashed into a mountain northwest of Tokyo
on Aug. 12, 1985, killing 520 of 524 people aboard.
   In March 1977, two 747s _ one a Pan Am jet, the other a KLM _
collided on a fog-shrouded runway in the Canary Islands, killing
more than 582 people. The blame was put on a mis-communication that
resulted in one pilot taking off when another was on the runway.
   Aviation expert John Galipault of the Aviation Safety Institute
in Ohio said the 747 aircraft has a safety record about average for
the early wide-body jetliners, according to statistical summaries of
jet aircraft accidents.
   The Pan Am 747 that crashed in Scotland on Wednesday was the 15th
747 ever built and it was delivered to Pan Am in February 1970.
   The aviation industry recently has focused on aging aircraft, due
in part to the in-flight damage sustained by an Aloha Airline Boeing
737 airplane in Hawaii this year. Boeing has undertaking a series of
studies of its older airplanes to determine what effect age and use
have on airworthiness.
   A Boeing 747 military version is being outfitted to become the
new Air Force One presidential aircraft.
   David Jimenez, of Boeing Commercial Airplanes division in
Seattle, Wash., said the plane that crashed was a 747-100 model with
approximately 16,500 takeoff and landings.
   The 747-100 was the initial model of the aircraft and is no
longer manufactured. It was capable of seating up to 385 passengers.
   The plane also was produced in other models and configurations,
including the high capacity type involved in the Japan crash that
could carry 550 passengers for short range flights.
   The 1985 Japan Air Lines crash was attributed to a crack in the
rear cabin wall opened, sending a rush of pressurized air into the
tail section, blowing the tail apart and severing hydraulic lines
used to control the aircraft.
   After that crash, the Federal Aviation Administration ordered
modification of all 747s aimed at preventing such a rush of
pressurized air if the rear cabin wall fails.
   The Boeing Co. admitted that its faulty repairs were one of the
causes.
   According to Boeing, 18 of the 883 747s produced have crashed or
been otherwise destroyed.
   Among them was the Korean Air Lines 747 that was shot down by a
Soviet jet fighter Sept. 1, 1983, after flying through Soviet
airspace near Sakhalin Island.
   Others included an Air India 747 that crashed June 23, 1985 off
the coast of Ireland, killing 329 people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881221-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 2132EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-RedCross 1stLd-Writethru a0637 12-21 0835</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Red Cross, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0637,0859</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lebanon Laments Departure of Red Cross</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs UPDATING with last ferry leaving with Swiss
ambassador returning home for consultation. Pickup 5th graf `With
the...'; EDITS thereafter to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanon bade a bitter goodbye Wednesday to
the Red Cross, one of the few sources of care and comfort in this
violence-scarred country.
   The agency's pullout, prompted by terrorist death threats, means
an end to what often has been the only humanitarian aid for
thousands of people during 13 years of civil war and factional
violence.
   ``Lebanon is the only loser,'' Beirut's leftist As-Safir daily
lamented Wednesday as the International Committee of the Red Cross
evacuated its Swiss workers.
   The last ferry headed for Larnaca, Cyprus included Michael
Dufour, the chief Red Cross delegate, Swiss Ambassador Dino Sciolli
and 12 other Swiss nationals, boarded the boat, police said.
   Sciolli, based in the Cypriot capital Nicosia, told an official
of the Lebanese Foreign Ministry that his government was recalling
him to Switzerland to discuss the Red Cross' pullout.
   Eleven Red Cross workers who left Tuesday completed the same
route and arrived in Switzerland on Wednesday. On Tuesday, Red Cross
officials in Geneva had said all had left.
   With the collapse of government authority over the years, U.N.
organizations and humanitarian groups have been the saviors of
countless victims of the bloodletting.
   The Red Cross worked closely with the Lebanese Red Cross, whose
rescue crews have braved bombs and bullets to carry out their
mission in Christian and Moslem areas.
   The departure left hundreds of Lebanese and Palestinian prisoners
in Israel and the Khiam detention camp run by the Israeli-backed
South Lebanon Army with no way to correspond with their families.
   Red Cross officials visited the detainees regularly to deliver
messages and to try to improve living conditions.
   The agency also had been instrumental in arranging prisoner
exchanges between Palestinian guerrillas and Israel.
   Another casualty of the departure is an orthopedic center in
south Lebanon's provincial capital of Sidon. For five years it has
cared for disabled victims of Lebanon's violence and provided them
with artifical limbs.
   The Red Cross' 150 Lebanese employees face losing their jobs if
the withdrawal becomes permanent.
   ``One minute we were happily going about our work. The next I was
told to go home for a week, pending the (Red Cross') final decision
on whether to shut down its operations in Lebanon or not,'' one
Lebanese worker said.
   In Geneva, Andre Pasquier, the Red Cross chief of operations,
said all the delegates were ready to go back to Lebanon as soon as
conditions would permit, ``even tomorrow.'' He said the fact that
they stayed on their posts after one of them, Peter Winkler, was
kidnapped last month, ``demonstrated their determination to
continue.''
   Until the last year, humanitarian workers were generally
considered immune from kidnappings and death threats by Lebanon's
extremists because they gave help regardless of political or
religious affiliations.
   They remained when thousands of other foreigners fled
kidnap-plagued Moslem areas in recent years. They treated the sick
and wounded, provided relief aid and even food, often in highly
dangerous conditions.
   The evacuation was ordered Tuesday by international Red Cross
headquarters in Geneva following the release Friday of Winkler, 32,
a Swiss national.
   He was abducted Nov. 17 in south Lebanon by unidentified gunmen.
They were believed linked to pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem extremists
apparently seeking to trade Winkler for alleged Shiite hijacker
Hussein Hariri, who goes on trial in Switzerland in February.
   It was not clear why the kidnappers released Winkler, or whether
the subsequent death threats made against the all-Swiss Red Cross
officials came from the same group.
   The two largest Moslem militias in south Lebanon on Wednesday
urged the Red Cross to return.
   The appeals came in separate statements by the Sunni Moslem
Nasserite leftist militia that governs Sidon and the Shiite Moslem
mainstream Amal militia in Tyre.
   ``The kidnapping of humanitarian activists has tarnished our
national image,'' said the Nasserite statement issued by the group's
chief of staff, Usama Saad.
   He said the pullout was ``strange, especially after the intense
national efforts that were exerted to gain the release of Peter
Winkler.''
   Amal's statement in Tyre said ``criminal gangs here and there''
were behind the terrorist attacks aimed at ``emptying Lebanon of all
humanitarian organizations.
   Five other humanitarian activists have been kidnapped in south
Lebanon this year. Four _ a Briton, a Swede, a Norwegian and a
Syrian _ were freed.
   But Belgian physician Jan Cools, who disappeared May 21, remains
missing. A previously unknown group calling itself ``the Soldiers of
Justice,'' said Sunday it was holding Cools and accused him of
spying for Israel.
   Cools, 32, had worked for the Norwegian humanitarian organization
Norwac near Tyre for three months before he disappeared.
   There was no word whether Norwac and other humanitarian groups,
such as the French-based Medecin Sans Frontiers and Britain's Oxfam
charity, will follow the Red Cross' example.
</TEXT>
