<2ND_LINE>AM-Syria-Egypt,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syria President Extends Olive Branch to Egypt, Iraq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hafez Assad opened the door
Wednesday to re-establishing ties with two of Syria's bitter foes,
Egypt and Iraq, a presidential spokesman said.
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak was quoted Wednesday as saying
he invited Assad to visit Egypt in an attempt to improve relations.
   Assad, during a meeting with a delegation from the Federation of
Arab Lawyers, said ``cooperation between Syria and Egypt on a
national basis has always been favored by both countries and would
benefit the Arab nation,'' presidential spokesman Jibran Kourieh
said.
   The president also told the lawyers, including the chairman of
the Egyptian bar association, that although past attempts at
Syrian-Iraqi reconciliation did not work, ``Syria supports any Arab
solidarity action,'' said Kourieh.
   Mubarak made the invitation to Assad in an interview with the
Saudi newspaper Al-Shark al-Awsat, which was published in Cairo
Wednesday by the state-run Middle East News Agency. Mubarak also
said he earlier offered to go to Syria, but Assad snubbed the idea.
   Political observers, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
statements by Assad were a new overture to two of its longstanding
foes.
   Egypt and Syria have been at odds since the late Egyptian
President Anwar Sadat flew to Jerusalem in 1977, an event that
culminated with Egypt's peace treaty with Israel in 1979.
   Syria led the drive to expel Egypt from the Arab League as well
as other regional and Islamic organizations.
   Arab leaders have been trying to organize a summit of the
22-member Arab League, which has not met in regular session since
1982 because of rifts between member governments. Saudi Arabia, the
scheduled venue for the summit, has indicated it wants Egypt to
attend.
   The feud between Syria and Iraq, one of the most bitter
inter-Arab vendettas, was rekindled following the Aug. 20 cease-fire
in the Iran-Iraq war. Assad allied himself with Persian Iran against
Arab Iraq. Syria and Iraq are ruled by rival wings of the Baath Arab
Socialist Party.
   Syria has faced growing political isolation in the region. Arab
states condemned it for its alliance with Iran. Presidential
elections in Lebanon in August and September collapsed after
Christian deputies refused to attend the parliamentary sessions
where Syrian-supported candidates were expected to win. Syria keeps
40,000 troops in Lebanon, which it considers under its sphere of
influence.
   Assad has also waged a campaign since 1983 to depose Yasser
Arafat as chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization. Arafat
has gained unprecedented recognition in the past month for leading
the PLO through the declaration of a Palestinian state and talks
with the United States for the first time in 13 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
