<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Murder 1stLd-Writethru a0690 12-21 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Murder, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American English Teacher Found Murdered In Seoul</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with police questioning students and
associates, police now saying there were signs of struggle and items
robbed. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An English teacher from the United
States has been found slain in her apartment, her throat slashed,
and police said they were questioning people Thursday.
   The police officials, who declined to be identified in keeping
with Korean practice, said a motive had not been established for the
killing of Carolyn J. Abel of Lafayette, Ind.
   The body was found Tuesday by friends who went to her 15th floor
apartment after Ms. Abel, 26, failed to appear at work at English
Language Services in southern Seoul.
   Ms. Abel, one of about 25 English-language instructors at the
private school, came to Korea in October after working as an English
teacher in Japan.
   Police said it appeared she was killed shortly after midnight
Tuesday, because a resident in the apartment building reported
hearing several loud screams.
   The officials also said earlier reports that there were no signs
of a struggle were not correct. They said it looked like Ms. Abel
resisted the attacker and there were 10 cuts on her body, including
wounds on her face and arms. She had a 9-inch cut across her throat.
   Police, reversing earlier statements, said it now appeared a
number of items, including a camera and a tape recorder, had been
removed from Ms. Abel's apartment and there were signs of ransacking.
   On Wednesday police had said there were no signs of a robbery.
However on Thursday they said they were still not convinced that
robbery was a motive because some jewelry was left behind.
   Police quoted friends from the language institute as saying Ms.
Abel was last seen Monday night at a subway station with six other
teachers. Police quoted friends as saying her apartment was
frequented by students and she shared her home with a roommate who
was on vacation in the United States.
   Several Korean students of the slain teacher were being
questioned because the students visited Ms. Abel late at night.
Several sets of fingerprints taken from the apartment were being
checked, officials said.
   Ms. Abel and two other American teachers reportedly went on a
trip to the east coast tourist area of Mount Sorak last weekend with
three male Korean students who were being questioned, police said.
   The Korea Herald reported in its Thursday editions that police
were also checking on a Japanese man thought to be Ms. Abel's
boyfriend. The paper quoted police as saying the unidentified man
left Seoul before the killing.
</TEXT>
