<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Activist, Four Children Die In House Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with fire believed to be
electrical, other details on cause; second fire in Florida killing
three children. Picks up 10th graf, `A crisis...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN HUDDLESTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW PALESTINE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A short circuit in wiring under a
bathtub sparked a fire that killed a woman and her four children in
their home early Wednesday, authorities said.
   Authorities at first believed a newly installed furnace might
have caused the blaze after neighbors reported hearing an explosion,
but later in the day State Fire Marshal Larry Bosell eliminated the
furnace as a possible cause.
   ``The cause is electrical,'' Bosell said. ``It appears the wiring
was underneath the floor. It shorted out underneath the bathtub.''
   In Fort Pierce, Fla., another early-morning fire engulfed a
downstairs apartment in a two-story building, killing three young
children while a passerby rescued a fourth child from the house,
investigators said.
   The mother of the four children, Dany Matheu, told police she was
home when the fire started, but witnesses said she was not. The fire
and the causes of the deaths of Janet Matheu, 8; Loune Bieneme, 4;
and their brother Louisena Bieneme, 3, were under investigation.
   In New Palestine, the dead were identified as Julia M. Kennedy
Westcott, a 34-year-old anti-abortion activist; her daughters from
another marriage, Brandi Kay Neal, 16, Holli Ann Neal, 14; and the
Westcotts' children, Veronica Marie ``Vonni'' Westcott, 6; and
Joshua Andrew Westcott, 4.
   Karen Ford, who lives next door, said she and her husband heard
an explosion and called the fire department. They went outside and
found Mrs. Westcott's husband, Roy Andrew Westcott, in the yard in
his bathrobe.
   ``He was running around the yard trying to get back in,'' Mrs.
Ford said.
   Mrs. Ford said Westcott was screaming for someone to shut off the
natural gas line. Westcott had installed a gas furnace in the home
last weekend, she said.
   Westcott, 34, had leaped through a bedroom window and was
hospitalized in critical condition with third-degree burns,
officials said.
   But authorities said any explosions heard at the fire most likely
came from small propane or acetylene tanks stored in the house. Four
or five of the tanks, which are used to thaw out frozen water pipes,
most likely were on premises, said a spokesman for the Hancock
County Sheriff's Department.
   County Sheriff Nick Gulling said some of the more than 50
firefighters who responded to the alarm were relatives of the
Westcotts and many others were friends.
   A crisis intervention team from Indianapolis was at a nearby
church later in the morning, counseling firefighters and others in
the town of 760 people.
   ``This is the first fire with multiple fatalities in the
township,'' said Jerry Nulliner, Sugar Creek Township fire chief.
``Several firefighters, they're experiencing quite a bit of stress.''
   Westcott, an assistant manager in clinical engineering at the
Indiana University Medical Center in Indianapolis, and his wife were
active in church congregations in Indianapolis. They were youth
leaders at Harvestime Assembly of God Church and also attended the
Calvary Temple.
   Mrs. Westcott operated a pro-life telephone counseling service
from her home.
</TEXT>
