<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SoldierEspionage 1stLd-Writethru a0684 12-21 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soldier Espionage, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0684,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldier Arrested On Suspicion Of Espionage In U.S., Europe
^Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with specifics of allegations
and charges against civilian, details from court documents; picks up
7th graf pvs `Hall's home...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army soldier stationed in Europe three
times in the last 11 years was arrested Wednesday on suspicion of
espionage for allegedly passing defense secrets to East German
agents, officials said.
   A civilian, Huseyin Yildirim, who lives in the St. Petersburg,
Fla., area was charged with conspiracy to commit espionage by giving
agents of a foreign government national defense secrets, said FBI
spokesman Ed Dutko.
   Warrant Officer James William Hall III, an analyst in the Army's
G-2 intelligence section, was being held at the Fort Stewart
detention facility but was not formally charged, said Lt. Col. John
Chapla, an Army spokesman in Washington.
   Chapla said he had no information ``on the classification or
nature of the information allegedly provided by Hall, or to whom it
went.''
   But Dutko said Hall, 30, is accused of dealing with the East
Germans in an operation involving ``national defense secrets.''
   Federal affidavits filed with U.S. Magistrate G.R. Smith in
Savannah said Hall met Tuesday night at a hotel with an FBI agent
posing as an officer of the Soviet intelligence service.
   ``Hall boasted of the important signal intelligence information
he had passed and admitted his motivation to be greed,'' the court
documents stated.
   Officials said it was unknown how much money allegedly passed
hands.
   The documents said Hall told the FBI agent he began passing
secrets in 1982 while stationed in Germany and continued until
January 1988 when he was reassigned to the United States.
   An affidavit filed in Savannah by FBI agent Charles B. Youmans
Jr. said Hall told the undercover FBI agent that Yildirim, a
60-year-old Turkish national, ``actively participated with him in
the reproduction and transmittal of classified national defense
documents to the East Germans.''
   Hall's home in Richmond Hill, Ga., and Yildirim's home in Florida
were searched Wednesday by FBI and Army intelligence officers, the
FBI said.
   Hall has spent most of his career working as a signals
intelligence-electronics warfare analyst, responsible for helping to
analyze intercepted enemy radio traffic, telephone conversations and
coded messages.
   Hall had three assignments in Europe, the first in June 1977 with
an Army security agency company in Schneeberg, West Germany, Chapla
said. In January 1981, he went to West Berlin, again working in a
signals intelligence assignment.
   Hall returned to the United States in March 1985 and was assigned
to a Fort Monmouth, N.J., military intelligence group, Chapla said.
He went to Frankfurt, West Germany, in January 1986 with a military
intelligence battalion, Chapla said.
   He was sent back to this country in May 1987 and was assigned to
the 24th Infantry Division at Fort Stewart, west of Savannah, in
July of this year.
   Hall is a native of New York City who joined the Army in
September 1976, Chapla said.
   Army officials said Hall's commanding officer will determine how
his case is handled under the Uniform Code of Military Justice.
</TEXT>
