<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two 11-year-old boys accused of ordering pit
bulls to attack a schoolyard full of children surrendered to police
Wednesday, while another young man faces assault charges in a second
pit bull attack.
   The Dec. 15 school attack left five children with bites on their
feet and legs, authorities said.
   The boys, who live in the school's north Philadelphia
neighborhood, face aggravated and simple assault charges, said Capt.
Jim Boyle of the Police Department's juvenile division.
   Meanwhile, a 20-year-old southwest Philadelphia man faces assault
charges in a pit bull attack on two teen-age girls. Police said the
man, Dwayne Vinson, ordered his dog to attack the girls after they
refused to talk with him Tuesday afternoon.
   The two pit bulls involved in the Dec. 15 schoolyard attack,
which were among six picked up since Friday by police and officials
of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, have been
identified by neighborhood residents.
   The dogs had been kept in vacant houses not far from St. Edwards
Parochial School, police said.
   In the attack, police said, the two boys walked into the
schoolyard and ordered the dogs to ``sic'' the children, about 100
of whom were on recess.
   The children, ages 10 to 12, began screaming and running. Some
tried to scale a fence, some climbed a wall and others grabbed
sticks to fight off the dogs.
   Five youngsters were bitten on the ankles and feet, including one
who suffered more than 30 cuts.
   School officials did not know what prompted the attack but said
they were thankful it had not occurred minutes earlier, when younger
children _ first-, second- and third-graders _ were in the yard for
their recess.
