<2ND_LINE>PM-Cancun Recovery, Adv 29,0789</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<HEAD>Adv for Release Thur PMs Dec. 29 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Resort Recovers From Hurricane but Parts of Beach Still Missing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANCUN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hotels have repaired hurricane damage,
palms sway and discos throb, but fine stretches of beach were blown
away and the tourists, without whom Cancun has no purpose, are slow
to return.
   ``We have to erase the image that exists abroad about the damage
caused by the hurricane,'' said Carlos Constandse, who owns a hotel
in this resort on Mexico's Caribbean coast.
   Hurricane Gilbert struck Cancun on Sept. 14 with 160 mph winds
that snapped power poles like toothpicks, uprooted trees and rammed
a 240-ton fishing boat into one of the hotels.
   Gilbert tore at the hotels first from one side, then the other.
It left them a shambles of shattered glass, soaked furniture and
sand-filled rooms, but caused little structural damage.
   The storm killed more than 300 people on its destructive tour of
the Caribbean, but only 14 of them in this state, Quintana Roo. It
caused $61 million in damage to the Cancun airport, telephones and
other services and $90 million to hotels, the government tourism
agency said.
   When Gilbert was gone, the resort began a feverish repair program
to get ready for the winter season, which means healthy profits for
hotel and shop owners and millions of dollars in foreign exchange
for Mexico's struggling economy.
   ``I'm amazed at how well they got it back together already,''
said George Weist of Lancaster, Pa., who also visited Cancun a year
ago. ``The only thing we wanted to do that we couldn't do was walk
the beach.''
   Fine white Caribbean sand has been shoveled out of hotel lobbies
and rooms, bars and kitchens, but still isn't all back where it came
from.
   The Cancun hotel strip runs for 15 miles, in the shape of a 7,
along a ribbon of sand that sits off the Yucatan Peninsula like a
bracket.
   Beaches are the same as ever along the top of the 7, perhaps even
broader, but not along the vertical stretch, where 100 feet of sand
used to slope gently toward the turquoise surf.
   Some hotels on the northern third lost their beaches entirely and
others have them only at low tide. The beach remains farther south,
but is much narrower than before.
   Residents say the beach changes with the seasons under normal
conditions, shrinking with the north winds of winter and growing
when they shift to the southeast.
   Sand is returning naturally, according to hotel managers and
scientists, and the beach already has widened, but no one knows how
long full recovery will take.
   Because of high repair costs and low income, most hotel
managements will wait until after the four-month peak season to
decide whether to speed up the beach recovery, probably with suction
dredging.
   Several major hotels will not be ready until January or later but
others have reopened in stages, renting some rooms while repairs
continue on others. New discos are opening, but a few old ones
remain closed.
   ``A lot of people aren't here,'' said Craig Debano of Anaheim,
Calif. ``It takes away from it for the single people.''
   A well-known nightclub at his hotel still is being repaired.
   Cancun brings in about 20 percent of all the foreign exchange
Mexico earns from tourism, collecting $500 million a year from 1
million visitors. The tourism agency said the 1988 total would be
about $30 million less.
   Hotels in the resort offered discounts when they reopened, but
some said they would raise prices to last year's levels for the peak
season _ more than $180 a night in some cases.
   The Cancun Chamber of Commerce said 10 percent to 15 percent of
non-tourist businesses closed because of the storm, in part because
hotel and restaurant employees had to live without tips.
   One manager, Giovanni Ronghi, said his hotel would be full for
the Christmas-New Year holiday and was heavily booked for the
February-April period.
   He expects business to be down 7 percent overall from last year,
``but that could change depending on how cold the United States
gets.''
   Hundreds of travel agents were brought in before the peak season.
   Gerda Vandyck of Syracuse, N.Y., said she would recommend Cancun
to clients who ``wanted to see the Yucatan and be on the beach.''
   If they ``just want to go to the beach and have peace and
quiet,'' she will send them somewhere else, Mrs. Vandyck said as a
smoke-belching bulldozer clanked by.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thur PMs Dec. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
