<1ST_LINE>a i BC-YE--Decision-Peace 1stLd-Writethru   12-21 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-YE--Decision-Peace, 1st Ld-Writethru,0633</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release in Year-End Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>1988 Kindles Hopes for Peace</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 9-10, ``Greek and Turkish,'' to update with U.S.
talking to PLO, Gandhi visit to China. Original moved, also as
b0980, on Dec. 12.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WALTER C. PUTNAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guns fell silent on several battlefronts in 1988,
and hope emerged that mankind stood at the dawn of a more peaceful
age. It seemed as though the world had decided it had enough of war.
   Blood was still being shed in some parts of the globe. But Iran
opted for a cease-fire in its 8-year-old war with Iraq, the Soviets
began to withdraw troops from Afghanistan, and Cuba, Angola and
South Africa chose to work towards peace in southwestern Africa.
   The year began with the ink barely dry on the first superpower
treaty to eliminate a class of nuclear weapons. Before the year was
out, many missiles were destroyed. U.N. truce troops won the Nobel
Peace Prize. President Reagan met not once, but twice, with Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who announced unilateral reductions in
military strength.
   ``Forces have already emerged in the world that in one way or
another stimulate the arrival of a period of peace,'' Gorbachev said
in a speech to the U.N. General Assembly.
   Among other developments, Olympic athletes from both East and
West met in the Summer Games for the first time in 12 years in
Seoul. Fears of North Korean sabotage of the Games proved unfounded,
and the two Koreas took steps toward reconciliation.
   The United Nations also mediated peace talks on the Western
Sahara between Morocco, which occupies most of the northwest African
territory, and the Polisario independence movement.
   Southeast Asia's non-communist nations, Japan, and the
U.N.-recognized Cambodian government-in-exile worked toward getting
Vietnamese occupying forces to withdraw from Cambodia.
   Greek and Turkish Cypriot leaders met to discuss the possibility
of reuniting the divided Mediterranean island. Rajiv Gandhi became
the first Indian prime minister in 34 years to visit China, long at
odds with India over a border dispute and other issues.
   The PLO said it recognized Israel's right to exist, and the
United States agreed to talks with Yasser Arafat's group for the
first time in hopes of peace in the Middle East. Meanwhile,
Palestinians died at the rate of almost one a day in their
anti-Israeli uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   And conflicts raged on in many other parts of the globe:
   _Burma struggled through political turmoil.
   _Central America simmered with continued fighting in El Salvador
and an uneasy truce in Nicaragua.
   _Moslem guerrillas continued their fight in Afghanistan against
the Soviet-allied government.
   _The Sikhs still struggled for an independent homeland in India,
as did the Tamils in Sri Lanka, and other rebel groups in the Sudan
and Ethiopia.
   _Five thousand died in ethnic violence in Burundi.
   _Dozens died and thousands were forced to leave their homes
because of domestic unrest in Armenia and Azerbaijan in the southern
Soviet Union.
   _And in Lebanon, the streets of Beirut remained a battleground.
The nation came closer than ever to formal partitioning into
Christian and Moslem sectors, and Israeli raiders struck repeatedly
against the south in retaliation for anti-Israel guerrilla activity.
   Still, the year wound to a close with a sense of hope.
   ``There is a new mood of understanding and common sense,'' U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said in accepting the
peace prize Dec. 10.
   ``We can, and must, achieve what we have dreamed of for so long,
that is to make the rule of law the standard rather than the
exception in world affairs.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Year-End Editions</NOTE>
