<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   12-21 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0565</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation slowed to an annual rate of 3 percent
last month and economic growth did the same in the third quarter,
the government says.
   The Labor Department report released Tuesday eased fears among
many economists and market watchers that an overheating economy was
about to trigger a wage-price spiral.
   Seasonally-adjusted consumer prices rose just 0.25 percent in
November compared with a 0.4 percent increase in October, the Labor
Department said. Before the seasonal adjustments, prices rose only
0.1 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy expanded at a moderate 2.5 percent
pace during the July-September quarter, the government reported, but
analysts said growth was rebounding and the Federal Reserve probably
would nudge interest rates higher as a result.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that growth of the gross
national product, the broadest measure of economic health, slowed
during the third quarter from 3.0 percent in the second quarter.
   The GNP, after adjusting for inflation, rose $24.2 billion to an
annual rate of $4.01 trillion in the third quarter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department's encouraging report on
inflation added a spark of life to some financial markets and eased
concerns about higher interest rates, but most analysts remained
wary about the economy's direction.
   The dollar rallied Tuesday against most major currencies in
foreign-exchange trading in the United States and abroad, while bond
prices headed sharply higher.
   But on Wall Street, stocks declined. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials closed 6.61 points lower at 2,166.07.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush, emphasizing his
opposition to tax increases, appointed Republican Paul Laxalt and
Democrat Thomas Ashley to a national commission struggling to find a
formula for reducing the federal budget deficit.
   ``I intend to hold the line on taxes,'' Bush said Tuesday.
``There are a lot of people around saying I can't do that.''
   The appointments put the National Economic Commission at its full
strength of 14 people. The panel was created last year after
October's stock market crash.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp. hopes to break new
ground in the fight against unfairly low-priced imports by asking
the government to monitor imports of televisions from 10 countries,
Zenith's chairman says.
   The comments Tuesday by Jerry Pearlman in a wide-ranging
telephone interview were the first public disclosure of a key
component in Zenith's plan for returning to consistent profitability.
   In another development related to foreign dumping, American
Telephone & Telegraph Co. said it would file a petition with the
U.S. government alleging that manufacturers in Japan, Taiwan and
South Korea are charging unfairly low prices for small-business
phone gear in the United States.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporations reported a 3.9 percent rise in
after-tax profits for the third quarter, down from an 8.9 percent
surge in the previous quarter but substantially above the
preliminary estimate last month, the government says.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that profits rose $6.4
billion to a seasonally-adjusted annual level of $169.1 billion for
the third quarter.
   That compares with the slight 0.2 percent rise reported a month
ago, but the department noted almost all of the improvement came
from profits earned by foreign subsidiaries of U.S. companies.
</TEXT>
