<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   12-21 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0580</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. said its profit fell 38 percent
in its second quarter and 10 percent for the first half of its
fiscal year due partly to the costs of its unsuccessful battle
against hostile suitor Grand Metropolitan PLC.
   Pillsbury said Tuesday its net income in the three months ended
Nov. 30 was $44.8 million, or 52 cents a share, down from $72.5
million, or 84 cents a share, in the same period a year earlier.
Sales rose to $1.75 billion from $1.69 billion.
   The food and restaurant giant agreed Sunday to accept a sweetened
$5.68 billion takeover bid from the British conglomerate, which had
made its first offer on Oct. 4.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ocean Spray Cranberries Inc. has pleaded guilty to
21 misdemeanor charges and was fined $400,000 for releasing highly
acidic waste into municipal sewers near its fruit-processing plant
in Middleboro, Mass.
   Under a plea agreement with the U.S. attorney's office in which
more than 50 charges were dropped, the cooperative also promised
Tuesday to buy the town wastewater treatment equipment worth more
than $100,000.
   Federal officials said the case was one of the first in which a
municipality damaged by pollution has been considered the victim of
a crime and granted a monetary settlement.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 drought cut deeply into U.S. and
global grain stockpiles, but the Agriculture Department says normal
weather could improve things significantly by this time next year.
   Drought in the United States and Canada lowered world crop
production by more than 6 percent, the department's Economic
Research Service said Tuesday.
   Meanwhile, world supplies of animal products will remain large
enough to dampen increases in livestock prices, the department said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As its own 100th birthday approaches, the song
``Happy Birthday to You'' is about to change owners.
   A spokesman for Warner Communications Inc. confirmed Tuesday that
the corporation's music publishing division has signed an agreement
to buy Birchtree Ltd., the Princeton, N.J. publishing company that
owns rights to the birthday song.
   The spokesman, Geoffrey Holmes, refused to disclose the price of
the deal, but the New York Times reported Warner Chappell had agreed
to pay $25 million for Birchtree.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of Americans behind in their
mortgage payments fell in the July-September quarter to the lowest
levels in a year, according to an organization of lenders.
   The Mortgage Bankers Association of America said Tuesday that
4.73 percent of the payments on the 10.8 million mortgages surveyed
in the third quarter were at least 30 days late.
   It was the lowest rate since the third quarter of 1987, when 4.71
percent of the mortgage payers were behind. The rate a year ago was
the lowest in eight years. In the second quarter, the delinquency
rate was 4.90 percent.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined broadly Tuesday. The Dow Jones average of
30 industrials fell 6.61 points to 2,166.07.
   The dollar rose, strengthened by yearend corporate demand,
speculation about higher U.S. interest rates and a sharp jump in oil
prices. Gold prices dipped in New York after mostly rising abroad.
   Bond prices advanced.
   Coffee futures prices surged; cocoa registered sharp gains;
platinum posted moderate gains; and the January contract for crude
oil futures skyrocketed $1.42 a barrel.
</TEXT>
