<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0130EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     12-21 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Rise, Sharply For January Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A squeeze on a futures trader who was caught
short sent an expiring contract for West Texas Intermediate crude
oil sharply higher, although other energy futures rose only modestly
at the same time.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, shot up $1.42 on Tuesday to settle at $17.73 a
barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. It had fallen 41 cents
the previous session.
   One major trader who was caught short had to buy January
contracts on the final day to close out a position, said Peter
Beutel, assistant director of the energy group at Elders Futures Inc.
   Traders who are short have sold borrowed contracts as a bet that
the price will fall, and they will be able to repay their debt with
contracts bought at the cheaper price.
   But in a classic short squeeze Tuesday, the trader was forced to
pay exorbitant prices to get anyone to sell, said another trader,
Jack Unger of Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   There were conflicting reports about the identity of the trader
or traders who were caught short. Any trader who is still short when
the contract expires must make delivery of actual oil to the holder
of the contract, something most oil traders are scarcely prepared to
do.
   Reflecting the unusual circumstances of the short squeeze,
contracts for delivery in later months rose by far smaller amounts.
The February contract rose 33 cents to $16.15 a barrel and the March
contract rose 32 cents to $15.75 a barrel.
   Crude oil got some support from a report that the Saudis were
cutting back their allocation of oil to Japan, forcing the Japanese
to buy oil elsewhere, Beutel said.
   There also are some long-term reasons for an increase in oil
prices, said James L. Carroll, an analyst at PaineWebber Inc.
   ``The OPEC agreement that was struck shortly before Thanksgiving
was met initially with a great amount of skepticism in the crude
trading community. But it's been accepted so far by all the cartel
members to a degree that was not expected,'' Carroll said.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange Tuesday,
January wholesale home heating oil rose 0.72 cent to 51.47 cents a
gallon.
   The January contract for unleaded gasoline settled at 45.55 cents
a gallon Tuesday, up 0.13 cent from the close Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
