<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0140EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AT&T-Dumping     12-21 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AT&T-Dumping,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Companies Dumping Phone Systems, AT&T Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Companies in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea are
taking over the U.S. market for small business phone equipment by
charging unfairly low prices for phone gear shipped here, American
Telephone & Telegraph Co. says.
   Unfair competition has allowed the foreign companies to increase
their share of the $4 billion-a-year U.S. market to 60 percent from
40 percent over three years, AT&T said Tuesday as it announced its
first-ever ``dumping'' accusation.
   ``Our investigation showed a very clear picture of not just
small-scale dumping, but massive dumping,'' J.A. Blanchard, an AT&T
executive, said in a telephone interview.
   The companies' prices in their home markets averaged more than 75
percent higher and in one case were 170 percent higher than in the
United States, AT&T said.
   The equipment at issue is for small businesses with two to 80
phone lines and consists of phones and switches. The two major types
are known as key systems and private branch exchanges, or PBXs.
   It is illegal under U.S. law for foreign companies to sell
products in the U.S. market for less than they sell them at home,
regardless of the motivation.
   ``One obvious possible explanation (for the dumping) is if you
can sell it for twice as much in the home market, then you can grow
your market share abroad,'' Blanchard said.
   AT&T accused more than a dozen manufacturers that sell products
under more than 17 brand names. Among those accused were giants such
as Japan's Toshiba Corp. and Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. Ltd.
Spokesmen in the United States for both of those companies declined
to comment, saying they did not have enough information about the
allegations.
   Blanchard said that while the foreign companies were increasing
their market share over the past three years, the share of U.S.
manufacturers fll to 35 percent from 55 percent.
   ``We decided we were simply not going to let that continue,''
Blanchard said.
   The petition will be filed Dec. 28 with the Commerce Department,
AT&T said.
   The Commerce Department has 20 days from the filing date to
decide whether AT&T's dumping claims merit investigation. If it
does, the International Trade Commission will begin a separate
investigation to determine whether the alleged dumping has harmed
the U.S. industry. It should make its preliminary determination
within 45 days.
   Final determinations and the possible imposition of dumping
duties would occur in about a year.
   In addition to Matsushita and Toshiba, the other Japanese
companies named by AT&T were Hasegawa, Iwatsu, Meisei, Nakayo,
Nitsuko and Tamura.
   Also named were South Korea's Goldstar, OPC and Samsung, and
Taiwan's Sun Moon Star.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881221-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 0142EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Honeywell Bjt   12-21 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honeywell, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honeywell To Lose About $400 Million In 1988; Picks New Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although it posted a $67.1 million profit for
the first nine months of 1988, Honeywell Inc. says it faces a
surprise loss of more than $400 million for the full year, largely
due to charges for tax expenses and streamlining costs.
   Honeywell on Tuesday also said it would cut 1,200 of its
79,000-employee worldwide workforce, as part of a plan to trim costs
and increase the defense contractor and building controls maker's
competitiveness.
   Unusual tax expenses are responsible for about $300 million of
the projected annual loss, Honeywell said Tuesday.
   ``There had been no indication earlier there would be a loss for
the year,'' said Susan Eich, a Honeywell spokeswoman.
   Honeywell posted a profit of $254 million on sales of $6.7
billion last year.
   Honeywell announced the expected 1988 loss after the stock market
closed Tuesday. In composite New York Stock Exchange trading,
Honeywell stock was down 62{ cents Tuesday to $59.62{.
   Honeywell also said Tuesday that James J. Renier, president and
chief executive officer, will replace retiring Chairman Edson W.
Spencer. Renier, 58, who joined Honeywell in 1956 as a senior
research scientist, was appointed president and chief executive in
October 1987.
   Spencer, 62, will remain on the company's board of directors.
   Mike Hamilton, an analyst for Piper Jaffray & Hopwood in
Minneapolis said he had been projecting a break-even fourth quarter
for Honeywell after the company posted its nine-month profit of
$1.58 a share. But after Tuesday's announcement he has revised his
projection to a fourth quarter loss of $480 million.
   ``It's obviously a fairly messy situation at this stage to put it
mildly,'' Hamilton said. ``It's clear from Renier's comments that
they have just taken the posture of blowing all ballast here in
1988. They're taking charges wherever they can do so.''
   Tax expenses will account for about $300 million in losses for
the fourth quarter, the company said. Other charges are related to a
restructuring of its Solid State Electronics Division, a loss of
some defense contracts and early retirement and severance costs
related to the 1,200-person workforce reduction.
   In a news release, Renier said the company had a core of
profitable businesses where earnings had been exceeded by a series
of unusual charges. However, ``Achieving our long-term financial
goals would have been unacceptably delayed without these aggressive
actions to improve operations,'' he said.
   The principal tax expense results from Honeywell's inability to
assume tax benefits this year for operational writeoffs where actual
expenses will occur in the future, the company said. For example,
Honeywell won't be able to realize a tax benefit for a
fourth-quarter restructuring of its integrated computer circuits
business.
   The restructuring, which included the November sale of its
Colorado Springs, Colo., merchant semiconductor operation, reflects
Honeywell's retreat from computer manufacturing. That strategy
includes an anticipated reduction of Honeywell's interest in
Honeywell Bull Inc., the information systems company it formed with
Japan's NEC Corp. and France's Bull group, Renier said.
   Eich said the job cuts were part of a program to reduce costs and
enhance competitiveness. About 60 percent of the reduction will be
made through early retirements and severance agreements that will
add to fourth quarter costs, she said.
   ``It's very decentralized and its being implemented now,'' Eich
said of the cuts, which will include involuntary layoffs.
   Other factors in the huge fourth-quarter loss will be the loss of
military contracts in certain space and aviation businesses that
Honeywell will sell, Eich said.
   Other factors in the huge fourth-quarter loss will be the loss of
military contracts in certain space and aviation businesses that
Honeywell will sell, Eich said.
   Honeywell said its projection of a $400 million annual loss for
the year was unaudited and could change.
</TEXT>
