<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UniversalFoods     12-21 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Universal Foods,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Universal Foods Board Rejects Sweetened Takeover Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sweetened $577.5 million takeover bid by High
Voltage Engineering Corp. failed to win support of the Universal
Foods Inc. directors, who have rejected the offer and urged
shareholders to do the same.
   A news release issued by the Milwaukee-based Universal Foods said
the board concluded Tuesday that ``it is not in the best long-term
interests of the shareholders or the company's other constituencies
to sell or dismember this growing enterprise.''
   The $35 a share offer by High Voltage expires at midnight Dec. 30.
   Universal's stock declined 37{ cents to $35.62{ a share Tuesday
on the New York Stock Exchange.
   High Voltage, based in Burlington, Mass., is jointly owned by New
York-based investors Clifford Press and Laurence Levy and S&W
Berisford PLC, a British food conglomerate.
   The group sweetened the offer last week from its initial $30.50 a
share bid that Universal rejected earlier this month. The sweetened
bid values Universal's 16.5 million outstanding common shares at
$577.5 million.
   John L. Murray, Universal chairman, said the latest offer
involved too many financial risks.
   ``The highly leveraged transaction proposed by High Voltage
Engineering risks crippling the company's expansion and causing
drastic cuts in our research expenditures and capital investment
program,'' he said.
   Murray said that High Voltage, which ``is already highly
leveraged,'' was proposing to finance the offer through a newly
created subsidiary with less than $10 million of its own funds.
   Levy said Murray was incorrect, and that his group was committing
a total of $195 million to the buyout of Universal Foods. Levy also
argued that Universal's stock ``would at best be trading in the
mid-$20 range'' if High Voltage had not made the tender offer.
   ``We believe we have created for shareholders of Universal value
of approximately $170 million,'' Levy said.
   Guy A. Osborne, president and chief executive officer of
Universal, said he expected upcoming results for the first quarter
of 1989 to confirm his company's accelerating growth rate.
   Universal is a maker of food colors and flavors, yeast products,
frozen potatoes and Italian-style cheeses.
   The company announced Monday it was acquiring Imperial Flavors
Inc. of Winter Haven, Fla., a Borden Inc. subsidiary which
manufactures and sells flavorings and other ingredients to the
dairy, ice cream, cultured products and bakery industries.
</TEXT>
