<HEAD>UAW Official Says Kenosha Could Get New Engine Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenosha is under consideration from Chrysler
Corp. as a possible site for producing the new V-10 engine the
company plans to develop over the next several years, a union
official said.
   Ed Steagall, president of United Auto Workers Local 72 at
Kenosha, said Tuesday that he was told by Ronald W. Lightcap,
manager of Chrysler's engine plant, ``Kenosha was putting in a bid
to bring new engine work to Kenosha, the V-10.''
   But Steagall said Lightcap told him there was no guarantee that
Kenosha would get the work.
   Chrysler this week is ending auto production at Kenosha,
eliminating more than 5,000 jobs, but will continue operating an
engine plant with about 1,200 workers.
   Metalworking News, a weekly trade publication, also reported this
week that Kenosha was being considered as an alternative site for
making the V-10 engines.
   The report said the likely target date for production of the
engines was 1993, and they were expected to be used initially in
light-duty trucks, vans and motor homes.
   ``We don't comment on future products or what engine work goes
into what plant,'' Chrysler spokesman Lloyd Northard said when asked
about the report.
</TEXT>
