<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Toyota,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toyota to Export U.S.-Built Cars to Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Corp., Japan's largest automaker, said
Wednesday its sales arm in the United States will begin exporting
U.S.-made Toyota passenger cars to Taiwan in January.
   A Toyota official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Toyota Motor Sales, U.S.A. will export 300 four-door Camry sedans a
month to Taiwan from Toyota Motor Manufacturing U.S.A., Toyota's
U.S. subsidiary, in Georgetown, Kentucky.
   Toyota Motort Sales also will export 100 four-door Corolla sedans
a month to Taiwan from New United Motor Manufacturing Inc., a joint
venture with General Motors Corp. of the United States, in Fremont,
California, beginning in March, the official said.
   Taiwan has banned imports of passenger cars from Japan since 1974
to reduce its trade deficit with Japan, which totaled $4.8 billion
last year.
   The official said Toyota Motor Manufacturing now produces 5,500
cars and New United Motor Manufacturing 10,000 cars a month.
