<HEAD>Crop Futures Decline On Cancelled Soy Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower today on
the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting disappointment over the
cancellation of some large export sales of U.S. soybeans and soybean
meal.
   Late Tuesday, the Agriculture Department announced the
cancellation of a sale of 200,000 metric tons of soybeans to the
Soviet Union.
   The USDA also announced cancellation of a sale of 200,000 metric
tons of soybean meal to an unknown destination, which was believed
to have been the Soviet Union.
   Analysts said such cancellations were not unheard of when dealing
with the Soviet Union, which has very limited port capacity.
   ``The bottom line is that they sometimes buy more than can
physically take and they probably have a clause that allows them to
get out of the commmitment,'' said Walter Spilka, a grain market
analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   ``More than likely, they want the stuff but can't take it now,''
he said. ``More than likely, they'll be back to take it.''
   In early trading, wheat was 1} cents to 2} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.34{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
to 1} cents lower with March at $2.78{ a bushel; oats were 2} cents
to 3{ cents lower with March at $2.24} a bushel; soybeans were }
cent to 7{ cents lower with January at $7.79 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .28 cent lower with February at
73.10 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent lower to .03 cent
higher with January at 83.85 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent
to .37 cent lower with February at 46.05 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .55 cent to .92 cent lower with February at 44.60 cents
a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
