<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1256EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-AutoOutlook Adv25   12-21 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Auto Outlook, Adv 25,0735</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Dec. 25 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Auto Industry At Peace With Labor, Enjoying Bigger Profits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automakers received some pleasant surprises in
1988 _ higher sales, fatter profits and, for the most part, labor
peace.
   One Japanese company began shipping U.S.-made cars back home,
another began building cars in the United States, and General Motors
Corp. began flexing anew its muscle as No. 1 carmaker.
   In the fall of 1987, analysts fretted about flat sales in the
1988 model year, and less than two weeks into the model year the
stock market crashed, increasing gloomy predictions.
   But the 1988 model year ended Sept. 30 with automakers posting
the third-best sales year on record. Buyers drove 15.6 million cars
and light trucks off showroom floors.
   The calendar year promised an impressive performance as well,
depending on December sales.
   Financially, it was a good year for the Big Three automakers,
with analysts predicting at yearend that GM, Ford Motor Co. and
Chrysler Corp. would combine for a record $11 billion in earnings.
   Ford posted industry-record quarterly earnings during the first
and second three-month periods of the year, taking in $1.62 billion
and $1.66 billion, respectively.
   In the third quarter, historically a period of lower earnings, GM
surprised analysts by outearning Ford for the first time in five
quarters with $859.2 million.
   Moves designed to strengthen GM's position that started as far
back as 1982 were beginning to show results, GM Chairman Roger Smith
said in a yearend interview. ``Quality has come up, our new plants
are on stream...A lot of the investments we made are paying off.''
   While GM was streamlining, Ford and some overseas carmakers
snatched some of the market that had put GM at the top.
   Securities analyst Charles Brady of Oppenheimer & Co. said Wall
Street is beginning to take GM officials' promises of economic
improvement more seriously.
   ``That's what they've been trying to indicate for the better part
of six to seven months,'' he said. ``The skepticism regarding the
turnaround was phenomenal. But you're seeing the vast majority of
the people beginning to believe.''
   In labor relations, 1988 was relatively smooth for GM and Ford,
rougher for Chrysler. The year was headlined by an early contract
agreement between Chrysler and the United Auto Workers.
   That contract ratified in May brings the UAW's contracts with
each of the Big Three to a common expiration date _ Sept. 14, 1990.
The UAW agreed to three-year contracts with GM and Ford in 1987.
   The path to the Chrysler-UAW contract was rocky.
   The company faced noisy protest demonstrations after Chairman Lee
Iacocca announced Chrysler may sell its Acustar Inc. parts
subsidiary. Chrysler later scrapped that idea.
   The company announced in April, three days after negotiations
began, that it would move production of its K-cars to Mexico from
the United States. Chrysler backed down on that temporarily.
   But in Kenosha, Wis., Chrysler remained committed to close an
aging former American Motors Corp. assembly plant Dec. 23,
eliminating 5,500 jobs.
   Other notable auto industry events during 1988 included:
   _Toyota Motor Manufacturing U.S.A. Inc. began building cars at a
new plant in Georgetown, Ky., and Diamond-Star Motors, a
collaboration between Mitsubishi Motors Corp. of Japan and Chrysler
in Illinois, started production.
   _Offers of cash rebates moved in and out, Oldsmobile offered free
gasoline and airplane tickets, and Chrysler experimented with money
back or exchange guarantees in new-car purchases in two markets.
   _In March, American Honda Motor Co. began shipping two-door
Accords from its plant in Marysville, Ohio, to Japan.
   _Iacocca gave a clear indication about his choice for a successor
in mid-November when he announced a restructuring in the company's
executive office suites. Chrysler Motors Chairman Gerald Greenwald
was named vice chairman of the parent corporation, to share the
office of chairman with Iacocca, who has three years left on his
contract.
   _In Washington, the Transportation Department in October set
fuel-economy standards at 26.5 miles per gallon for 1989 cars. GM
and Ford had said a higher corporate average fuel economy standard
could cause layoffs and production cuts.
   Chrysler said it could meet the original target of 27.5 mpg for
1989 models.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Dec. 25</NOTE>
