<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ZZZZBest-Minkow     12-21 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-ZZZZ Best-Minkow,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barry Minkow Praises Prosecutors in Holiday Wishes</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Misspellings in quoted material cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Minkow, who convinced Wall Street he was
a business genius before his ZZZZ Best rug-shampooing company turned
out to be a fraud, gave his prosecutors a Christmas card.
   ``Just a brief note to wish you both a wonderful holiday
season,'' Minkow wrote to assistant U.S. attorneys Gordon Greenberg
and James Asperger, who convinced a jury he was guilty of 57 counts
in the securities fraud case.
   ``You guys truely are the best at what you do,'' wrote Minkow,
22, who is facing a prison term of up to 403 years.
   There were numerous misspellings in the card, hand-delivered to
the attorneys last week during jury deliberations. ``I'm too cheap
to send this card,'' Minkow said in a P.S.
   ``I wouldn't have wanted anyone else up there making me look
soooo bad,'' the hand-printed message continued. ``I am really sorry
for all the trouble I've caused you and your staff. But the real
tragidy would of been if I haven't learned anything through all of
this. But I have! God bless you both and I wish you all the best in
the future.
   ``All my best wishes, Barry.''
   The stamped message on the card read: ``Remembering you is one of
the special joys of the season.''
   Minkow became familiar to millions of people through appearances
in television ads and talk shows, portraying himself as a
clean-living, hard-working super-salesman who began his company in
his parents' garage.
   He was convicted last week of 57 counts of conspiracy, securities
fraud, mail fraud and credit card fraud and is to be sentenced Feb.
21.
</TEXT>
