<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   12-21 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Rebound On Corn Exports, Bullish Sentiment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed higher
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade with corn and soybeans
posting strong gains amid a generally bullish outlook for export
sales.
   The markets had opened lower in reaction to the Agriculture
Department's announcement late Tuesday of some cancelled export
sales, including a sale of 200,000 metric tons of soybeans to the
Soviet Union.
   But the disappointment quickly faded amid news of strong export
sales of corn and ``inherent bullishness in the market,'' said
Walter Spilka, a grain-market analyst with Smith Barney, Harris
Upham & Co. in New York.
   ``I suspect traders would argue that although the Soviets have
canceled these purchases, they will make some purchases further down
the road,'' he said. ``It's inevitable that some new business will
filter back in.''
   Wheat futures prices rose shortly before the close on a report
that China was bidding for 400,000 metric tons of subsidized U.S.
wheat under the USDA's Export Enhancement Program, analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 3{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.38} a bushel; corn was 4{ cents
to 6} cents higher with March at $2.84{ a bushel; oats were 3{ cents
to 4\ cents higher with March at $2.32 a bushel; soybeans were 5
cents to 11\ cents higher with January at $7.96 a bushel.
</TEXT>
