<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1718EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SatellitesContract     12-21 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Satellites Contract,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Martin Marietta Signs Contract To Launch Two Satellites</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Marietta Commercial Titan Inc. on Wednesday
announced it has signed a contract with Hughes Aircraft Co. to
launch two communications satellites on Commercial Titan launch
vehicles.
   Terms of the contract were not announced.
   Richard E. Brackeen, president of Commercial Titan, a wholly
owned subsidiary of Martin Marietta Corp., said the Hughes contract
brings to six the number of satellites to be launched on the
Commercial Titan, according to a Martin Marietta news statement.
   Two Hughes HS 601-class communications satellites will be
launched under the contract. The Hughes HS 601 has been selected for
the Navy's next-generation ultra-high-frequency communications
satellite program. Hughes also will employ the satellites for direct
broadcast use during the early 1990s, according to the news
statement.
   The first launch of a Commercial Titan is scheduled for the
summer of 1989 from Cape Canaveral, Fla., when communications
satellites for the Japan Communication Satellite Co. and the British
Ministry of Defense will be taken into space.
</TEXT>
