<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TrumpLand     12-21 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trump Land,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump To Keep Television City Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The largest undeveloped plot of land in the city,
a 76-acre, riverfront rail yard on Manhattan's West Side, will
remain the private domain of Donald Trump, the developer announced
Wednesday.
   He intends to proceed with plans to build the world's tallest
building on the site as part of his ``Trump City'' project, a
mixed-use development that would include apartments, retail and
office space.
   A Trump spokesman, noting that teams of bidders from four
continents were interested in the parcel, said all discussions with
potential buyers have been terminated.
   ``Now that all talk of sale is behind us, we hope to be certified
to begin the ULURP (Uniform Land Use Review Procedure) and zoning
processes in the next several months,'' Trump said in a prepared
statement.
   Trump bought the 15-block site, then called Lincoln West, four
years ago at the fire sale price of $95 million from Argentine
businessman Francisco Macri and Abraham Hirschfeld, who ran into
financial problems trying to develop the property.
   When asked at a news conference two months ago about reports that
he had been offered more than $500 million for the site, Trump
replied: ``I don't believe anyone has enough money to pay me for
this piece of land.''
   He used a different tone in his statement Wednesday, saying:
``Building a great city for New York and New Yorkers is more
important to me than selling this unique and wonderful site for a
very substantial, short-term profit.''
   The mammoth project would include a 150-story apartment tower,
eight 60-story residential towers, three smaller towers, shopping
mall, marina and 20 acres of parks between 59th and 72nd Streets.
   Trump's plans have met with almost universal criticism from
environmentalists, preservationists and community groups.
</TEXT>
