<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1936EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Insurance     12-21 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Insurance,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unveils Plan To Open Up Life Insurance Market</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to restore cycle designator.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community's
executive body disclosed a plan Wednesday to open up the life
insurance market in the 12-nation trade bloc.
   The plan by the EEC Commission would allow individuals to shop
around the bloc for life insurance policies and would permit
insurance companies to offer their services throughout the trade
bloc without having to set up a branch or subsidiary.
   It is part of the EEC's drive to create a single market of trade,
goods and investment by the end of 1992.
   The plan contains a controversial reciprocity clause which would
allow foreign insurers to offer their services in all EEC nations,
to the extent that their home countries give EEC insurers reciprocal
market access.
   The clause has been used already in draft EEC legislation
liberalizing banking and investment services.
   Under the terms of the plan, which needs approval by the 12
member states, insurers from one country selling services in another
would be bound by the rules governing domestic sales.
</TEXT>
