<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     12-21 0863</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodities Rdp,0894</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platinum Futures Rise Again; Further Gains Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures prices rose for a second straight day Wednesday
amid growing confidence that Ford Motor Co.'s new catalytic
converter will not substantially reduce demand for platinum for at
least the next several years.
   On other markets, coffee futures gained for the sixth consecutive
session; grains and soybeans were higher; cattle futures advanced
while pork futures were mixed; energy futures were mixed; and
stock-index futures retreated.
   Platinum settled $6.60 to $8.10 higher on the New York Mercantile
Exchange with the spot December contract at $542.40 a troy ounce and
the more active contract for delivery in January at $538.40 a troy
ounce.
   Spot platinum plunged from more than $600 to $510 an ounce last
Thursday after Ford announced it had developed an automobile
catalytic converter that did not use platinum. The use of platinum
as a catalyst in the pollution-control devices accounts for about
one-third of platinum consumption worldwide.
   Analysts linked Wednesday's rally to buying by bargain hunters
whose confidence was bolstered by statements from the London-based
platinum refiner Johnson Matthey PLC.
   Johnson Matthey, which helped Ford develop the new converter,
stood by its early-November projection of platinum supply shortfalls
in 1988 and ``over the next few years.''
   The world's largest platinum refiner cited the global tightening
of exhaust emission standards and the widespread use outside the
United States of leaded gasoline. Platinum is better than other
catalyst metals at cleaning up the exhaust produced by leaded
gasoline, Johnson Matthey said in a statement.
   Analysts expressed skepticism about the degree to which Ford has
developed its new technology for practical use.
   ``The impression I'm getting ... is that there are still a lot of
unanswered questions and it doesn't look like the technology is
going to be applied on a widespread basis anytime soon,'' said
Bernard Savaiko, metals analyst with PaineWebber Inc. in New York.
   He said January platinum probably could climb another $15 to $20
before encountering significant resistance.
   Peter Cardillo, commodities trading adviser with Josephthal & Co.
in New York, predicted platinum would rally even further, to $565 or
$570 an ounce.
   ``The market was obviously grossly oversold on the announcement
by Ford,'' he said. ``The supply situation has not changed and will
not change.''
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled $1.30 higher
across the board with February at $418.80 a troy ounce; silver was
1.8 cents to 2.3 cents higher with March at $6.23 a troy ounce.
   Coffee futures prices rose to new two-year highs on New York's
Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange but the gains were slight due to
heavy profit-taking earlier in the session.
   The bullish impact of poor weather in South America and Central
America has been exacerbated by a dockworkers' strike since Dec. 13
in Brazil, the world's largest coffee producer.
   ``We saw profit-taking today but the trend from here on out is
probably up,'' said Kim Badenhop, an analyst in New York with
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   Coffee settled .07 cent to 5.06 cents higher with March at
$1.5594 a pound.
   Corn and soybean futures posted strong gains on the Chicago Board
of Trade amid a generally bullish outlook for export sales.
   After the close, the U.S. Department of Agriculture announced it
had targeted Morocco for sales of 1 million metric tons of U.S.
wheat at subsidized prices, a bullish development.
   But the USDA also said the Soviet Union had canceled a sale of
102,500 metric tons of U.S. soybean meal, a bearish development.
   Wheat settled } cent lower to 3\ cents higher with March at
$4.38} a bushel; corn was 4} cents to 6} cents higher with March at
$2.84} a bushel; oats were 4 cents to 4} cents higher with March at
$2.32{ a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents to 11 cents higher with
January at $7.95{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in a
technically inspired rally while pork futures finished mixed.
   After the close, the USDA released its monthly cold-storage
report pegging supplies of frozen pork bellies on Nov. 30 at a
record-high 95.75 million pounds. Pork belly futures were expected
to open sharply lower Thursday in reaction to the report.
   Live cattle settled .25 cent to .50 cent higher with February at
73.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .45 cent higher
with January at 84.17 cents a pound; live hogs were .35 cent lower
to .35 cent higher with February at 46.62 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .03 cent to .35 cent lower with February at 45.17 cents
a pound.
   In energy futures trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 2 cents to 15 cents higher
with February at $16.30 a barrel; heating oil was .06 cent to .45
cent higher with January at 51.92 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .10 cent lower to .15 cent higher with January at 45.70 cents a
gallon.
   Stock-index futures dipped on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the contract for March delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
settled .85 point lower at 280.45. Each point is worth $500.
</TEXT>
