<1ST_LINE>u f DieselEngineProducerSuspendsTradingAfterHea</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Diesel Engine Producer Suspends Trading After Heavy Activity</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cummins Engine Co. Inc. suspended trading
in its stock nearly an hour early Wednesday amid heavy speculation
about a possible buyout attempt sent its stock surging higher.
   Cummins was up $6 to $57.37{ a share on the New York Stock
Exchange in unusually heavy trading of more than 1.15 million
shares. The jump came on top of a $2.25 a share gain during
Tuesday's session.
   In a generally light market Wednesday, nearly 10 percent of
Cummins outstanding shares were traded.
   Cummins said it had been notified by a representative of
Rothschild Inc. of New York that a client of that firm has acquired
more than 5 percent of the company's stock and that a formal
announcement of the purchase will be made late next week.
   The identity of the shareholder was not disclosed, the company
said. Cummins also said it was told the shares had been acquired for
investment only and that it could not account for the unusually
heavy trading volume and rise in its stock price.
   There have been unconfirmed market rumors that West Germany's
Daimler-Benz AG might be interested in acquiring Cummins, which is
based in Columbus.
   After trading was halted 57 minutes early, the diesel engine
maker also announced it would take a fourth-quarter charge against
earnings of about $50 million. The charge will relate mainly to
discontinuation and write-down of assets of unprofitable operations.
   In its fourth quarter last year, Cummins posted a loss of $4.4
million on sales of $754.3 million.
</TEXT>
