<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Continental-TokyoRoute     12-21 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Continental-Tokyo Route,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Orders DOT to Award Route to Continental</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has ordered the
Transportation Department to award the Seattle-Tokyo air route to
Continental Airlines in the latest round of a 2-year-old battle
among three of the nation's largest airlines over the lucrative
route.
   A little more than a month ago, the department decided to ignore
an earlier appeals court decision and award the route to United
Airlines.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals, in a brief decision late Tuesday,
again ruled that the department had violated various deadlines in
awarding the route and overstepped its authority in giving the route
to United.
   ``We cannot countenance the creative use of procedural mechanisms
to evade either our order or the FAA's (Federal Aviation
Administration) review deadlines,'' the court said, adding that the
department had engaged in a ``thinly disguised attempt to circumvent
the decision of this court.''
   The court had found in September that Continental should receive
the route, but the department had decided to once again review the
case.
   At various times over the past two years, administrative law
judges and top department officials have awarded the route to
Continental, United and American Airlines.
   The route generates more than $100 million in revenue annually.
   Hal Paris, a DOT spokesman, said the department would have no
immediate comment on the latest court order.
   ``We haven't seen the decision yet and will have to review it
before commenting,'' said Paris.
   Art Kent, a Continental spokesman in Houston, said his airline
was ``delighted'' with the ruling.
   ``As far as we are concerned, the Court of Appeals ruling brings
this matter to a close and we will begin our planning to institute
our service on the route sometime next year,'' said Kent.
   Kent said it was too soon to say when Continental may begin
actual flights between Seattle and Tokyo.
   The airline has said previously it would offer one-way
Seattle-Tokyo fares as low as $299.
   A United spokesman in Chicago said the court's decision was based
on ``what amounts to a legal technicality'' and that an appeal was
possible.
   ``United will act swiftly to review all options available and
will take prompt action to protect the interests of our customers,
the communities we serve, the traveling public and our own
employees,'' said Rob Doughty.
   United has been flying the route since 1986 when it purchased Pan
American World Airways' Pacific division, but DOT approved the
purchase only on the condition that the route be dealt with in a
separate proceeding.
   Both Northwest Airlines and Japan Air Lines also fly non-stop
between Seattle and Tokyo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881221-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 2019EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Cuomo-PoisonPill     12-21 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Cuomo-Poison Pill,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Signs ``Poison Pill'' Legislation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo on Wednesday signed into law
a bill allowing New York corporations to use ``poison pill''
takeover defenses to fight hostile takeover bids.
   The new law is designed to undo, until April 1, 1989, the state
Supreme Court's ruling earlier this year that a poison pill Irving
Bank Corp. tried to use to thwart a hostile takeover by Bank of New
York Co. was illegal.
   The court decided New York state law prohibits the inequitable
treatment of shareholders, and ruled the Irving pill created such a
condition. The decision cleared the way for Bank of New York's
acquisition.
   A typical poison pill gives existing shareholders the right to
buy additional stock in a company once an outside concern acquires a
certain amount of the company's shares. That increases the number of
shares a hostile buyer must to acquire to take over the company,
making a hostile bid prohibitively expensive.
   A special task force is studying the use of such defensive
measures and will report to the state Legislature in early spring.
At that point, the Legislature and Cuomo either can make the new law
permanent or let it expire.
   Both houses of the Legislature approved the bill unanimously last
week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
