<1ST_LINE>r f BC-HeathCandySale     12-21 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Heath Candy Sale,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Finnish-Owned Company Buying Heath Bar Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROBINSON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 74-year-old maker of Heath
chocolate-toffee bars is being sold to a Finnish-owned candy company
that markets Milk Duds and Clark bars, a spokesman announced
Wednesday.
   Leaf Inc., which also markets Whoppers and other candy and
chewing gum products, will purchase L.S. Heath & Sons Candy Co. in
January, Leaf announced. Terms of the sale were not disclosed.
   Joel Feldstein of the N.W. Ayer public relations company in
Chicago said Leaf bought 49 percent of Robinson-based Heath's stock
a year ago and would complete the purchase next month. Leaf is based
in Bannockburn, Ill., in suburban Chicago.
   Heath, a family-operated company, produced the first Heath bar in
1914, although the candy did not become a national product until
1938, said Feldstein. Today, Heath is one of the 25 biggest-selling
candy bars in the United States, he said.
   James A. Hanlon, president of Leaf's North American operations,
said the purchase of Heath reflected Leaf's strategy of acquiring
and building strong, well-known candy and gum brands, according to
Feldstein.
   He said the Heath plant employs about 350 people. It also makes
Heath ice cream bars, the Bit O' Brickle candybar and baking toffee.
   Leaf is owned by Huhtamaki of Helsinki, Finland. It has 3,000
employees in 12 plants in North America as well as 1,500 in
factories in Europe and China, said Feldstein.
</TEXT>
