<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 2028EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Fruehauf     12-21 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fruehauf,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fruehauf Plans Restructuring After Inconclusive Sales Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fruehauf Corp. said Wednesday it would propose a
restructuring after talks on the sale of all or part of the
truck-trailer and auto parts manufacturer proved inconclusive.
   Fruehauf will file documents with the Securities and Exchange
Commission within the next two weeks detailing a recapitalization
proposal that would defer some debt and increase cash available for
operations, spokesman David A. Hladik said.
   Fruehauf has battled large debts, high interest payments and
operating losses since its managers dodged a hostile takeover
attempt by taking control of the company in a leveraged buyout in
December 1986.
   The firm employs 15,800 people and manufactures truck trailers,
auto parts and maritime refinishing products. Its Kelsey Hayes
subsidiary is a leading supplier of antilock braking systems.
   ``The goal is to make it a stronger company at this point,''
Hladik said. ``We're still in debt and we're still pursuing trying
to sell off the Kelsey Hayes operation.''
   In October, Toronto-based Varity Corp. ended talks to buy
Fruehauf, saying only that the halt followed a review of Fruehauf's
records and assets.
   Fruehauf said in a news release Wednesday it would continue to
explore any alternatives presented to it, but that there was no
assurance any would be presented.
   The company said it has $200 million worth of 13.5 percent senior
subordinated notes due in 1996 and $310 million in 13.75 percent
senior subordinated debentures due in 2001.
   It proposes to exchange for those a package of securities
including 15.5 percent discount debentures due in 2001, 14.5 percent
priority senior subordinated debentures due in 2001, and its Class B
common stock.
   The 1986 buyout, arranged to dodge a takeover bid by New York
investor Asher Edelman, resulted in more than $1 billion in new debt.
   To help cut the debt, Fruehauf since has sold assets such as its
U.S. and European trailer rental operations, a finance subsidiary
and aerospace and other operations. In 1987, it reduced overall debt
from $1.4 billion to $870 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881221-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 1949EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Drexel-Company     12-21 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drexel-Company,0746</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drexel Once Seen `Like A God'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drexel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Drexel is like a god,'' an awed competitor said
in 1986.
   At the height of its power, Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. bestrode
the financial world like a colossus, using its money-raising power
to finance everything from nursery school chains to corporate
takeovers.
   On Wednesday, the colossus dropped to its knees, legally if not
financially. Drexel agreed to plead guilty to six federal felony
counts and pay a record $650 million fine to settle the biggest Wall
Street securities fraud case in history.
   The deal requires approval of the Securities and Exchange
Commission and senior Justice Department officials.
   Drexel's power came from its exploitation of an area of finance
that other investment bankers had ignored, either because of lack of
imagination or lack of appetite for risk.
   Drexel helped clients raise large amounts of money quickly by
issuing bonds that were riskier than investment-grade securities and
hence paid higher yields.
   The securities quickly became known as junk bonds, to the dismay
of Drexel and Michael Milken, the brilliant strategist who helped
pioneer them.
   In spite of its upstart image, Drexel was not a newcomer to Wall
Street. It traces its roots to the founding of Burnham & Co. in
1935. Drexel Firestone, which Burnham acquired in 1973, goes back to
the 1830s and once counted J.P. Morgan among its partners.
   Drexel was a second-tier investment bank, though, until the
mid-1970s, when it came up with the concept of selling junk bonds as
original issues.
   Until then, the only junk bonds were securities that had
originally been issued with a higher rating but whose issuers had
fallen on hard times.
   Drexel worked both sides of the deal, lining up investors who
were attracted by the bonds' attractive yields and grateful issuers
who had never before been able to raise money in the bond market.
   Frederick H. Joseph, now Drexel's chief executive, was then head
of corporate finance, leading underwriting efforts.
   Milken led Drexel's junk-bond trading operation and moved it to
Beverly Hills, Calif., from New York in 1977.
   Drexel's biggest break came in the early 1980s, when it hit on
the idea of using junk bonds to finance corporate takeovers. That
idea vaulted it to the front ranks of investment banks and
revolutionized the mergers and acquisitions business.
   Corporate raiders such as Carl Icahn, Sir James Goldsmith, Saul
Steinberg and T. Boone Pickens Jr. established close relations with
Drexel, as did stock speculators such as Ivan Boesky.
   Among the companies taken over with the help of junk bonds
floated by Drexel were TWA Inc. and Crown Zellerbach Corp. Drexel is
also playing a major role in financing Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &
Co.'s $24.5 billion buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc.
   ``Drexel is like a god in that end of the business and a god can
to anything it wants. ... They are awesome. You hate to do business
against them,'' Michael Boylan, the president of Macfadden Holdings,
told Barron's magazine in 1986.
   Drexel liked the quote so much that one of its investment bankers
framed it, Connie Bruck recounts in a book published this year,
``The Predators' Ball.''
   Drexel earned enormous fees for underwriting and trading junk
bonds and for its takeover advice.
   Drexel's capital as of Dec. 31, 1987, totaled nearly $2.2
billion, up from $1.8 billion the previous year and up more than
tenfold from 1981. That made the privately held company the fifth
largest firm on Wall Street.
   Although Drexel still is the dominant player in junk bonds, the
market's rapid growth has drawn competition from other investment
banks.
   Drexel's influence in the takeover game began to diminish
somewhat amid the insider-trading scandal on Wall Street, which
erupted with the arrest of a Drexel investment banker, Dennis R.
Levine, and then led to a government investigation of Drexel's
tactics.
   Still, Drexel has denied suggestions that the probe severely
impaired the firm, claiming its junk bond business and its other
investment banking operations remained strong.
   As recently as Wednesday, before Drexel's agreement to plead
guilty, Southland Corp., the parent company of 7-Eleven convenience
stores, announced it had switched its investment banking business to
Drexel, dumping the prestigious investment banking firms of Goldman,
Sachs & Co. and Salomon Brothers Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881221-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-88 2115EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Brazil-Petrobras     12-21 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Brazil-Petrobras,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Accepts Resignation of State Oil Company Head</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Brazil's state-run oil
monopoly Petrobras resigned Wednesday, the day after the resignation
of the Mines and Energy minister.
   Armando Guedes Coelho, who had headed Petrobras since June, said
in a letter to President Jose Sarney that his resignation was
unrelated to an internal financial scandal rocking the oil concern.
   Guedes' resignation from the presidency of the Petrobras oil
company had been expected since late last week.
   No substitute has yet been named to replace Guedes, who was
personally chosen to head the oil monopoly by Mines and Energy
minister Aureliano Chaves, the presidential palace said. Chaves
resigned Tuesday amid press reports speculating that he hoped to
become a full-time presidential candidate for the 1989 elections.
   ``I never expected to continue in my post through the end of
Sarney's mandate,'' Guedes told the Gazeta Mercantil newspaper
earlier this week. ``I was chosen by Chaves and I will leave with
him. It is unfortunate the two events must coincide''
   Petrobras has been rocked by financial scandal in which two
directors last week were removed from their jobs after allegedly
receiving kickbacks from banks in return for company accounts in
those financial institutions.
   Federal police were to decide later this week whether to open a
police enquiry based upon a Petrobras report that discovered
``evidences'' and ``indications'' of wrongdoing by the Petrobras
officials.
</TEXT>
